<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PieFight     08-09 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pie Fight,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owners of Restaurant Fight for Slice of Pie Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1 of Aug. 8.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pies lining the two shelves behind
the counter at the Club Cafe have always been in demand. Now,
they're in court.
   When Robert McNanna bought 51 percent of the cafe in May, he
thought he was buying the restaurant's award-winning recipes, too.
   But then the baker _ Mary Allen, a former part-owner who had the
recipes in her head _ quit and McNanna sued to get the recipes back.
   ``They're not written down someplace,'' said Mrs. Allen's
attorney, Steven Oliver. ``The recipes are something my client has
developed over many years.''
   Attorneys still are taking depositions and will request a final
hearing in a month or so in chancery court to determine ownership
of the recipes, Oliver said.
   In the meantime, the 45-year-old Club Cafe still offers, for $1
a slice, 14 varieties of pies: peanut butter, chocolate, coconut,
banana, lemon, pineapple, egg custard, pecan, apple, Dutch apple,
cherry, blueberry, banana split and strawberry. And four
cheesecakes.
   McNanna says the pies these days are every bit as good as Mrs.
Allen's, and his baker, Ricky West, a 14-year veteran at the
restaurant, agrees.
   ``The pies, we have it down to an art,'' McNanna said. ``Just
right after she quit, we had it down pretty close.''
   The customers? ``They can't tell the difference,'' West said.
   But some say they can.
   ``My opinion is that the crust isn't as good,'' said Larry
Williams, an administrative assistant for a judge who's been a
regular at the cafe for about five years.
   ``If you've had the way the pies used to be, you know what's
genuine and what's imitation,'' Williams said. ``We true Hot
Springs natives could brag that we had the best pies in Arkansas.''
   Businessman Barry Horner has been indulging in Club Cafe pies
since he was a teen-ager 30 years ago, when he was known as the
``Dutch Apple Kid.''
   Horner said he couldn't quite put his finger on the difference.
   ``It seems like it's not quite up to what it used to be,'' he
said. ``But they're still good pies.''
   Tammy Lawrence, 19, who used to help out at the restaurant when
her mother worked there, said she can't taste any difference and
she's sampled everything on the pie menu.
   ``They taste the same to me. The meringue has a different
texture, but the fillings are the same,'' she said.
   West said he cranks out 50 to 70 pies a day, a job he calls more
stressful than his old duty of cooking the main meals. The
chocolate pie, one of several crowned with 3 inches of meringue, is
his customers' favorite, with coconut next, he said.
   Under a temporary restraining order issued in May, Mrs. Allen
has been barred from the Club Cafe premises and is working as a
waitress at a local Oriental restaurant. Oliver said there are no
orders preventing her from baking elsewhere.
   Mrs. Allen filed a counterclaim in June asking that the sale of
the 51 percent share to McNanna be rescinded because of a dispute
over payment on a $40,000 banknote for her mother and aunt, who
each owned a 20 percent share in the cafe. Mrs. Allen had owned the
remaining 11 percent sold to McNanna.
   Mrs. Allen's husband, Frank, still owns 29 percent of the
restaurant and West owns the remaining 20 percent.
   Monty Montgomery, owner of Monty's Pawn Shop, said he's gone
into the cafe just about every day since 1954 and has seen a lot of
changes, though the same faded red-and-white ``Club Cafe'' sign
still hangs over the door.
   ``Five to six years ago, you could come here for lunch and
there'd be a line out the door,'' Montgomery said. But until the
last couple of months, that wasn't the case anymore, he said.
   ``There are lots of new faces,'' Montgomery said. ``More
tourists seem to be coming in here.''
   ``It's kind of funny, getting all the publicity,'' West said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
