<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0259EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StatisticiansConvention     08-09 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Statisticians Convention,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lies, Damned Lies and T-Shirts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Nirmal in 15th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the quirkier statistics presented at a
convention of statisticians here indicates that men should get
married, have children and get divorced if they want to be promoted
on a university faculty.
   Another statistic concerned the sale of T-shirts, but it was
less precise.
   Among more than 1,000 scholarly papers being presented at the
joint meetings of the American Statistical Association, the
Biometrical Society and the Institution of Mathematical
Statisticians was one by Lynne Billard of the University of
Georgia, who studied promotion rates on college faculties.
   Here's what she found about the path of advancement from
assistant to associate professor:
   _Among those who were married but childless, 51 percent of the
men and 41 percent of the women were promoted.
   _Among those who had spouses and children, 66 percent of the men
and 51 percent of the women were promoted.
   _Among those who were single, divorced or widowed and childless,
53 percent of the men and 37 percent of the women were promoted.
   _Among those who were unmarried and had children, 80 percent of
the men and 33 percent of the women were promoted.
   Ms. Billard, in a paper reflecting the jargon of her industry
(``the standardized regression coefficients in the prediction
equations for men and women''), drew no conclusions although the
moral was clear:
   For male assistant professors, the way to get ahead is to get
married, have children and get divorced. For women, that path leads
to stagnation.
   As for T-shirts, vendor Mary Cuzzucoli said statisticians seemed
to snap them up.
   A couple of hundred arrived at her table at 7:40 a.m. Tuesday
and by 9 a.m. they were all sold, she said. They bore this legend:
``I'm Statistically Significant.''
   Bumper stickers using a play on the statistical term ``moment,''
moved more slowly. ``Statisticians May Be Dull ... But We Have Our
Moments.''
   The annual August meeting filled two Washington hotels and
brought together 4,215 statisticians to observe the 150th year of
the ASA, which was founded in Boston and whose membership has
included Florence Nightingale, Alexander Graham Bell, Andrew
Carnegie and Martin Van Buren.
   The meeting's youngest presenter of a paper was 16-year-old
Nirmal D.C. Pugh, a junior at the Mahrishi School in Fairfield,
Iowa. His topic was ``Multivariate vs. Univariate Time Series
Forecasts of Weather Variables.''
   He's an old hand at delivering papers, having previously done so
before the International Neuroscience Conference.
   Outgoing ASA President Janet Norwood, who heads the government's
Bureau of Labor Statistics, noted in a speech that her bureau used
to draw moral conclusions from the numbers it gathered.
   For example, she said, in 1888, studying the conditions of women
workers, the bureau found that those living in rooming houses had
to receive guests in their rooms because there was no other place.
   It concluded: ``Such a condition tends either in the direction
of crushing out social intercourse, especially between the sexes,
or of carrying it beyond the limit of prudence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North-Drugs     08-09 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Drugs,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oliver North Begins Community Service in Anti-Drug Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North is
beginning his service as a draftee in the war against narcotics by
helping reformed drug dealers and other underworld figures to repay
their crimes.
   The national security aide who directed some of the Reagan
administration's boldest covert ventures abroad now will be
plotting forays much nearer the White House as five men calling
themselves the ``New Pied Pipers'' attempt to clean up their old
neighborhoods in the capital.
   North will ``most definitely'' be given a tour of the worst drug
neighborhoods, but he won't be active on the streets, program
coordinator Donald Lewis said Tuesday. ``He's not a street-wise
individual _ we know that. His element is administration.''
   North, conscripted into the drug battle by the judge who
sentenced him in the Iran-Contra trial, began his orientation
Monday as a management adviser to Save Our Youth, Inc., a private
umbrella group for several anti-drug projects. He will focus, to
start with, on the ``Pipers'' initiative.
   Under an arrangement with the court, North will work in the
program about 16 hours a week for 75 weeks. Early last month, U.S.
District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell sentenced North to two years'
probation, a $150,000 fine and 1,200 hours of community service for
his conviction on three felony counts in the Iran-Contra case.
   North is appealing his conviction, but told the court he was
eager to begin the community work.
   North, in a two-hour get-acquainted meeting with program
organizers, was ``very excited about his involvement,'' coordinator
Donald Lewis said Tuesday. ``He wanted to get to work right away.''
   North initially was scheduled to return to the program's offices
at the National City Christian Church on Tuesday afternoon, but
Lewis said the second session was postponed to avoid the glare of
media attention.
   Lewis said Gesell assigned North to the Save Our Youth program
after the judge learned of the ``Pipers'' effort. The five men, all
well-known in the drug community, will try to dissuade youngsters
from using drugs and also will seek out dealers in efforts to give
them legal employment, Lewis said.
   Ronald ``Roach'' Henry, a member of the Pipers who met with
North on Monday, said he has no qualms about working with the
former White House aide. ``He's interesting ... and I think he was
interested in us,'' said Henry. ``I think he will use his mind to
help us develop solutions.''
   John Staggers, chairman of Save Our Youth, said North
``represents one of the best minds in the nation when it comes to
strategizing on how to attack problems.''
   As a deputy on Reagan's National Security Council staff, North
not only was a key figure in the secret sale of arms to Iran _ and
diversion of profits to the Nicaraguan rebels _ but played a major
role in planning the invasion of Grenada, the retaliatory bombing
of Libya and the interception of an Egyptian airliner carrying the
hijackers of the Achille Lauro cruise ship.
   Staggers and Lewis acknowledged that North's political image is
a far cry from that favored by Washington's black community. But
``we're creating a marriage of two extremes,'' said Lewis.
   ``The focus is not on our differences. The focus is on changing
what is happening on our streets and to our young people. The young
black man is self-destructive; he's becoming an endangered
species,'' Lewis said.
   Under terms dictated by Gesell, North cannot act as a
fundraiser, cannot counsel young people, and cannot give speeches
or act as a spokesman for the group.
   Thus, North will ``serve as a advisor in the management and
administration of SOY's activities,'' with his initial focus on the
Pipers, Lewis said. ``He will stay in his element, and we'll stay
in ours.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WrightInvestigation     08-09 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Investigation,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups Say Staff Wanted Books Purchased in Lieu of Speaking Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury wants to examine
documents from at least three groups that bought hundreds of copies
of a book by former House Speaker Jim Wright instead of paying him
a speaking fee, the groups say.
   The Justice Department refused Tuesday to discuss the grand jury
probe. But lawyers for Southwest Texas State University and the
National Realtors Association confirmed they received subpoenas
requesting documents related to the book.
   A spokesman for Ocean Spray, a cranberry and citrus growers
cooperative in Massachusetts, said the grand jury also was seeking
documents from his group. Company spokesman John Lawlor wouldn't
discuss details of the subpoena, but he did say the group bought
$2,000 worth of Wright's book for Wright's use.
   Wright resigned this summer after the House ethics committee
accused him of trying to evade House limits on outside income
through bulk sales of ``Reflections of a Public Man.'' He earned
royalties of 55 percent on the book's sales.
   The House limits members' earnings from speaking engagements to
30 percent of the congressional salary, but royalties are exempt.
   Wright spokesman Larry Shannon said the investigation appeared
to be ``very routine.''
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said the agency's
inquiry is continuing.
   ``I can't comment on any aspect of the investigation, except I
will confirm that it is ongoing,'' he said.
   Lawlor said Wright spoke to Ocean Spray growers and management
employees in November 1985. He said Wright's staff suggested that
instead of giving the House speaker an honorarium, the cooperative
could use the money to buy the books.
   ``As far as we were concerned, it was an honorarium in the form
of a book purchase in place of a cash honorarium,'' Lawlor said.
``How he was to use them (the books) was for him to determine.''
   Bill Fly, a lawyer for Southwest Texas State University, said
the school received a subpoena for documents relating to Wright's
1984 speech there and the subsequent purchase of $3,000 worth of
books.
   Fly said the university had agreed to pay Wright $3,000.
However, a Wright aide called after the speech to say the speaker
had reached his limit on outside income and asked if he could use
the money to buy copies of his book for the university, Fly said.
   ``We received about 504 copies of that book,'' Fly said.
   Laurene Janik, general counsel for the Realtors organization,
said Wright spoke to the group in April 1985. A $2,000 check was
issued and voided, and the money was to be used to buy Wright's
book, she said.
   However, the Realtors have no record of receiving copies of the
book, Ms. Janik said.
</TEXT>
