<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Politics     08-09 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Politics,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Hitting the Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, never one to sit still for
long, is traveling to his vacation home in Maine next week by way
of Miami. ``It's a fairly common route,'' jokes spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Bush's 2,000 miles of backtracking en route to Kennebunkport is
a political detour that Fitzwater says will be just one of many
upcoming campaign appearances by the president.
   In the Florida instance, it's all in the family.
   The president will campaign for Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, the
Republican nominee for the seat left vacant with the death in May
of Democratic Rep. Claude Pepper. Bush's son, Jeb, a 36-year-old
Miami real estate executive who has long been active in GOP
politics, is the candidate's campaign manager.
   The president's appearance comes in advance of an Aug. 29
special election.
   Actually, there has been considerable political maneuvering
lately in Bush's family _ both his official one and his personal
one. But most of the movement entails declarations of
non-candidacies.
   Jeb Bush, for instance, is sending out signals that he's not
interested in running for elective office after a stint as
Florida's secretary of commerce _ preferring instead to spend time
developing his business.
   And Bush's oldest son, George W. Bush, 43, an oilman and part
owner of the Texas Rangers baseball team, announced he was more
interested in the American League pennant race than running for
Texas governor in 1990.
   He had been widely viewed as a likely contender before last
week's announcement.
   About the same time, Andrew H. Card Jr., deputy to White House
Chief of Staff John Sununu, announced he is abandoning the notion
of a gubernatorial bid in his home state of Massachusetts and will
devote his time to his White House post.
   Sununu earlier took himself out of the 1990 New Hampshire race
for the seat being vacated by the retiring Sen. Gordon Humphrey,
R-N.H. He said he hopes to serve Bush for at least four years,
preferably eight.
   But speculation continues to swirl around persistent rumors that
Sununu's wife, Nancy, may challenge Rep. Charles G. Douglas,
R-N.H., next year. The Sununus and Douglas have been on less than
friendly terms recently.
   Meanwhile, presidential aide Steve Studdert, who has served
three Republican presidents, announced recently that he was
resigning _ to return home to Utah, spend more time with his family
and serve as a political consultant.
   And what about reports that he may run for governor of Utah?
``No plans at this time to run,'' Studdert says. However, he
doesn't hesitate to note that ``there are major economic structural
challenges that face Utah'' and to outline how he would approach
them.
   Bush, meanwhile, appears ready for his vacation, which starts a
week from today and will last until Sept. 5.
   On Monday night, Bush was preparing to speak via telephone
hookup to a town meeting in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and was chatting
with the local host, Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., about their travel
plans.
   The preliminary conversation was piped into the White House
press briefing room, and Bush told Shaw that first lady Barbara
Bush was already in Kennebunkport. ``We're going up next week,''
the president said enthusiastically.
   A case of the pre-vacation sillies may be setting at the White
House.
   Bush the other day jokingly told a group of photographers in the
Oval Office: ``Don't anybody take the ashtrays.''
   And on Tuesday, he rushed into the White House press room
brandishing a gag photo depicting him as an invisible leader _ and
jokingly threatened to fire the top aides who sent it to him as a
practical joke.
   The photo showed aides seated around Bush's desk at the Oval
Office, with his seat empty. It read: ``To President Skippy. From
the gang that sees through you.''
   It was a reference to the comic strip ``Doonesbury,'' and
creator G.B. Trudeau's frequent depiction of Bush as invisible and
references to an imaginary ``evil twin'' whom Trudeau named Skippy.
   ``This is a vicious assault on my presidency,'' Bush said.
   Bush has made no secret that he's no fan of Trudeau, who was
excluded from the invitation list when Bush invited cartoonists to
lunch last spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
