<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     08-09 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Industry Stockpiling Ammunition for Quota Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's sugar industry is stockpiling
statistics to throw into the fight to maintain import quotas that
ward off foreign sugar and boost consumer prices at home.
   An industry study unveiled Tuesday said the sugar and allied
corn-sweetener industries directly create 144,442 full-time jobs
nationwide and pump almost $7.4 billion a year into the U.S.
economy.
   ``It shows there is a lot more to this industry than the attacks
that say it only benefits a handful of growers,'' American Sugar
Alliance Chairman Luther Markwart said in making the study public.
   Markwart cited findings that, counting indirect effects, sugar
and sweetener production generate $18.5 billion in wages and
revenues, plus 361,000 jobs annually in 42 states.
   If there is a move to lift quotas as part of the 1990 farm bill,
the survey is guaranteed to be used by the industry to offset
claims that it represents only a narrow special interest.
   Because of the quotas, a pound of raw sugar that sells for 14
cents in world markets goes for about 24 cents in the United
States. That difference is passed on to consumers after the sugar
is processed, packaged and sent to the grocery shelf.
   Consumer groups and industries such as soft drink and candy
makers complain about the high cost of U.S. sugar. The House and
Senate Agriculture Committees, however, have left the quotas
intact. The two panels include members from major sugar-growing
states and lawmakers reap hefty campaign contributions from growers.
   The survey also takes into account jobs and earnings generated
by the corn-sweetener industry. Its products, used widely in soft
drinks and various foods, trail sugar in price and the two
industries are often allies.
   Lifting quotas would eventually scuttle not only beet and cane
growers but sweetener manufacturing in this country, Markwart said.
   The survey said annual sugar and sweetener output totaling more
than $7.3 billion a year is spread over many states. It said that
the combined value topped $100 million in 17 states.
   The major corn states of Iowa and Illinois headed the list of
17. Those two states, plus Indiana, Tennessee and Ohio, were the
leading corn-sweetener producers. Major cane states were Florida,
Louisiana and Hawaii; New York made the list principally as a
refining site.
   Also among the 17 were the sugarbeet producing states of
Minnesota, California, Idaho, North Dakota, Nebraska, Michigan and
Colorado. Among states on the list, Texas was notable for its
diversified production.
   In employment, the agricultural side of the two industries
contributes 115,268 jobs and the processing side 29,173, according
to the study.
   It cited seven states with substantially higher employment
totals than others: Florida, 11,057; California, 10,513; Iowa,
9,929; Louisiana, 9,890; Minnesota, 9,731; Illinois, 8,907; and
Nebraska, 8,889.
   The total includes farm workers involved in growing corn, even
though economists aren't sure just what would happen to those jobs
if sweetener production in the United States halted. But the study
said that, leaving out corn production, overall employment in the
industries would total ``a highly creditable 75,411 full-time
positions.''
   Agricultural wages for corn and sugar totaled more than $1.2
billion nationwide, according to the study. Cane states had the
highest overall payrolls, $159 million for Florida and $82.7
million for Louisiana.
   On the processing side, wages came to more than $811 million.
California led the way with $118.5 million. Overall wages for
growing and processing nationwide were just over $2 billion, the
survey said.
   It said that sugar and sweetener business generates wages of
$100 million a year or more in eight states: Florida, California,
Iowa, Illinois, Louisiana, Hawaii, Minnesota and Nebraska.
   Sugar industry critics are quick to point out not only the
impact of quotas on the wallets of consumers but the other side of
the employment story.
   ``U.S. workers also do not escape the adverse effects of this
program,'' Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., told the Senate recently.
   Bradley, the program's leading Senate critic, noted that U.S.
refineries have been closing their doors and laying off workers
because of high sugar prices. He said those costs are also hurting
other industries.
   ``The U.S. food and beverage manufacturing industries employ
hundreds of thousands of people,'' he said. ``The chocolate and
confectionary industries alone employ more than 60,000 people.
These jobs are threatened by competition from foreign manufacturers
who have access to sugar at world market prices, not America's
inflated price.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm machinery sales are expected to rise for
the third year in a row, increasing from $6 billion in 1988 to as
much as $6.7 billion in 1989, according to the Agriculture
Department.
   Higher net cash incomes, lower real interest rates, rising
farmland values and lowered agricultural debt are all trends that
are contributing to expectations for a better year in tractor
sales, USDA said.
   It said demand for the more powerful tractors is especially
strong thus far in 1989. Sales of 139-plus horsepower, two-wheel
drive and four-wheel drive tractors are expected to climb 23
percent and 65 percent respectively.
</TEXT>
