<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     08-09 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Officials Can't Find Files of Former Assistant Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development says it can't locate the files of a former housing
official whose conduct is under scrutiny in the influence-peddling
probe, but the former official says he doesn't have them.
   ``I don't even know where they are kept, much less take them
with me,'' Thomas T. Demery said Tuesday, adding that he took no
files when he left HUD last year. ``I don't have them.''
   James Lafferty, deputy assistant secretary for public affairs at
HUD, said, ``He may have taken them with him _ we don't have them
here.'' However, he said the department has no evidence that Demery
took the files.
   ``They could be someplace that we don't now know about but they
are not in the typical places that you would look for them,''
Lafferty said.
   HUD officials realized the files were missing after receiving a
Freedom of Information Act request for access to them.
   The files of two other former HUD officials _ Secretary Samuel
R. Pierce Jr. and his top aide Deborah Gore Dean _ have provided
dramatic insight into their activities at the agency.
   Pierce told Congress in May that he had no direct role in
funding decisions. Since then, however, a number of news accounts
have detailed Pierce's personal intervention in several HUD
projects, and his files offer further evidence that he was more
involved in some decisions than he indicated in his congressional
testimony.
   Ms. Dean's files show that she was often contacted by developers
and consultants seeking HUD approval for projects and often gave
proposals her endorsement although her job carried no official
funding authority.
   For two years Demery was HUD's assistant secretary for housing,
a powerful position that has jurisdiction over many of HUD's
subsidy programs.
   The report that sparked the congressional and internal
investigations of HUD focused heavily on Demery's conduct. That
report, by HUD's inspector general, questioned the selection
process used to award lucrative rehabilitation subsidies and said
many of those who benefited were contributors to a charity Demery
helped establish.
   HUD Inspector General Paul A. Adams concluded that Demery
committed no criminal offenses but said that prominent Republicans
and former agency officials appeared to get special treatment from
HUD.
   The Justice Department, which reviewed the report to determine
whether Demery violated HUD's standards of conduct, said last month
it would not prosecute him.
   Demery also was in charge of another program that was the
subject of a critical audit by the inspector general.
   That report said Demery awarded emergency HUD funding to a
number of projects that weren't eligible. Several qualified
projects that didn't receive funding later went under and were
taken over by the government, the report said.
   An Associated Press review of the program found that developers
of projects that got emergency funding although auditors said they
didn't qualify included a former business associate and several
donors to his pet charity.
   Demery, in a recent interview, said he made the awards ``on the
merits'' and questioned the audit's assertion that many of the
projects weren't eligible.
</TEXT>
