<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MistakenForDead     08-09 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mistaken For Dead,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Nearly Embalmed Had No Pulse, Home Operator Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 87-year-old woman who regained
consciousness as she was about to be embalmed showed no signs of
life before she was taken to the funeral home, a boarding home
operator said.
   ``The lady died away for a while and later came back to,'' said
Robbie Caldwell. ``The lady was laying there. She had no pulse, no
blood pressure, nothing. She was just gone.''
   Ms. Caldwell did not say whether Carrie Stringfellow was
pronounced dead by a physician before she was taken to the funeral
home on Saturday, and she refused to answer additional questions.
   Ms. Stringfellow, whose murmuring startled a mortician preparing
to embalm her, was listed in fair condition Tuesday at Mercy
Medical Center. She was taken to the hospital after she was found
to be alive.
   ``She has no recall of what happened to her Saturday evening,''
Ernest Henson, vice president of medical services at the hospital,
said at a news conference. ``It's kind of like a black period.''
   He said her memory otherwise seems to be unaffected and that she
appears to be ``cheerful and happy.'' He said Ms. Stringfellow, who
is blind, may be released from the hospital as early as Friday and
plans to live with a niece.
   Hospital officials turned down reporters' requests to interview
Ms. Stringfellow.
   ``To me, it's a horrendous ordeal she's been through,'' said
Henson.
   The incident is under investigation by the Ohio Department of
Health, according to Dr. Beth Klitch, chief of the department's
bureau of medical services.
   Ms. Klitch said the state could seek a court injunction to end
operation of the home, ask Clark County to remove residents and
pursue criminal charges.
   She said the department cited the home last April for several
structural deficiencies, such as unsafe handrails. She indicated
that some of the problems have been corrected.
   Henson said he has talked with about five physicians who have
cared for Ms. Stringfellow in the past and none said they were
contacted Saturday evening about the apparent death.
   Dennis L. Porter, director of the Dennis L. Porter Funeral Home,
said he was called by the home Saturday about 8:30 p.m. and asked
to pick up a body. When he arrived, Ms. Stringfellow was slumped in
a chair.
   ``She actually appeared to be dead,'' he said.
   Porter said the woman was placed in a pouch, which was zipped
and then placed on a cot. The cot was loaded into Porter's vehicle,
and he drove back to the funeral home, arriving about 8:45 p.m.
   Porter said he unzipped the pouch and prepared to move the woman
to the embalming table when ``she uttered a sound.''
   It was ``a very eerie feeling,'' he said. ``I was amazed.''
   Porter, 64, said there is no requirement that a death
certificate be signed before a body is transported to a funeral
home. He said he often fills out death certificates himself and
then has them signed by physicians.
   Webster Junk, an inspector for the State Board of Embalmers and
Funeral Directors, the state agency that licenses funeral homes,
said a funeral director must know that a coroner or licensed
physician will sign a death certificate before a body can be
transported to a funeral home.
   He also said the family of the deceased must give permission
before the body can be embalmed. Porter said Ms. Stringfellow's
family had given permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-09 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,480</SECOND>
<NOTE>Homeless Number Growing, Study Says</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 14 million families could be forced
into homelessness by a mild recession in the U.S. economy,
according to a study.
   The report by the American Affordable Housing Institute said
public efforts to help the homeless rely are badly underfinanced,
uncoordinated and are conducted by officials often unaware of the
resources available to them.
   The report by the institute, a research center at Rutgers
University in New Brunswick, N.J., estimated that there are 4
million to 14 million American families ``living on the knife edge
of homelessness'' who could face life on the streets should a mild
recession occur.
   ``They are one pay check, one domestic argument from the
streets,'' the report said. ``In a mild recession, homelessness in
America is likely to double and triple almost overnight.''
   Estimates on the current number of homeless people range between
655,000 to 4 million, but the total is growing 20 percent to 40
percent annually, the study said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>CIA Says Turmoil Will Hobble China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turmoil in China means the government there
will have a difficult time dealing with inflation and other
economic problems, the CIA has concluded.
   Economic reform has been put on hold by the central government
and economic problems could prompt renewed political unrest in the
1990s, said the report to the Joint Economic Committee released
Tuesday.
   ``The new leadership has endorsed a continuation of the
austerity program, but the social and political turmoil that has
gripped China since April will make it difficult for Beijing to
solve its pressing economic problems,'' the report said.
   Inflation in 1989 hit 19 percent overall and 30 percent in urban
areas, the highest levels since the communists came to power in
1949.
   The CIA authors also said China's military leaders probably will
play a larger political and economic role in return for the
military crackdown last May on democracy demonstrations in Beijing.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FCC Says Prof Filed False License Applications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission suspects
that a professor at the State University of New York at Oswego was
running an ``application mill'' that filed for more than 100
broadcast licenses under false or forged names in order to collect
settlement payoffs.
   ``You could use that term,'' FCC spokeswoman Patricia Chew said
Tuesday discussing the case of Bernard Boozer, of Central Square,
N.Y. ``Some of his applications did enter into settlement
agreements, if I remember correctly.''
   Outgoing FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick sent a letter last week
to the Justice Department asking for an investigation of Boozer.
After an investigation, the FCC concluded that Boozer may have
violated both commission regulations and federal law.
   Boozer could not be reached for comment. There was no telephone
number listed under his name in Central Square, N.Y.
</TEXT>
