<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     08-09 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadway Revival of `Shenandoah' Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The songs sound better the second time around in
the Broadway revival of ``Shenandoah,'' and John Cullum, returning
in the starring role, is just as good as he was when he won a 1975
Tony Award.
   The homespun anti-war musical opened Tuesday at the Virginia
Theater with a cast boasting a larger percentage of very good
voices than most Broadway musicals.
   Cullum's fine voice isn't as effortless as it once was, but the
September that has entered it improves his ability to convey the
widower Charlie Anderson's deep love for his family.
   ``Shenandoah'' originally opened Jan. 7, 1975, at Broadway's
Alvin Theater and ran for 1,050 performances. The revival, which
first played in Toronto, is scheduled through Sept. 2, with an
extension considered.
   The story is based on the 1965 movie of the same name which
starred James Stewart. It tells of a father, six sons, daughter and
daughter-in-law who live and farm together in the Shenandoah Valley
of Virginia during the Civil War.
   Undertakers are the only winners in a war, Anderson believes,
and he keeps his family neutral. But the war won't leave them alone.
   A corny moment, as Anderson tells his prospective son-in-law
that women sometimes get angry when husbands don't do things the
women haven't asked them to do, is bearable because it's comic
relief against tragedies the audience knows must come in Act. 2.
``Shenandoah'' is sentimental, too, but focusing on individuals in
one family makes the sentiment meaningful, not shallow.
   The songs are a cross between the wholesome Rodgers and
Hammerstein style and ballads written for somebody like Tony
Bennett. There's an anthem, ``Freedom''; a lullaby, ``Papa's Gonna
Make It Alright''; the up-tempo ``Next to Lovin' (I Like
Fightin')'' for the five grown sons, and ``The Only Home I Know,''
an Irish-sounding tune sung by Irish tenor Stephen Simms.
   Tracey Moore was the daughter of the house, displaying a voice
that would fit perfectly in ``Me and My Girl.'' Other principals
were Camilla Scott, the daughter-in-law; Burke Lawrence,
Christopher Martin, Nigel Hamer, Stephen McIntyre and Robin Blake,
the grown sons; Jason Zimbler, the young son; Roy McKay, his slave
friend, and Thomas Cavanagh, the son-in-law.
   Gary Geld wrote music and Peter Udell wrote lyrics. Their first
Broadway show was ``Purlie.'' The book was by James Lee Barrett,
Udell and Philip Rose, based on Barrett's screenplay. Rose directed
the revival and the original.
   Scenery is by Reginald Bronskill, based on Kert Lundell's
minimal originals. Producers are Howard Hurst, Sophie Hurst and
Peter Ingster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
