<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Hirsch     08-09 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Hirsch,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Source Tells Newspaper No Evidence of Spying Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czech-born Air Force officer continues to be
restricted to a Texas base while the Pentagon investigates
allegations of espionage, but a report published today says no
evidence of spying has been uncovered.
   ``No one in channels is saying that this guy's a spy,'' The
Washington Post quoted an unidentified official as saying about
Capt. John Vladimir Hirsch.
   The newspaper also said that some high officials, whom it did
not identify, were cautioning that only ``irregularities'' that
need explanation had been discovered, not evidence of spying.
   ``No charges have been made against him at this point,''
spokesman Pete Williams told reporters at a Pentagon briefing
Tuesday.
   Hirsch, suspected of selling secrets to the Soviet bloc while
serving with the 690th Electronics Security Wing in West Berlin,
has been restricted to Kelley Air Force Base near San Antonio while
the investigation is conducted.
   The restriction began last week after he returned from Germany.
   Williams said he couldn't comment to queries that Hirsch isn't
cooperating with the investigation. He did say, however, that no
hearing has been scheduled.
   Hirsch was head of engineering and installation at the Air
Force's electronic security wing at the West Berlin Templehof
Central Airport. The unit collects intelligence on Warsaw Pact
radar and communications.
   Pentagon officials, speaking privately, said the Air Force found
uncashed paychecks, evidence of bank accounts totaling more than
$120,000, photographs of Western military installations and other
classified documents in Hirsch's Berlin home.
   Hirsch came under suspicion during the routine review of his
security clearance, reportedly after he failed a lie detector test.
   Lt. Erlinda Baker, a public affairs officer with the Electronic
Security Command, said the command works on communications and
electronic combat capabilities, including ways the Air Force
protects its radar from being jammed.
   Hirsch, 33, lists Cleveland Heights, Ohio, as his home and has
been with the Air Force since 1979, Baker said. He was born in
Prague, Czechoslovakia, and became a U.S. citizen in 1971.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
