<FIRST>u i AM-Japan 3rdLd-Writethru a0446 08-09 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0446,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Delays Confirmation of Kaifu, Senate Votes for Doi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new graf 8 beginning: Meanwhile, Uno's ... to UPDATE
with Cabinet resigning en masse. Picks up graf 8 pvs, `On Tuesday ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition imposed an embarrassing delay
Wednesday in Parliament's confirmation of Toshiki Kaifu as Japan's
second new prime minister in a little over two months.
   Kaifu, who was elected Tuesday to head the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, was approved by the more powerful lower house,
but the Senate then voted for Japan Socialist Party Chairwoman
Takako Doi.
   It was the first time in 41 years that the two houses disagreed
on who should take power.
   Delegates from the two chambers were to meet in conference later
in the day to go through the motions of finding a compromise. If
they fail, as expected, under the constitution the lower house
victor prevails.
   Kaifu, 58, called the delay a ``severe consequence of our
election defeat.''
   Kaifu is succeeding Sousuke Uno, who decided to step down after
the Liberal Democrats were thrashed in the July 23 election for
half the seats in the upper house of the Diet, Japan's parliament.
   The party lost its majority in the Senate for the first time
since it was formed in 1955, but still commands the lower house.
   Meanwhile, Uno's Cabinet met and resigned en masse, clearing the
way for Kaifu to form a new government to try to win back the
public approval that the Liberal Democrats have lost in a
succession of scandals and unpopular policies.
   On Tuesday, Kaifu pledged to restore public trust after a year
of scandal and unpopular policies that caused voters to turn on the
governing party for the first time since it was formed.
   ``I am painfully aware of the weight of my responsibility,''
Kaifu told a news conference Tuesday. ``We have been reborn and we
must forge ahead. We must carry out political reforms and shed our
old skin.''
   A secret ballot of Liberal Democratic members of parliament and
state-level party leaders resulted in 279 votes for Kaifu, 120 for
former Welfare Minister Yoshiro Hayashi and 48 for Shintaro
Ishihara, a novelist and former transport minister.
   The upper house elections cost the Liberal Democrats their
majority for the first time since the party was formed in 1955.
General elections for the more powerful lower house must be called
by next July.
   On Tuesday night, Kaifu met with other party officials to decide
on a new Cabinet and party leadership, a delicate task of balancing
key jobs among rival party factions in the party.
   He succeeds Sousuke Uno, who was plagued by reports that he kept
paid mistresses. Uno resigned to take responsibility for the loss
of the upper house elections, attributed to the sex and money
scandals and a 3 percent sales tax that outraged housewives.
   Uno had replaced Noboru Takeshita, who stepped down June 2 to
take responsibility for the Recruit Co. influence-buying scandal,
which reached the top levels of politics, business and the
bureaucracy.
   Takeshita chose Uno, one of the few ranking politicians
untouched by the Recruit scandal, as his successor but Kaifu was
selected by the first party election in 17 years.
   Despite the election, many still see Kaifu's candidacy as a
product of backroom politics. He has no personal power base and is
viewed as unlikely to stand in the way of more senior leaders
temporarily blocked from the prime ministry by the Recruit scandal.
   How long Kaifu will serve is not clear. His term as party
president is only three months, until the end of Takeshita's
original term, but he could be elected to another.
   Before Tuesday's vote, candidate Hayashi said: ``I read in the
newspaper this morning that the election was already decided. The
Liberal Democratic Party presidential election is not subject to
the Public Election Law, but if it were, it would be violating the
rules.''
   Opposition parties accused the Liberal Democrats of continuing
politics in the old style.
   ``As always, it was secret factional politics,'' said Ms. Doi of
the Japan Socialist Party, which made the greatest gains in the
upper house elections. ``There is simply no change. It's just what
has been done all along: they're changing a book's cover without
changing its contents.''
   An editorial in the newspaper Asahi said maneuvering within the
party ``blatantly reflects a design to sustain a system of
leadership monopolized by the mainstream factions.''
   ``The starting point for Kaifu is to grapple with the issues
that were brought to light in the presidential election and to
change what should be changed,'' it said. ``Otherwise, his election
by vote will prove to be a farce.''
   In pledging to change the system, Kaifu told the news conference
Tuesday: ``In various ways, factions have had an evil influence,
but just saying that they are bad won't make them go away.''
   Kaifu lacks experience in foreign and financial affairs, does
not lead his own faction and has never served in a top party post.
   He was the youngest member of Parliament when elected at age 29
and predicted at the time he would become prime minister in another
29 years.
</TEXT>
