<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0213EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-Calif-Abortion 2ndLd-Writethru a0417 08-09 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif-Abortion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0417,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Republican Leads in State Assembly Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with anti-abortion Republican's
lead narrowing. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Due largely...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Replacement, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-abortion candidate held a
narrow lead Tuesday among Republicans in the first state election
since the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling giving states more authority
to limit abortions.
   With 29 percent of the precincts reporting, Richard Lyles, 42,
of Poway was leading with 6,140 votes to 5,129 for GOP rival Tricia
Hunter, 36, of Bonita, the only pro-choice Republican on the ballot
in the heavily GOP district in San Diego and Riverside counties,
   Jeannine Correia, an instructor for the developmentally disabled
from Poway, was leading the Democrats in early returns with 1,508
votes to 729 for Stephen Thorne, 34, of Escondido.
   Due largely to the abortion issue, the unusual special election
to fill an empty Assembly seat managed to overcome the summer
doldrums.
   Voters in the 76th Assembly District in northeast San Diego
County and southwest Riverside County were picking a successor to
GOP Assemblyman Bill Bradley, who died of cancer June 1.
   The likely outcome was that one of the six Republicans and one
of the two Democrats would meet in a runoff general election on
Oct. 3, when the Republican would be the huge favorite in the
GOP-dominated district.
   One candidate would have to win more than 50 percent of the vote
in Tuesday's special primary to win the seat outright.
   The other Republican candidates were Linda Brannon, 42, of
Poway; Ray Foster, 69, of Spring Valley; Bill Hoover, 45, of
Escondido; and Dennis Koolhaas, 34, of Escondido.
   Although major local issues include crime, taxes and population
growth, national attention has focused on the abortion question.
Both pro-choice and anti-abortion advocates say the election is the
first for a state office since the high court's July 3 ruling in
the Webster case.
   The only pro-choice Republican is Hunter, a registered nurse who
is director of surgical services at Chula Vista Community Hospital
and president of the state Board of Registered Nursing.
   The Democrats, Thorne, a San Diego County mental health worker,
and Correia, are also pro-choice.
   Lyles, a management consultant; Hoover, a San Diego police
lieutenant; and Foster, a retired appliance store owner, are
strongly anti-abortion and opposed to state funding of Medi-Cal
abortions. Koolhaas, an aide to state Sen. Bill Craven, and
Brannon, a Poway City Council member and deputy mayor, also oppose
state funding but tend to sidestep questions on the legality of
abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The district sprawls over the desert area of the two counties,
extending into the populated areas of San Marcos, Escondido, Poway,
Alpine and Bonita. The Riverside County area has 65,439 registered
voters, while San Diego County has 173,541. The district is
overwhelmingly Republican _ 54.2 percent to 32.7 percent Democrat.
   All 10 candidates appeared on the ballot together, regardless of
party and voters could pick whomever they wanted.
   In the Webster decision, the Supreme Court expanded state
authority over abortions. Current state law and state Supreme Court
rulings protect women's abortion rights and require the state to
pay for poor women's abortions. But groups on both sides of the
issue focused on the race.
</TEXT>
