<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Jaywalking     08-09 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jaywalking,0122</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Police End Jaywalking Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittsburgh police have declared victory over
jaywalking and have quietly halted their crackdown on wayward
pedestrians.
   Cmdr. Edward Patterson said officers issued about 600 written
warnings to jaywalkers downtown and in the city's Squirrel Hill and
Oakland neighborhoods since January, when Public Safety Director
Glenn Cannon promised to go after those illegally crossing city
streets.
   Patterson said officers stopped issuing written warnings a
couple of months ago and no one was fined $32.50 for jaywalking.
But he said the effort was very successful because it made
pedestrians more aware of the dangers of jaywalking.
   He said pedestrians now are less likely to jaywalk in front of
police officers.
</TEXT>
