<FIRST>r p PM-AtlantaMayoral     08-09 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Mayoral,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maynard Jackson Headed for Third Mayoral Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The withdrawal of his sole opponent leaves the
way clear for former Mayor Maynard Jackson to return to City Hall
for a third term.
   Michael Lomax, chairman of the Fulton County Commission,
withdrew from the mayoral election Tuesday after polls showed he
was far behind. That left the 51-year-old Jackson, who served two
four-year terms beginning in 1974, with no opposition.
   Lomax, 41, who trailed by 34 percentage points in the polls,
said he was stepping aside to ensure ``this campaign does not
divide our city's family.''
   He might have been able to win, Lomax said, by hitting harder on
crime, but ``the real casualty of that attack ... would have been
the city ... It would have been too costly a victory.''
   The rate of 176 crimes per 1,000 residents in this city of
445,000 is the nation's worst, according to FBI statistics released
Monday.
   There are no other candidates; and if one announced, there
wouldn't be enough time before the Oct. 3 election to mount a
credible campaign, said Atlanta pollster Claibourne Darden.
``There's no time, no body and no money,'' Darden said. ``You've
got three no's.''
   City Councilman Hosea Williams hinted he might run simply to
give Jackson some opposition. ``It would be a tragedy to see
Maynard Jackson walk into City Hall. He ought to be challenged,''
Williams said.
   Jackson, like Lomax a black Democrat, had cemented his populist
appeal among the black majority with growing support from white
businessmen. Lomax ran as the more business-oriented candidate but
failed to broaden his support.
   During his terms, Jackson had often battled with businessmen,
who have gotten along well with outgoing Mayor Andrew Young.
   ``There has been a change in attitudes. And a lot of the old
guard is gone,'' said Angelo Fuster, Jackson's press secretary.
   Darden said the Lomax ads, in which he tried to link Jackson
with Atlanta's crime rate, probably had little impact and forced
Lomax to drain his coffers.
   ``He took that high-risk technique of viciously attacking his
opponent, and he found out why it's a high-risk strategy _ it
doesn't work most of the time,'' Darden said. ``That's the most
important thing. He's broke.''
   Jackson, whose campaign featured a pledge not to allow a
building boom to overrun neighborhoods, said the negative ads ``had
very little effect on me.''
   Lomax's withdrawal allows him to keep his job as commission
chairman, which he would have been forced to give up by the Aug. 16
qualifying deadline.
   Fulton County includes about 90 percent of Atlanta's population,
which is 61 percent black.
   Young, who cannot seek a third consecutive term, said Lomax's
decision to pull out ``probably relieves a lot of friends of both
of them.''
   Williams claimed that Lomax, who worked for Jackson in his
previous administrations, always intended to drop out to prevent a
candidate from running who was unacceptable to the ``black
middle-class power structure.''
   ``I have said from the beginning _ Maynard and Lomax would never
face each other. This was only a political drama,'' Williams said.
</TEXT>
