<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-09 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Tokyo Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slipped modestly against the
Japanese yen Wednesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange firmed.
   The dollar closed at 138.85 yen, down 0.40 yen from Tuesday's
close of 139.25 yen. It opened at 138.72 yen and ranged between
138.40-139.00 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average for 225 selected issues gained 99.79
points, or 0.29 percent, closing at 34,859.27. On Tuesday, the
index climbed 129.10 points.
   Daiwa Bank trader Shinzo Yamamoto said majority of market
players expect the dollar to move lower, and were reluctant to make
major moves ahead of the release of the U.S. producer price index
for July, scheduled for Friday.
   ``The dollar-yen rate is expected to back to the rate before the
unemployment rate release last Friday,'' he said. Earlier last
week, the dollar was moving in the 135-136 yen range but it went up
after the lower-than-expected U.S. jobless rate reported Friday.
   Yamamoto said investors in newly issued U.S. government bonds
were buying the dollar to facilitate their purchases.
   On the stock market, dealers attributed the index's rise largely
to the yen's upswing against the dollar and gains on overseas stock
market during their trading overnight.
   The index's gain was inspired by rises in housing issues, said a
dealer with a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The dealer said housing issues attracted participants by
prospects that housing improvement will be a major policy in the
new government that is to be led by legislator Toshiki Kaifu.
   Kaifu was elected chairman of the governing Liberal Democratic
Party Tuesday to succeed Sousuke Uno, who has resigned to take
responsibility for the party's loss in the July 23 election for the
upper house of parliament.
   Kaifu is expected to be named the new prime minister later
Wednesday after approval by the lower house of the parliament.
</TEXT>
