<DOCNO> AP890809-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Undercover-Rape     08-09 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Undercover-Rape,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Could Have Stopped Rape, Women's Groups Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer could have stopped the rape of a
suspected prostitute without blowing his cover in a drug
investigation, representatives of two women's organizations said.
   ``It doesn't take a police badge to stop a rape,'' said Karen
Ashmore, president of the Dallas Chapter of the National
Organization for Women, which has called for the firing of Officer
Tomas Echartea. ``I certainly would not be comfortable with a
police officer watching over my security and welfare who let a rape
happen.''
   She said the organization will formally ask Groesbeck Police
Chief Chuck Walker to fire Echartea, who said he pretended to be
sick while three men he was investigating on drug charges raped the
woman.
   Walker, who has defended Echartea's non-action, did not return
phone calls Tuesday to The Associated Press.
   Wanda White, a counselor at the Rape Crisis Center in Dallas,
said Echartea's failure to do something was ``a crime in itself.''
   ``If a crime is being committed, somebody should do something
about it ... That's a decision all of us have to make,'' Ms. White
said.
   ``You don't want to ruin your credibility,'' Echartea told The
Dallas Morning News. ``If it had been a life-threatening situation,
I'd have blown my cover. I'd have had to. You just can't let
someone be killed.''
   Echartea said he included the rape in that day's report to his
superiors. The officer who took the report could not be reached for
comment.
   Dallas police said they will begin a criminal investigation and
try to find the woman and ask if she wants to press charges.
   Detectives will also ask Echartea for a full account of what
happened, Dallas Deputy Chief Ray Hawkins said.
   ``I think he had some obligation as one human being to another
to help her as best he could,'' Hawkins said. ``All women, even
prostitutes, have a right not to be raped.''
   Echartea's investigation resulted in the arrests of four people
on charges of selling drugs. He is an officer on the police force
of Groesbeck, 85 miles south of Dallas.
   Dallas County District Attorney John Vance said he did not know
whether state law requires Texas police to intervene in felonies
they observe.
   Echartea first recounted the incident publicly in an interview
last week.
</TEXT>
