<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-09 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Key Tokyo Index Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen for
a second day today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index
gained.
   The dollar closed at 138.85 yen, down 0.40 yen from Tuesday's
finish of 139.25 yen. It opened at 138.72 yen and ranged between
138.40 yen and 139.00 yen.
   On Tuesday, the dollar declined 0.53 yen after gaining 3.58 yen
in the three previous trading days.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues added 99.79
points, or 0.29 percent, closing at 34,859.27. The index had gained
129.10 points Tuesday after a four-day decline.
   Daiwa Bank's Shinzo Yamamoto said many traders expected the
dollar to move lower and were reluctant to make major moves before
the release Friday of the U.S. producer price index for July.
   On the stock market, dealers attributed the rise of the Nikkei
index mainly to the yen's upswing against the dollar and overnight
gains on overseas stock markets.
   A dealer with a major securities firm in Tokyo said construction
and housing issues attracted buyers who anticipated that housing
improvement will be a major policy in the new government to be led
by Toshiki Kaifu, the governing Liberal Democratic Party's choice
to replace outgoing Prime Minister Sousuke Uno.
   Uno resigned to take responsibility for the party's loss in the
July 23 election for the upper house of Parliament.
</TEXT>
