<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0609EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-AlbanyElection     08-09 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Albany Election,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incumbent Loses Mayoral Race in City Where Murder Rate Is Hot Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The incumbent lost but denied that his defeat
in the mayoral primary had to do with FBI statistics showing the
area has the nation's highest murder rate.
   Mayor Larry Bays conceded victory to challenger Tommy Coleman,
who had 57.2 percent of the vote according to final returns
Tuesday. The returns showed Coleman had 8,684 votes to Bays' 6,506.
   FBI statistics released Monday showed the two-county Albany
metropolitan area had the highest rate of murders per 100,000
residents among the nation's metropolitan areas. The statistics
became a last-minute issue in the Democratic primary, where Bays
and Coleman, a banker, were the only candidates.
   Bays did not elaborate about why he lost the primary, but called
upon the city to support Coleman, who faces no Republican
opposition in the Nov. 7 general election.
   Bays told voters Monday that the new FBI statistics are
misleading and that Coleman hurt the city's image by capitalizing
on the murder rate in his campaign.
   Coleman replied: ``I've walked all over Albany. People are
concerned about crime and drug abuse.''
   The FBI Uniform Crime Report said the Albany area had 24.1
murders per 100,000 residents in 1988. The New York City area was
second with 22.7 per 100,000, a total of 3,577 murders compared to
the Albany area's 29. The Albany area's population is 120,560,
compared to New York's 8.6 million.
   Assistant Police Chief Bob Boren said 70 percent of Albany's
murders could be attributed to drug abuse. Police say crack has
become pervasive in the city's poor neighborhoods.
   Bays, an accountant, was elected in 1986 to complete the term of
former Mayor James Gray Sr., who died in office. Bays won his first
full two-year term in 1987, when he ran unopposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
