<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSChild     08-09 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Child,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Suffering From AIDS, Sexual Abuse, Placed in Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social workers put a 9-year-old girl with
AIDS in a foster home after a report that her mother had sexually
abused her and punished her with drug injections.
   ``Everybody just wants to give her the best we can give her in
the time she has,'' said David Reilly, regional director of the
Texas Department of Human Services. ``She is with the person she
wants to be with and if that works out, there is no reason to move
her.''
   The girl is now in foster care with a family who knows her, and
will likely remain in state custody until she dies, he said.
   State District Judge Tom Rickhoff on Monday held a closed-door
hearing about the girl, citing a law requiring confidentiality in
AIDS cases.
   Her mother, a drug abuser, died of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   The youngster was left to live with relatives, but social
workers became concerned that those surroundings were further
endangering her life, and an emergency court order removed the girl
and placed her in foster care.
   One of the issues believed to have been discussed in the Monday
hearing was whether the child will attend public school.
   ``As far as we're concerned, she's going to go to school,''
Reilly said. ``I don't think we have an obligation to tell the
school (about the disease). In fact, we may be precluded (by law)
from telling them.''
</TEXT>
