<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0617EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NewZealand     08-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Zealand,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palmer Begins Forming Cabinet, Says He Will be Less `Exciting'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Prime Minister Geoffrey
Palmer today began forming his Cabinet and said there would be no
domestic or foreign policy changes under his administration.
   He also said his administration would be ``less exciting'' than
that of his predecessor, David Lange, who announced his resignation
Monday for health reasons.
   A Labor Party caucus elected Palmer prime minister on Tuesday
and chose Helen Clark to replace him as deputy prime minister.
   Palmer, a lawyer, says he pales in comparison to the colorful
Lange, who for five years captured world attention by arguing with
the United States and France over nuclear issues.
   Lange's departure followed major economic change in New Zealand,
a former British colony of 3.3 million in the South Pacific.
Palmer, 47, promised to pursue the Lange vision of an independent
New Zealand.
   He also reiterated that there would be no change in the nation's
anti-nuclear stance, which led to U.S. warships being banned from
the nation's ports.
   The United States welcomed Palmer's appointment, noting he had
spent considerable time in the United States as an academic.
   Asked at a news conference today if he was prepared to meet
President Bush, Palmer replied that he would meet anybody at any
time.
   Earlier, he said: ``We want to have dialogue with the
Americans.''
   Lange's resignation prompted tributes from around the South
Pacific. The prime minister of Papua New Guinea, Rabbie Namaliu,
said he would miss Lange's ``fearless dipolomacy.''
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke of Australia said that despite some
policy disagreements, the men were friends.
   Cook Island Prime Minister Geoffrey Henry said history would
judge Lange as New Zealand's most effective prime minister so far.
   Palmer, a former attorney general, said he would probably
complete his Cabinet appointments by Friday.
   He also said he offered Lange, also a lawyer, the position of
attorney general and that Lange had said he might consider the
offer.
   Palmer said it was certain he would have discussions with U.S.
ambassador-designate Della Newman when she arrives in New Zealand
to take up her post.
   ``But diplomacy is best not conducted through loud speakers in
the media,'' he said.
</TEXT>
