<FIRST>r a PM-InterstateFire 1stLd-Writethru a0468 08-09 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interstate Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Plans To Start Clean Up After Dump Fire Is Put Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Kean declaring state of emergency,
picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Flames and...' EDITS 6th graf pvs to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges closed down a dump where a fire
destroyed part of an interstate highway and officials said it could
take as long as a year to reopen the busy commuter link.
   The two-judge panel of the Superior Court's Appellate Division
on Tuesday ordered Hub Recycling and Scrap Metals Co. to remove the
waste under Interstate 78 and adjoining Route 22. They put the
cleanup under the state Department of Environmental Protection's
supervision.
   Gov. Thomas H. Kean declared a state of emergency to obtain
federal funds to rebuild the charred interstate.
   Flames and heat from a giant pile of debris early Monday buckled
an elevated portion of Interstate 78, a critical east-west link in
one of the nation's busiest highway interchanges between New York
City and Pennsylvania. The fire was extinguished Tuesday afternoon.
   State officials said repairs that forced the closing of a
1\-mile stretch of the highway could take a year. Traffic has been
rerouted from the roadway, which carried five lanes of traffic in
both directions.
   A report in The New York Times today said three of the five
eastbound lanes were supported by a set of columns and beams that
were sound enough to carry traffic, and said that section might
open within a month or so.
   Kean lauded the judges' decision, saying it would pave the way
for a cleanup at the site, which authorities say is an illegal dump
and waste transfer station. Hub says it's a recycling facility.
   State officials have been trying for two years to halt the
pile-up of waste at the four-acre site.
   Essex County Counsel H. Curtis Meanor, a former federal judge,
estimated the site contained 50,000 tons of waste beneath the
highways, and that it would cost about $100 per ton, or about $5
million, to clear it.
</TEXT>
