<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-09 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady in quiet morning trading in
Europe, with little news in the market to influence its movements.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Traders said they didn't expect any news to move the market
until Friday's release of the U.S. producer price index and retail
sales figures for July.
   Market activity was very quiet, they said, with intermittent
interest in the dollar and more sustained activity on cross
currency rates.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 138.85 yen.
Later, in London, it rose to 138.95 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid morning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8953 West German marks, up from 1.8900
   _1.6323 Swiss francs, up from 1.6270
   _6.4075 French francs, up from 6.3995
   _2.1382 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1398
   _1,363.00 Italian lire, up from 1,362.50
   _1.1710 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1720
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.6230 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $1.6250 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $365 a troy ounce, down from $365.45
late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's main bullion dealers fixed
a recommended price of $365.15.
   In Zurich the bid price was $365.20, down from $365.85 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.40 to close at $365.88.
   Silver was quoted at $5.16 an ounce, unchanged from Tuesday.
</TEXT>
