<SECOND>PM-Turkey-Bombing,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Damages Justice Ministry in Ankara</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blast at the Justice Ministry today
caused minor damage but no casualties, police said.
   The blast came at a time when the justice minister, Oltan
Sungurlu, has come under criticism from the opposition and press
because of a 42-day-old hunger strike by 200 leftist inmates.
   No group claimed immediate responsibility for the bombing.
   Investigators said the explosive device was placed inside a
garbage can in the ladies' room on the first floor of the ministry.
   The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported police detained
one person, but the report was not immediately confirmed.
   The explosion came a week after two leftist inmates died due to
what officials said was dehydration from the hunger strike.
Newspapers and other inmates said the men were beaten to death.
   The deaths came after they were transferred along with 280
fasting prisoners from Eskisehir province to a prison in Aydin, 300
miles west.
   The two inmates belonged to the outlawed Kurdish Labor Party, a
guerrilla group that is fighting for an independent state in the
southeastern parts of Turkey.
   The inmates began a hunger strike at Eskisehir prison on June 28
to protest restrictions imposed by prison authorities after it was
discovered that the inmates were trying to tunnel to freedom.
