<FIRST>r i PM-China-Executions     08-09 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Executions,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>18 Criminals Executed in Canton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen criminals were executed in the
southern Chinese city of Canton today, including a man from the
nearby Portuguese enclave of Macao, a pro-Beijing newspaper
reported.
   The crimes committed by the condemned men included robbery,
murder and rape, the Chinese-language New Evening Post reported
from Canton. It appeared the cases were not connected with the
pro-democracy protests that erupted across China beginning in April.
   Macao's Liang Mingyuan, 40, was executed for masterminding a
plan to steal gold from sellers involved in the Canton black market
two years ago, the report said.
   Also executed were two officers of the armed police accused of
smuggling and five roaming bandits accused of robbery.
   China releases no figures on capital punishment, but more than
10,000 criminals are believed to have been executed since 1983,
when an anti-crime drive was initiated.
   Murder, rape and multiple thefts are among the most common
crimes in China leading to execution, normally carried out by a
bullet to the back of the head.
</TEXT>
