<FIRST>u a PM-Bush-Gunman     08-09 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Gunman,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Says Voices Told Him to Kill Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robber told authorities he plotted to
assassinate President Bush and came close to making an attempt on
Bush's life in Michigan four months ago.
   John Spencer Daughetee, 34, told Oakland, Calif., police and FBI
agents about the attempt after he was arrested during a bank
robbery Friday. Daughetee was being held in Oakland without bond
Tuesday on bank robbery charges.
   Police and Secret Service agents said Daughetee has no apparent
motive for stalking Bush.
   ``He admitted that at some point he started hearing voices and
that he has been following the president around the U.S. in an
effort to get close enough to kill him,'' Sgt. Sam Maddux, a
robbery investigator with the Oakland Police Department said
Tuesday.
   Authorities said Daughetee has a history of psychological
problems and was investigated several years ago in Indiana after
making threats against then-President Reagan.
   Maddux said Daughetee, believed to be from Flora, Ind., said
during interviews with authorities that he was in a crowd of about
4,000 people that attended Bush's speech in the Detroit enclave of
Hamtramck on April 17. Bush announced economic incentives for
Poland during the speech.
   James Huse, special agent in charge of the Secret Service office
in Detroit, said Daughetee claimed he had been in Hamtramck the
night before Bush's speech.
   ``He told agents he had picked out the perfect spot to shoot
from but couldn't reach it on speech day because of metal
detectors,'' Huse said. ``He then ran to several areas trying to
get close enough for a shot but before he could shoot, the
president finished and left the podium.''
   Maddux said Daughetee had spoken of carrying guns including a
.22-caliber automatic pistol and a .380-caliber automatic handgun,
but it wasn't clear what gun Daughetee had in Hamtramck.
   Daughetee had $1,400 when he was arrested Friday for robbing
Gateway Savings in Oakland, Maddux said.
   Sgt. Greg Bingham of the Oakland police said Daughetee said he
needed the money to ``go back east and kill the president.''
   Daughetee also told investigators he committed a spree of bank
heists dating back to November 1986, beginning with a bank in
Sacramento, Calif. Maddux said the other banks Daughetee admitted
to robbing were in Miami; Charlotte, N.C.; Baltimore; Portland,
Ore.; and San Francisco.
   Two of the banks, Gibraltar Savings and First Interstate Bank,
both in San Francisco, were robbed Friday before Gateway Savings.
</TEXT>
