<FIRST>r r PM-Afghanistan     08-09 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Sources Say One Killed in Ammunition Dump Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man died after a rocket hit an
ammunition dump, triggering explosions that lasted more than 3{
hours, U.S. sources said today. Relief workers said eight people
were injured.
   The man, who lived about 500 yards from the dump in the Khair
Khana district of northwest Kabul, was running from his house after
the rocket hit at dusk Tuesday and ammunition and rockets in the
dump started to explode, said the U.N. sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said he expected
to have information on the death later today.
   The Avicina emergency hospital, which acts as a coordinating
center for casualties, reported five Tuesday after the dump started
exploding. But today, doctors there said they knew of no dead or
injured and that casualties might have been taken to military
hospitals.
   Relief workers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said eight
people suffered serious injuries in rocket attacks citywide Tuesday
night, some in the Khair Khana district.
   After intense rocket attacks on Kabul for four days, the city
had been relatively quiet until about half a dozen rockets hit the
hillside dump.
   Clouds of black smoke billowed over the northwestern part of
Kabul, flames danced in the night sky and explosions boomed across
the city, several rocking buildings. At one point, all the lights
in the city went out for 20 minutes in a power outage.
   But this morning the Khair Khana district was bustling again,
including the streets just below the hillside dump, which looked
like a burned field. In some houses the windows were broken and the
floors were covered with ash, but otherwise the area looked
untouched by the explosions.
   The government blames Moslem guerrillas for rockets that have
slammed into Kabul almost daily since late June.
   More than 115 rockets have hit the city since Saturday. More
than 40 hit the capital Monday, the worst day of the recent blitz.
Eight people were reported killed.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-allied
government have tried repeatedly with little success to hit
military targets in Kabul.
   Most of the rockets since late June have struck civilian areas.
At least 281 people have been killed and 745 injured in the
attacks, and a car bombing July 15 killed 19 and wounded 56,
according to U.N. sources.
   A military source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Afghan army recently moved a large amount of ammunition from the
city's airport to the depot.
   In a report quoting the official Afghan Bakhtar news agency, the
official Soviet news agency Tass said government forces seized 300
artillery shells and hundreds of mines in Monday's operations. The
report gave no other details.
   The government announced Tuesday that three men had been
captured in connection with the car bombing.
   Amani, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said the men belonged to
``counterrevolutionary organizations'' based in the Pakistani city
of Peshawar. He said they had admitted masterminding the explosion.
   The most powerful guerrilla forces are based in Pakistan.
   Amani said police were searching for other conspirators
identified by the three men.
</TEXT>
