<SECOND>PM-Fires Glance,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Fires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a glance at forest fires Tuesday in the West:
   California: Both the 15,300-acre Vail fire in Cleveland National
Forest east of San Diego and the 7,500-acre Balch fire in Sierra
National Forest east of Fresno were declared contained Monday.
   Idaho: Fires still burned on 104,000 acres in the western and
central parts of the state. Several dozen residents of Lowman, 70
miles northeast of Boise, were allowed back in their homes Tuesday
as firefighters had secured lines around 60 percent of the
43,000-acre Lowman Fire.
   Oregon: Lightning started new fires in southwestern Oregon. But
the 12,000-acre Monument Rock Fire in the Malheur and
Wallowa-Whitman national forests was contained. Crews were close to
containing the 23,350-acre Canal Fire on the eastern boundary of
the Eagle Cap Wilderness near Enterprise.
   Utah: The 1,700-acre Chalk Creek blaze, 45 miles east of Salt
Lake City, was contained and expected to be controlled by Wednesday.
   Washington: Scores of lightning fires were contained before they
grew to more than a half-acre. A 3,000-acre fire still burned in
range land and timber on the Colville Indian Reservation in the
state's northeastern section.
