<FIRST>u p PM-Calif-Abortion     08-09 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Calif-Abortion,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Abortion Candidates Gain in Conservative California District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two abortion-rights activists running
in the first state election since the Supreme Court ruling on
abortion emerged the apparent winners in the eight-way race for an
Assembly seat and will meet in a runoff Oct. 3.
   Tuesday's results occurred in a district known for its
conservatism even by Southern California standards.
   ``I believe the abortion issue was the deciding factor in this
election,'' said Jeannine Correia, who was the top vote-getter
among the two Democrats in the race.
   The big winner appeared to be Tricia Hunter, the only
abortion-rights candidate among six Republicans, who made a late
surge to edge past candidate Richard Lyles. Hunter had 14,658 votes
to 14,446 votes for Lyles.
   Some 500 absentee ballots will be counted later this week, said
Deborah Seiler, a spokeswoman for the Secretary of State's office.
Lyles said he was optimistic the absentee votes would reverse the
outcome.
   Voters in the sprawling district, which covers arid sections of
San Diego and Riverside counties, were picking a successor to GOP
Assemblyman Bill Bradley, who died of cancer June 1.
   Voters were free to pick from among six Republicans and two
Democrats, who appeared on the same ballot. None of the candidates
won 50 percent of the vote, forcing a runoff between the top
vote-getter from each party.
   The district is largely Republican _ 54.2 percent to 32.7
percent Democrat _ making the GOP candidate an overwhelming
favorite.
   Hunter, 36 of Bonita, is a nurse and president of the state
Board of Registered Nursing.
   Activists on both sides of the abortion issue regarded the
election as a significant indicator of public opinion. It was the
first election for a state office since the July 3 Supreme Court
ruling in Webster vs. Health Reproductive Services Inc., which gave
states more authority to limit abortions.
   ``If it hadn't been for the $100,000 the nurses association put
into Tricia Hunter's campaign, the abortion issue never would have
gained prominence in this race because she never would have been
seen as a viable candidate,'' said Lyles, a 42-year-old management
consultant from Poway.
   ``It certainly gained more attention than it would have if the
Webster decision hadn't come down, but our research showed most of
the voters were concerned about other issues like water and
education.''
   Correia, an instructor for the developmentally disabled who
lives in Poway, received 3,186 votes while the other Democrat on
the ballot, Stephen Thorne, 34, of Escondido, got 1,256 votes.
Thorne also is pro-choice.
   The district has about 240,000 registered voters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
