<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0486 08-09 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0486,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kaifu Formally Declared Prime Minister After Upper House Delay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD government appointments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the governing Liberal Democratic
Party, Toshiki Kaifu, today was declared prime minister after an
unprecedented parliamentary clash over who should have the job.
   Kaifu, 58, became Japan's third prime minister in 10 weeks after
sex and money scandals and a major loss in upper house elections
forced his two predecessors to step down.
   ``There are many difficulties awaiting the Liberal Democratic
Party, and I will try to work hard and express my frank feelings to
the people,'' Kaifu said after his selection by the lower house,
where his party has a comfortable majority.
   The less powerful upper house supported Socialist Party leader
Takako Doi.
   It was the first time in 41 years that the two houses had
clashed over who should head the government. Under the
constitution, if the houses cannot agree on a prime minister, the
lower house decision prevails.
   On Tuesday, Kaifu was elected president of the Liberal
Democratic Party, which lost public support after the disclosure
last year that the Recruit Co. conglomerate tried to buy political
favors from leading politicians.
   Kaifu has said he received about $110,000 in legal political
donations over five years from the Recruit Co.
   Two people he named today to top posts in the governing party
also have Recruit links. Ichiro Ozawa, the new party
secretary-general, and Shunjiro Karasawa, the new chairman of the
decision-making Executive Council, have acknowledged receiving
legal donations from the company.
   Hajime Tamura, speaker of the lower house, declared Kaifu prime
minister in a brief announcement.
   Ms. Doi said she was not discouraged.
   ``Today, the door was only half opened, but I am determined to
continue to work to fully open this door some day,'' she said.
``Aug. 9 surely reflects the beginning of the end of the long rule
by the LDP.''
   The general secretary of the Socialist Party, Tsuruo Yamaguchi,
said Ms. Doi's upper house victory ``proved we will be seeing a
very unstable political situation'' in coming months.
   ``For the first time in 41 years the wheels of history have
shifted,'' he told The Associated Press. ``Formally, the lower
house choice prevails, but politically the upper house vote has
proven that this administration is only half an administration, and
Kaifu is only half a prime minister.''
   Kaifu said the delay caused by the disagreement between the
houses was a ``severe consequence of our election defeat,'' a
reference to July 23 elections for half the seats in the upper
house.
   In that vote, the Liberal Democrats lost their majority in the
upper house for the first time in their 34-year history.
   Kaifu is succeeding Sousuke Uno, who resigned after the July
vote. He lasted only 69 days in office, losing support because of
reports he kept a paid mistress.
   Earlier today, Uno's Cabinet resigned en masse, clearing the way
for Kaifu to form a new government.
   Uno replaced Noboru Takeshita, who resigned because of the
Recruit scandal, which tainted most of the top figures in the
governing party.
   The tarnished reputations of top Liberal Democratic figures made
it possible for Kaifu to vault into the party leadership, even
though he has little personal clout as a member of a minor party
faction and has not served in top party or government offices.
   But Kaifu brings a more youthful image to Japan's highest office
and has credentials as a reformer. He was a member of the party's
reform committee and an aide to the late Prime Minister Takeo Miki
when Miki was trying to clean up Japanese politics in the 1970s.
   In addition to Ozawa and Karasawa, Kaifu today appointed Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka to be head of his party's Policy Affairs Research
Council. Mitsuzuka, the outgoing foreign minister, has said he did
not have any connections to the Recruit Co.
   Japanese newspapers gave mixed early notices to Kaifu's
election. The liberal-leaning Asahi Shimbun said it hopes ``he will
not stumble badly,'' and it called on Kaifu ``to work for genuine
changes in his own party.''
   The conservative Yomiuri Shimbun's editorial applauded the
debate that accompanied the election for party leader.
   ``After the Cabinet is formed, (Kaifu's) first task should be to
carry out political reform to regain public trust. The very fact
that Kaifu is not a faction leader demonstrates the acceptance of
the need for reform,'' Yomiuri said.
</TEXT>
