<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages-Hezbollah     08-09 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Hezbollah,0419</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Hezbollah Says Obeid Abduction Hurt Efforts to Free Hostages ^By
FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah said today
that efforts to free Western hostages in Lebanon suffered ``their
greatest setback'' as a result of Israel's abduction of a Shiite
Moslem cleric from south Lebanon.
   A statement released by the party's information center said the
July 28 kidnapping of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid and two relatives was
a ``terrorist crime of piracy.''
   Israel has offered to trade Obeid and all Shiite prisoners it
holds for three Israeli servicemen and the 16 Western hostages held
in Lebanon.
   ``The Zionist enemy has suffered a bitter dismay because of his
failure to achieve his objectives from the crime of abducting Sheik
Obeid,'' Hezbollah said.
   ``It is clear that things have backfired adversely on the enemy
after this foolish crime. It has become impossible to release the
Israeli POWs and all ways for a possible swap have been blocked,''
it said.
   ``Moreover, the refusal of the enemy to release Sheik Obeid and
his two relatives, and his linkage of the problem of the Zionist
POWs with that of the hostages might hurt the West and further
complicate the hostage issue,'' the statement added.
   Hezbollah, Iran's main ally in Lebanon, is believed to be the
umbrella group for extremist factions holding most of the hostages.
   ``We contend that past efforts for the release of the Western
hostages in Lebanon is passing through the greatest setback because
of the foolhardiness committed by the racist Zionists, who appear
perfectly willing to sacrfice all others for their selfish
interests,'' the statement said.
   It repeated its urging that the West pressure Israel to free
Obeid.
   Israeli officials have said Obeid admitted under interrogation
that he took part in planning terrorist attacks, including the
abduction of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins in south
Lebanon Feb. 17, 1988.
   Hezbollah said Israel is lying about the reported confessions.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, an extemist group
made up of pro-Iranian zealots, said July 31 that it had hanged
Higgins in retaliation for Israel's refusal to free Obeid.
   Higgins, 44, commanded a 76-man observer unit attached to the
U.N. Peacekeeping force in south Lebanon when he was kidnapped.
   There are eight Americans among the 16 hostages in Lebanon. The
hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
