<FIRST>r i PM-Mozambique-Massacre     08-09 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mozambique-Massacre,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mozambique Says Rebels Massacred 54 Civilians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government rebels armed with
axes, machetes and clubs massacred 54 civilians near the southern
coastal town of Xai-Xai, the official news agency AIM said today.
   The report said most of the victims were kidnapped by guerrillas
of the Mozambique National Resistance in Gaza Province and marched
to Fidel Castro village, just outside Xai-Xai and 90 miles
northeast of Maputo, the capital.
   The civilians were hacked or beaten to death on Monday, AIM
said, quoting a report in Maputo's Noticias daily newspaper. The
report said the fatalities included 13 women and eight children and
that 17 people were injured.
   The attack occurred while rebel leaders and government
representatives were meeting in Kenya in a bid to settle this
country's 12-year-old civil war. Mozambican churchmen, acting on
behalf of their government, met with rebel representatives Tuesday,
but no major breakthroughs were reported.
   No explanation was provided of why the civilians were killed.
However, the rebels, who have been accused of many civilian
atrocities, sometimes take civilians prisoner to carry their
equipment and then kill them afterward.
   No government acknowledges supporting the guerrillas. South
Africa openly supported them until 1984, and some reports say it
continues to do so.
   However, South Africa says it is now abiding by a non-aggression
pact with neighboring Mozambique.
   President Joaquim Chissano says he accepts South Africa's word.
However, officials in Mozambique still believe the rebels receive
help from non-governmental groups in South Africa.
   The war has killed 600,000 people, created more than a million
refugees, and left nearly half the country's 14.7 million people
dependent on food aid.
</TEXT>
