<DOCNO> AP890809-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0950EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ABA-Thornburgh     08-09 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ABA-Thornburgh,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Announces Plans for International Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh says he
wants to establish an international unit in the Justice Department
devoted mostly to curbing drug trafficking.
   ``Often more than 50 percent of my day is devoted to some matter
relating to our international involvement in fighting drug
trafficking, money laundering, international organized crime and
business fraud, environmental depredations, terrorism or
espionage,'' Thornburgh said in a speech Tuesday at the American
Bar Association convention.
   Outlining President Bush's $1 billion crime-fighting package,
Thornburgh said he would seek congressional approval for an
International Affairs Office. He said the State Department has
endorsed the idea.
   A spokesman for the attorney general's office said existing
money could be redirected to fund the unit.
   Thornburgh's proposal to have an office that reports directly to
him to coordinate Justice Department international law enforcement
efforts comes at a time in which the federal battle against drugs
is under great scrutiny.
   The president's drug policy coordinator, William Bennett, is
preparing a congressionally mandated battle plan. As part of the
effort U.S. attorneys around the nation recently issued a report
that placed heavy blame on international drug trafficking for the
30 percent increase in violent crime in the United States in the
past decade.
   Although violent crime is mainly the responsibility of state and
local authorities, ``the federal law enforcement cannot look the
other way while violence, often drug-related, ravages many of our
inner-city communities and subjects innocent citizens to the
cross-fire of turf wars between urban terrorist gangs,'' Thornburgh
said.
   Bush's crime package focused on increasing the penalties for the
criminal use of guns, ending plea bargaining in such cases, hiring
more investigators and prosecutors and doubling the space in
federal prisons, Thornburgh said.
   ``Such a comprehensive approach, if replicated at the state and
local level, can go a long way toward restoring much-needed
credibility to the deterrent capacity of our criminal justice
system,'' he said.
   Regarding drug use and trafficking in the United States,
Thornburgh said the only way to win the ``war on drugs'' was to
``re-establish the values that make a drug-dependent lifestyle an
inadmissible option in this great nation.''
   He praised the military's mandatory drug testing program, saying
it reduced the incidence of drug use from 27 percent in 1980 to 4.8
percent last year. Thornburgh urged more drug testing of American
workers.
   Speaking to reporters after the speech, Thornburgh said the U.S.
Supreme Court's validation of drug-testing meant private and
public-sector employers could begin ``reasonable'' drug-testing
progams.
   ``I think private employers should examine the appropriateness
of it in the workplace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
