<FIRST>r w PM-US-IranAssets 2ndLd-Writethru a0536 08-09 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Iran Assets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0536,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribunal Works Behind the Scenes on Frozen Iran Assets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling to Mohammad sted Mohammed in 13th graf, The
United</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International judges are working quietly to
resolve disputes between the United States and Iran over billions
of dollars of frozen assets, despite bitter differences between the
two nations.
   The members of the Iran-U.S. Claims Tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands, have remained isolated from day-to-day politics. On
Tuesday, the State Department rejected a suggestion that American
hostages in Lebanon could be released if the United States agreed
to release frozen Iranian assets.
   The English-language Tehran Times quoted a source saying Iran
would intercede to gain the release of the American hostages if
Washington gave assurances it would release frozen Iranian assets.
   Eight American hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslems in Lebanon.
   ``The questions of the assets have no connection ... whatsoever
with the hostage issue,'' said State Department spokesman Richard
Boucher. ``This is a legal process. It's a very technical process.
And it's the business of the tribunal to work through the claims
and the cases before them and to work them out.''
   Boucher said the United States refused to consider tying the
hostages' fate to issues before the tribunal but is continuing its
``intensive diplomatic efforts'' to free the captives.
   However, The New York Times quoted an unidentified senior
administration official as saying there may be more room for
maneuvering.
   ``And while we would not give a direct quid pro quo, we would
offer some understanding or agreement that `if you use your good
offices to get the hostages,' we will look favorably on your desire
to get the assets,'' this official was quoted as saying.
   The tribunal, established in 1981 after Iran freed American
hostages held at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran for 444 days, has done
its work in a non-political environment.
   Since it was established, the tribunal _ composed of nine
international judges _ has resolved billions of dollars worth of
claims. Three judges are American, three are Iranian and three are
from other countries.
   The State Department said U.S. nationals have been awarded about
$1.2 billion, while Iranians have received about $118 million.
   The claims, made by banks, companies, individuals and
governments, stem from the 1979 breakdown in diplomatic relations
between the two nations.
   The United States froze billions of dollars of Iranian assets,
including hundreds of millions of dollars worth of military
equipment bought by Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi before his regime
was toppled. Iran also seized U.S. assets.
   When the tribunal was established, the United States transferred
about $9.9 billion in frozen assets to escrow accounts and to Iran.
Washington has little control over that money, the disposition of
which is regulated by tribunal rulings.
   But the Iranians have filed separate claims, amounting to
roughly $12 billion, for military equipment bought under the shah.
The State Department said it doesn't know how much the shah had
already paid, but he had committed to buying $20 billion worth of
hardware.
   Iran has generally followed the tribunal's decisions, making
payments to claimants when ordered to do so, American officials
said. Some American companies, however, have appealed the
tribunal's decisions in U.S. courts, effectively delaying payments,
they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
