<FIRST>r a PM-PretendDrugs     08-09 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pretend Drugs,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Upset by Kids' Selling Pretend Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police discovered a playground stand where
children operated a make-believe drug ring offering bags of grass
clippings and sugar.
   ``We just lost the war on drugs,'' said Capt. Bernie Reilly. ``I
don't care what (President) Bush says, this is bad.''
   Police discovered the stand last week and said children had
recorded pretend drug transactions on a ledger and on scraps of
colored notepaper.
   One note read ``Cocaine, small half-baggie, 55 cents, small
baggies, $1,'' The Patriot newspaper of Harrisburg reported today.
   ``What you have to understand is I have no doubt (they) are
copying their parents. They want to make a lot of money and not
work,'' said Detective Robert Bowman Jr.
   Detective Thomas Capello said one of the worst days of his 11
years of police work came when a city resident handed him a
fishing-tackle box containing the fake drugs, the ledger and a
crudely written IOU.
   The resident said the box came from a 7-year-old boy and a
9-year-old girl at the playground.
   ``It's a shame the kids can't use this kind of intelligence to
better themselves,'' said Police Chief Michael J. DeLeo. ``These
kids were intelligent to set something up like this.''
