<SECOND>PM-Activist Murdered,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Activist Gunned Down In House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A community activist who battled drug dealers in
her neighborhood was killed when her home was sprayed with gunfire
a week after a note warning her to ``back off'' reportedly was
slipped under her door.
   Maria Hernandez, 34, of Brooklyn, was dressing for her job at a
nursing home Tuesday when at least five shots shattered front
windows, police said. She was hit once in the head.
   Her husband, Carlos Hernandez, 33, and 3-year-old son were
unhurt, said Brooklyn Chief of Detectives Francis X. Smith. The
woman's husband said he threw his body on their sleeping son at the
first shot.
   The chief said the victim and her husband were community and
anti-drug activists who ``made a lot of enemies on the block.''
   ``She tried to clean up the drug dealers,'' said a neighbor who
would not give her name.
   A note slipped under the family's door said in Spanish, ``If you
don't back off, you'll be killed,'' Hernandez said.
   A neighbor was charged last week with slashing the victim's
husband several times, allegedly because authorities took away the
neighbor's children after the Hernandezes complained of abuse,
Smith said.
   ``There's a lot of bitterness there, although we don't know if
it's connected to the shooting,'' the chief added.
   Police said they had no suspects.
