<FIRST>r i PM-DanubeEscape     08-09 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Danube Escape,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pregnant Romanian Woman Escapes Across Danube, Gives Birth Hours
Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FRA8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Romanian woman who was nine months
pregnant fled her native country by floating across the Danube in
an inner tube and then hiked six miles before giving birth in a
hospital, a Belgrade weekly reported.
   Camelia Popescu Sorina, a 30-year-old teacher from Turn Severin,
a town near the border, made the escape alone, Ilustrovana Politika
said in its edition published Tuesday. Her husband escaped
separately to Austria, the report said.
   Mrs. Sorina reportedly took a taxi to a town near the border,
telling the driver she was visiting relatives. At about 2:00 a.m.
she inflated the inner tube, secured her documents and some food on
her arm, and started across the river, the magazine said.
   According to the report, she reached the Yugoslav side of the
river after about an hour and waited until morning before
continuing her journey.
   After hiking six miles, Mrs. Sorina reached the town of Kladovo
and boarded a bus for Belgrade.
   The woman went into labor during the ride and gave birth to a
girl in a hospital in the town of Negotin, 65 miles south of
Kladovo, Ilustrovana Politika said.
   Mrs. Sorina's husband, Alexander, was reportedly in a refugee
camp in Austria.
   He and a friend also had tried to escape by swimming the Danube,
but Romanian soldiers shot his friend to death, the magazine said.
It said Sorina then escaped from jail and fled via Hungary to
Austria.
   The magazine said the couple wants to either go to Canada or
settle in Austria.
   According to official statistics, 3,500 Romanians have escaped
to Yugoslavia this year.
</TEXT>
