<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSDrug 1stLd-Writethru a0445 08-09 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organizer of Underground Test of AIDS Drug to Meet with FDA</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, We have, with two grafs to clarify Delaney's
reason for beginning tests; SUBS 5th graf, Compound Q, and penultimate
graf, The only, to clarify that Genelabs drug used only in official trial
and Delaney's drug imported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco organizer of underground
tests of an experimental AIDS drug says he will accept a government
invitation to discuss bringing the trials into the open.
   Martin Delaney, co-director of the AIDS education group Project
Inform, said Tuesday that he found the Food and Drug
Administration's offer to discuss sanctioning the trials a positive
development.
   ``We have said from the beginning we would like to do this in
the open,'' Delaney said.
   The clandestine trial began in April when the drug began to be
viewed by AIDS patients as a last hope. Delaney said he and others
started the unauthorized testing to find out whether it worked
before its uncontrolled use became widespread. Going through the
FDA would have taken too long, he said, but he also has said that
he and others kept the FDA apprised of the study.
   The FDA began investigating the underground trials of Compound Q
in June after a patient died and two others had adverse reactions.
Delaney said it was unclear whether Compound Q was related to the
death.
   Compound Q is a protein from the root of a cucumber-like plant
that has been used for centuries in China to induce abortions and
treat certain tumors. Delaney's group smuggled the drug into the
country with the help of couriers.
   The FDA told Delaney in a letter he received Tuesday to stop the
trials, but offered to talk about conforming them to FDA
regulations.
   ``While we cannot condone the unapproved administration of
trichosanthin (Compound Q), we share your belief that important
drug evaluation information may be generated by community-based
organizations,'' said the letter, signed by Carl C. Peck, director
of the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research.
   ``We therefore want to meet with you, and with other concerned
parties, just as soon as possible, to discuss the possibility of
your participation in a community-based trial ... that complies
with existing law and regulations,'' the letter said.
   The FDA has come to rely increasingly on community-based trials,
a concept pioneered by AIDS activists in which local physicians
administer experimental therapies to AIDS patients and keep
detailed records as part of a safety and efficacy study.
   The underground study of 42 patients is nearly completed.
Treatments with the drug have finished and analysis of the data is
expected to be completed within the month, Delaney said.
   ``We will have enough data to make a reliable judgment to know
whether this is a big deal'' and worth further testing, he said.
   ``After that everybody at FDA is going to have to scratch their
heads and ask why it takes 3{ years under normal (FDA-approved)
circumstances'' to make the same determination.
   If the drug is worth testing further, Delaney said he and others
would bring the data to Washington and talk to FDA officials about
opening FDA-sanctioned, community-based clinical trials.
   The only approved clinical trial of the drug for AIDS patients
is being conducted at San Francisco General Hospital. A highly
purified form of trichosanthin developed at the University of
California at San Francisco and Genelabs Inc. of Redwood City,
Calif. is being used in that trial.
   The FDA says its procedure for approving drugs, including
several levels of clinical trials, is designed to determine
reliably the safety and effectiveness of a drug as well as to
protect those who volunteer to participate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
