<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   08-09 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0524,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Child Dies After Being Shot by Army Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with report that 6-year-old Palestinian
killed. Pickup 8th pvs, `A military...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish settler mistook soldiers in the
occupied West Bank for Palestinians about to attack and fired on
the troops, provoking return fire that killed his infant son, the
army and hospital officials said today.
   Also today, a 6-year-old Palestinian was reported killed when
troops opened fire during disturbances at a Gaza Strip refugee
camp, hospital officials said.
   Businesses in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip were closed
today as Palestinians held a general strike to mark the end of the
20th month of their uprising against Israeli rule.
   The infant, Itai Hamtzani, 19 months, was shot in the head and
died at Tel Hashomer Hospital in Tel Aviv, hospital officials said.
   The army said the soldiers opened fire when the father, Daniel
Hamtzani, 30, stopped his car Tuesday night and shot into a grove
of trees at an army patrol.
   The father was shot in the chest and slightly wounded, and a
second son, Ordan, 4, was slightly wounded, the army said.
   Yousef Ghazi Salameh, 6, was fatally shot in the chest by
soldiers firing from a rooftop during clashes in the Shati refugee
camp, according to an official at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City.
   The army said it was checking the report.
   Since the uprising began in December 1987, 531 Palestinians have
been killed in clashes with soldiers or other Israelis.
Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain.
   Also today, three Palestinian youths were shot and wounded in
clashes with soldiers, two in the Gaza Strip and the third near
Hebron in the West Bank, hospital officials said.
   A military spokesman said the army was checking the reports.
   Graffiti was sprayed across walls in the occupied lands calling
for the intefadeh, or uprising, to continue.
   ``Children of the intefadeh _ their faces are furious, their
games are stones,'' said one slogan signed by the uprising's
PLO-backed Unified Leadership in Gaza City.
   The incident involving the Jewish settler occurred while
Hamtzani was traveling to his home in the settlement of Ariel, an
army announcement said.
   Israel Radio said Hamtzani noticed a light in a grove of trees
and mistook the soldiers for Palestinians lighting a firebomb to
throw at his car.
   Hamtzani backed up and fired into the trees, the radio said. It
noted that news reports earlier Tuesday had reported a firebombing
nearby.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers live among 1.7 million Palestinians
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The settlers have complained
bitterly that the army has failed to protect them from stone and
firebomb attacks during the uprising, and many carry arms.
   Also today, soldiers tore down two houses in Gaza Strip refugee
camps that belonged to men who admitted killing four Arabs
suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities, the army said.
   The army identified the men as Tewfik Abdallah Abu Naim of the
Nusseirat refugee camp and Hassan Ahmed El-Makdama of the Bureij
camp.
   The army has destroyed more than 200 houses of Palestinians and
sealed about 100 others during the uprising.
</TEXT>
