<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-EstoniaStrike     08-09 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Estonia Strike,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Estonians Walk Off Jobs to Protest Residency Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-Estonian factory and transit workers went on
strike today in the Estonian capital to protest a new law adopted
with nationalist support to tighten residency requirements for
elections.
   ``The strike is against yesterday's decision, which the workers
consider discriminatory,'' said Yevgeny Kogan, an ethnic Russian
and leader of Inter-movement. The group is championing the
interests of Russians and other non-Estonians in this small Baltic
republic.
   The law passed Tuesday by the republic's Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, requires residents to live in their district for two
years or anywhere in Estonia for five years before they are allowed
to vote. Candidates for elective office must live in the same place
for five years or in Estonia for 10 years.
   The official Soviet news agency, Tass, said workers in Tallinn
were not unloading freight trains or airplanes and that some auto
transport workers also were on strike. Air freight was paralyzed,
it said.
   Kogan, speaking in a telephone interview from Tallinn, said the
Elamo construction enterprise, the Dvigatel motor works, and the
Kalinin electronics plant were on strike.
   He said workers had struck at least 17 sites, but he could not
give a figure for how many people had walked off their jobs. Tass
said workers at 19 sites were on strike.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population and pushed the law to protect themselves from an influx
of other nationalities.
   But Russians, who make up about a third of Estonia's 1.6 million
people, charge that the law discriminates against non-Estonians
because they tend to be more recent arrivals.
   ``The law guarantees general voting rights to practically all
citizens of Estonian nationality and deprives tens of thousands of
people of other nationalities,'' the government daily Izvestia
quoted a deputy identified as A. Lukoshkin telling the Estonian
Supreme Soviet on Tuesday.
   Non-Estonian workers conducted a warning strike in late July but
ended it when the government agreed to form a commission to look
into their complaints.
   Now, Tass said, the strikers want the Kremlin to set up a
commission to look broadly into Estonia's drive for greater local
control.
   Estonia has adopted a series of measures to increase its local
autonomy and protect ethnic Estonians. The republic has won
approval from Moscow to launch a new economic policy that Estonian
leaders say will even allow the republic to issue its own currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
