<FIRST>r a PM-AlterationSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0551 08-09 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alteration Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0551,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saks Fifth Avenue Settles Tailor Made Sex Discrimination Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `At the ...' with two grafs to ADD number
of stores and agreement to pay plaintiffs' legal fees.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has agreed to
settle a suit _ the legal variety _ by tailoring its policy on
alterations.
   The department store chain said Tuesday it will offer free
alterations on skirts and dresses, as it does already on suits,
blazers and slacks.
   The action settles a sex-discrimination suit filed by feminist
attorney Gloria Allred on behalf of two women charged $40 each for
alterations on dresses. The suit demanded Saks charge equally for
altering men's and women's clothes.
   ``We are now adding several free alterations on dresses and
skirts, and we will continue to review the policy for similar
appropriate revisions,'' said Patricia Fox, spokeswoman for the
Saks Fifth Avenue store in Costa Mesa.
   Saks also agreed to pay the plaintiffs nearly $25,000 in legal
fees, Allred said.
   At the same time, the store chain insisted its previous policy
was fair. Saks ``has never had a double standard so it can't agree
to end one,'' said Bill Acton, spokesman for Saks, which has 45
stores nationwide.
   Acton said Saks had charged for altering dresses and skirts
because they involve more work than men's clothing. There was no
charge for minor alterations to clothing considered ``unisex,''
such as blazers and slacks.
   Allred lauded Saks as ``sensitive to issues that affect women''
and said the stores' response to the suit ``could serve as a model
for the industry.''
   ``Women cannot afford to pay more for alterations than men must
pay,'' she said. ``Charging them more solely on account of their
sex is economically damaging both to their bank accounts and to
their dignity.''
</TEXT>
