<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NewZealand-Plane 1stLd-Writethru a0547 08-09 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Zealand-Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Americans Killed in New Zealand Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CORRECT tourists to four Americans, five
Canadians, ADD State Department IDs on Americans. Pickup 4th pvs, ``A New...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers reached a
snow-covered mountain today where a sightseeing plane crashed and
reported that the four Americans, five Canadians and one New
Zealander aboard all died.
   Nine bodies were recovered today and the workers were searching
in deep snow for the 10th, said Paul Fitzharris, chief police
inspector at Dunedin.
   In Washington, the State Department identified the Americans as
Gerald Burdick of Ridgefield, Conn.; George Palaez of Falls Church,
Va.; Douglas Palm of Flint, Mich., and James Duenas, no hometown
available.
   An earlier unconfirmed report in New Zealand had said the four
Americans were all from Wisconsin. Fitzharris said authorities in
New Zealand were withholding the names and hometowns of the
victims, probably until Thursday.
   A New Zealander was piloting the twin-engine Britten Norman
Islander that went down Tuesday near Mount Aspiring, between
Milford Sound and the town of Wanaka, on South Island, one of two
main islands that make up New Zealand.
   Two alpine rescue dogs were used to help a team of 27 police and
rescue personnel recover the bodies, the New Zealand Press
Association said.
   It said the wreckage was scattered about 4,000 feet up a
mountainside and that dogs were brought to help find bodies buried
in snow.
   Police site controller John Dedlury said the crash had triggered
a small avalanche that slid about 1,000 feet down the slope with
the wrecked aircraft.
   To minimize vibrations that could cause an avalanche, rescuers
used small Squirrel helicopters to carry the bodies away from the
scene.
   Some bodies were found inside the fuselage, but others were
scattered around the slope, Fitzharris said. The nine bodies were
transferred to a mortuary in the southern city of Invercargill.
</TEXT>
