<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Hostages-Hezbollah-Text     08-09 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hostages-Hezbollah-Text,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Text of Hezbollah Statement on Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of Hezbollah's statement
Wednesday on the Western hostages. It was translated from Arabic by
The Associated Press.
   In The Almighty's Name
   The Zionist enemy has suffered bitter dismay because of his
failure to achieve his obectives from the crime of abducting Sheik
Abdul Karim Obeid and his relatives from the struggling town of
Jibchit, the terrorist crime of piracy.
   It is clear that things have backfired on the enemy after his
foolish crime. It has become impossible to release the Israeli POWs
and all ways for a possible swap have been blocked.
   Moreover, the refusal of the enemy to release Sheik Obeid and
his two relatives, and his linkage to the problem of the Zionisventures
over the last 58 years in the delightful Jean de
Brunhoff books.
   ``Babar: The Movie'' brings the exploits of Babar, Queen
Celeste, their children and their friends to the screen. It is a
tale within a tale: Babar tells his four children the story about
how he, Celeste and Zephir the monkey outwitted Rataxes who was
trying to conquer the elephants.
   ``The rhinos don't respect others. They just trust violence and
force,'' said Laurent de Brunhoff, who continues the series of
Babar books created by his father in 1931. ``Babar respects the
other one, and always tries to find a clever way to solve a problem
_ without using force.
   ``The film has a lot of action. In the book, it's a totally
different way of looking or listening to the story. You can take
your time and dream. In the film you're passive, so the action has
to go on the screen more intensely.''
   Dozens of Babar books are in print, including ``The Travels of
Babar,'' ``Babar and the Professor'' and the one that started it
all, ``The Story of Babar,'' in which the young elephant is crowned
king.
   Babar's admirers even include many adults such as children's
author Maurice Sendak, who once wrote, ``If he had come my way, how
I would have welcomed that little elephant and smothered him with
affection.''
   ``I think every kid likes elephants,'' de Brunhoff said in an
interview. ``They may not like them in the same way as teddy bears
or rabbits, but elephants are funny because of their trunks. To
have this elephant living like a man is very, very funny. It's
possible for the kid to assimilate himself to the elephant.''
   De Brunhoff does not avoid the darker side of life. Babar is an
orphan (his mother was killed by a hunter in the first book) and,
in the film, the rhinos capture the adult elephants, leaving their
children behind, weeping. De Brunhoff insisted that showing pain
was essential.
   ``Children like to be in the middle of a drama,'' he said.
``It's not traumatic, they just react with emotion. As long as the
good win and evil is the loser, I think it's fine.
   ``It's bad when it becomes sadistic. Otherwise, I think it's
wrong that only sweetness is good for the kids.''
   De Brunhoff, who grew up in France, was introduced to Babar the
same way as most children: through a bedtime story. In 1931, when
he was 6 years old, his mother told him about a little elephant. De
Brunhoff and his younger brother, Mathieu, were so taken in, they
repeated the story to their father, a painter at the time.
   Jean de Brunhoff quickly filled in details, naming the elephant
Babar and creating Celeste, Zephir and the ``Old Lady'' who takes
care of young Babar after his mother is killed.
   ``He did a book for us with pictures,'' Laurent de Brunhoff
recalled.
   ``He enjoyed the story a lot and everybody in the family liked
it, too. I happened to have two uncles in publishing, so the book
was published and was a success. My father made a second and third
book, and so on.''
   But in 1937, Jean de Brunhoff died of tuberculosis. At the
urging of his uncles, 13-year-old Laurent completed two books
unfinished by his father and eventually devoted himself fulltime to
Babar.
   ``After World War II, I was working as a painter,'' de Brunhoff
said. ``The idea of making a book occurred to me because I loved
Babar; he was my friend. The idea was appealing and I tried to get
close to the style of my father.''
   Laurent eventually added some of his own touches, notably using
his niece as the basis for one of Babar's daughters. A resident of
Connecticut since 1985, de Brunhoff is at work on brand new Babar
stories for an upcoming HBO series on cable-television.
   ``There are times when you have nothing to write about, but
something always comes. You're traveling, in the countryside,
fishing or meeting somebody you're interested in. Maybe someone
tells a joke,'' he said.
   ``I have my studio in the house and a wall where I put some
sketches when I'm working. I also have one or two posters in my
study, but I don't like to be overwhelmed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
