<FIRST>r i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0550 08-09 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Marines Disarm Panamanian Soldiers, Civilians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs raise Noriega's first name and title to second
graf. Pickup 7th graf, ``There was...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another confrontation between U.S.
and Panamanian forces, Marines disarmed a group of Panamanian
soldiers and civilians who followed the Marines into an area the
United States controls.
   The group of 29 Panamanians, including 10 military officers and
lower-ranking soldiers, was briefly detained and then released
after Tuesday's incident, said Mercedes Morris, a spokeswoman for
the U.S. Southern Command.
   She said the soldiers included Maj. Manuel Sieiro,
brother-in-law of Manuel Antonio Noriega, the head of the
Panamanian Defense Forces and Panama's de facto leader. Sieiro
commands the Chorrera military zone, where the incident occurred.
   A local mayor said the Panamanians began following the Americans
after the Marines encountered an anti-American demonstration. The
pro-government news media had called the American maneuvers a
provocation.
   Ms. Morris said the incident occurred west of this capital city
when about 40 U.S. Marines in armored vehicles were carrying out a
reconnaissance exercise on roads leading to the Panama Canal.
   She said the Panamanians ``ventured without authorization into a
military zone'' reserved exclusively for American forces.
   Ms. Morris said the Panamanians were disarmed and held for about
an hour and 15 minutes. She said their weapons, including machine
guns and rifles, will be returned to the Panamanian Defense Forces.
Five Panamanian journalists were in the detained group, but they
refused comment.
   There was no report of any Panamanian resistance.
   A series of such minor incidents have been occurring since
February 1988, when two federal grand juries in Florida indicted
Noriega on drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges.
   The United States has been trying to use economic sanctions and
diplomatic pressure to force out Noriega.
   Most of the Panamanian-American incidents have involved exchange
of a few shots during the night or the arrest of Americans accused
of traffic violations.
</TEXT>
