<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Mozambique-Prisoners     08-09 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mozambique-Prisoners,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,600 Prisoners to be Pardoned, Gov't Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,600 prisoners, including 100
held for security offenses, will be released under a new amnesty
program, the national news agency reported Wednesday.
   Most of those to be released are common criminals sentenced to
two years or less, Justice Minister Ossumane Ali Dauto told the
news agency AIM.
   The goverment also plans to free about 100 people _ Mozambicans
and foreigners _ convicted under security laws covering treason,
armed rebellion, espionage and sabotage, AIM said.
   Dauto described the new measure as an extension of a 1987
amnesty law, saying both were part of the ``efforts to normalize
life'' in a country that has been devastated by 12 years of civil
war.
   The southeast African nation is one of the poorest countries in
the world and almost half of its 14.7 million people are in need of
food aid.
</TEXT>
