<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1238EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Strike     08-09 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Estonians Walk Off Jobs to Protest Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-Estonian factory and transit workers walked
off their jobs in the Estonian capital of Tallinn on Wednesday to
protest a new law that tightens residency requirements for voting
and holding elected office.
   ``The strike is against yesterday's decision, which the workers
consider discriminatory,'' said Yevgeny Kogan, an ethnic Russian
and leader of the InterMovement group that is pushing the interests
of Russians and other non-Estonians in the Baltic republic.
   ``I'm concerned about my children and grandchildren,'' said
Nikolai Chugunov, 42, one of those on strike at the Kalinin
electronics factory.
   ``They started with a language law, and then it's something
else, and et cetera, et cetera, et cetera,'' said Chugunov, a
33-year-resident of Tallinn, who won't be affected by the tighter
residency requirements.
   The strikers sent a committee of four to Moscow to seek a
meeting with Vice President Anatoly I. Lukyanov, Chugunov said.
   Chugunov, a member of the strike committee, said thousands of
workers were on strike at 20 enterprises in Tallinn and two in
Kokhtla-Jarve, an industrial city east of Tallinn.
   He could not give the total number of strikers, but he said that
at some of the largest factories, 3,000 or more workers were off
the job. Pickets blocked the entrances to the factories.
   Kogan, a deputy to the national Congress of People's Deputies
parliament, said in a telephone interview from Tallinn that in
addition the Elamo construction enterprise, the Dvigatel motor
works and the fishing port also were affected.
   Paab Kaala, an editor for official Estonian Radio, said he could
not estimate the number of strikers, but said the strike committee
overstated the number of strikers by several times when it
conducted a warning strike in late July.
   The Tass news agency said workers were not unloading freight
trains, and air freight was paralyzed. Many Tallinn bus drivers
also walked out, but officials brought in buses from other cities
and kept public transportation running.
   No disturbances or demonstrations were reported on the streets.
Kaala said there were no appeals from the government for the
workers to return to their jobs, or any other official statements
about the strike.
   Non-Estonians were protesting passage of a law by the republic's
Supreme Soviet, or parliament, on Tuesday, requiring residents to
live in their district for two years or anywhere in Estonia for
five years before they be allowed to vote.
   Candidates for elective office must live in the same place for
five years, or in Estonia for 10 years.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population, and pushed the law to protect themselves from an influx
of other nationalities.
   But Russians, who make up about a third of Estonia's 1.6 million
people, charge that the law discriminates against non-Estonians who
tend to be recent arrivals.
   ``The law guarantees general voting rights to practically all
citizens of Estonian nationality, and deprives tens of thousands of
people of other nationalities,'' the national daily Izvestia quoted
deputy A. Lukoshkin telling the Estonian Supreme Soviet on Tuesday.
   The warning strike in late July ended when the government agreed
to form a commission to look into their complaints.
   Now, Tass said, the strikers are demanding that the Kremlin set
up a commission to look broadly into Estonia's drive for greater
local control.
   Estonia has become a laboratory for reforms, and the republic
has won approval from Moscow to launch a new economic policy that
Estonian leaders say will even allow it to issue its own currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0511 08-09 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Cools Off Forest Blazes in West</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with lightning warnings withdrawn.
PICKS UP up 8th graf, `About one-third...'; SUBS 17th graf, `Calmer, cooler
...' to UPDATE with containment of largest fire in Washington and acreage
figure.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light rain and cooler weather today led fire bosses to lift the
``red flag'' lightning warnings that went up over the weekend in
the Northwest.
   Firefighters reported progress against dozens of mostly
lightning-caused blazes in Idaho, Washington, Oregon, Utah and
California.
   ``The temperatures have been lowering, the humidity has been
coming up,'' said Rebecca Burkhead of the Boise Interagency Fire
Center, the nation's wildfire command post. ``That's really given
us a handle on a lot of the fires.''
   The fire center replaced its long-running forecast for dry
lightning with a prediction of showers, lower temperatures and
higher humidity across the West.
   Still, 23,000 firefighters were battling blazes on 160,000 acres
of timber and range. More than 220,000 acres have been charred in
mostly lightning-caused fires since July 26.
   Western and central Idaho were still the hardest hit, with 15
major forest fires burning out of control over 104,000 acres. About
9,200 firefighters in Idaho, including hundreds of military troops,
cut fire lines in the rain.
   ``This by no means puts fires out, and it can give people a
false sense of security,'' Payette National Forest Supervisor Sonny
LaSalle said. ``But what it will do is give us the opportunity to
get a lot of line built, get some mop-up done and increase the
security around some of these fires.''
   About one-third of an inch of rain was reported Tuesday at
Lowman, a small mountain community 70 miles north of Boise
virtually leveled by fire 10 days earlier. Several dozen residents
were allowed to return home.
   Bob and Margie Carr's house was spared but everything around it
burned.
   ``The quietness and the peacefulness will come back, but the
scenery is gone,'' said Carr. ``It hurts to see this happen, but
it's happened and you can't do a thing about it.''
   Progress was reported 30 miles to the north, where 2,400
firefighters, including 600 soldiers from Colorado, battled the
18,400-acre Warm Lake fire complex.
   With higher humidity clearing the air of dense smoke, Army
Blackhawk helicopters supplemented Forest Service airpower on fires
still threatening the small town of Warren, about 120 miles north
of Boise.
   Resource losses in Idaho are estimated at more than $75 million
since a July 26 lightning storm scored the state's backcountry with
40,000 strikes, which sparked hundreds of wildfires.
   The 10,000-acre Emmett Mountain Complex and the 7,000-acre
Summit fire in the Hells Canyon National Recreation Area, on the
border with Oregon, should be contained by Thursday, said Thom
Corcoran of the Northwest Interagency Coordinating Center in
Portland, Ore.
   About 3,500 lightning strikes across Oregon started several
fires in the Siskiyou National Forest and a Bureau of Land
Management district in the southwest corner of the state, but rain
limited their size.
   The biggest fire in eastern Oregon, the 23,350-acre Canal fire,
was declared contained Tuesday evening, Corcoran said.
   Calmer, cooler weather helped firefighters contain Washington's
largest wildfire, a 2,500-acre blaze on the Colville Indian
Reservation.
   Crews by Tuesday had contained two southern California fires,
the 15,300-acre Vail fire in Cleveland National Forest and the
7,500-acre Balch fire in Sierra National Forest.
   Officials at the Chalk Creek fire, about 45 miles east of Salt
Lake City, released half the crews mopping up the 1,700-acre blaze.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
