<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LoiteringLawyer     08-09 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Loitering Lawyer,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Street Attorney Beats Loitering Rap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlie Campbell can continue to dispense legal
advice, chess lessons and religious instruction on the sidewalk
across the street from police headquarters.
   The attorney, ticketed on loitering charges after working out of
a van, beat the rap by default Tuesday in 36th District Court when
police failed to appear.
   ``The quick-silvered sparrow slipped the eagle's claw,'' said
Campbell, dressed in his usual courtroom attire _ a suit, tennis
shoes and Detroit Tigers' cap.
   Executive Deputy Police Chief James Bannon said he ordered
Campbell ticketed because his makeshift office, which blocked the
sidewalk with lawn chairs, Bibles and chessboards, was an
``eyesore.''
   ``I'm here to give a smile and a pat on the back for all the
needy people coming out of the jail,'' Campbell said.
   Jay Nolan, Campbell's attorney, said ``This is an important
victory for freedom of assembly. We've made the street safe for
loafers again.''
</TEXT>
