<DOCNO> AP890809-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurityCouncil     08-09 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security Council,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel's First Task to Tackle Health Care Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a Social Security advisory panel
that starts work this week said Wednesday the council's first
mission is to tackle the financing of a health care system that
faces new strains with the aging of the Baby Boom generation.
   Deborah Steelman, head of the Advisory Council on Social
Security, said the current health care system ``overlaps,
duplicates, omits, confuses'' and leaves many needy people without
adequate care.
   ``It is critical that we develop recommendations for a sound,
sustainable health care financing system, one that delivers the
benefits people need, at a price we can all afford,'' she said at a
breakfast meeting with reporters.
   The 13-member advisory council holds its opening meeting on
Thursday and Friday. Such a panel is appointed every four years to
examine issues affecting the Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid
programs.
   Ms. Steelman said the council hopes to issue a draft report on
health care financing by July 1990 and recommendations on the
financing and role of Social Security benefits by December 1990. A
final report to Congress and the Department of Health and Human
Services is due in January 1991.
   Ms. Steelman said the current Medicare system ``is projected to
be insolvent by early in the next century, before the Baby Boom has
even begun to enter retirement.''
   The smaller ranks of people in the generations following the
Baby Boom will make it difficult for them to finance benefits for
the bulge in retirees that precedes them, she said.
   Meanwhile, the current patchwork health care system and various
proposals for reform leave patients ``in a wilderness of health
care finance, trying to figure out what they're covered for, what
they're not,'' she said.
   ``I think there's a growing consensus that we have followed the
meandering path of health care financing just about as long as we
can afford to,'' Ms. Steelman said. ``I personally believe you
cannot fix this system without starting over.''
   Ms. Steelman said she is hopeful the panel will come up with new
ideas on how to restructure the health care system, saying the
council ``can be very radical'' as it searches for solutions.
   ``We can be the spurs in the side of the horse,'' she said.
   Ms. Steelman, a lawyer, was a Bush campaign adviser and is a
former associate director of the Office of Management and Budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
