<DOCNO> AP890809-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Jazz     08-09 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jazz,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saxophonist Benny Carter Saluted at Lincoln Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alto saxophonist Benny Carter, playing and
hearing his compositions at a concert on his 82nd birthday, told
the audience he's ``looking forward to a whole lot more.''
   Carter's alto saxophone style was elegant and tasteful at
Tuesday night's concert in Alice Tully Hall. It was the fourth
concert of six in this year's Classical Jazz at Lincoln Center
series.
   Carter's compositions, and arrangements for the Fletcher
Henderson and Count Basie bands, were important in the development
of big band swing.
   However, Tuesday's concert was uneven. Pianist Hank Jones,
bassist Ray Brown and drummer Bobby Durham started tentatively,
with ``Key Largo.'' Carter joined them for ``Blues in My Heart.''
Ernestine Anderson, who couldn't get rid of a frog in her throat,
sang a tune that sounded country-western and another that called
for a bossa nova beat. The drums were too loud and the bass too
soft.
   Every time the music began to capture a listener's attention,
the master of ceremonies brought the audience back down with long,
irrelevant remarks about the musicians.
   After intermission, Dizzy Gillespie joined the four, and some
starch entered the evening. Carter introduced ``Carter Gillespie
Inc.,'' which he said they recorded in 1976. It included a pretty
melody for their duet. ``Easy Money,'' which followed, swung. And
it was about time.
   Sylvia Sims sang three Carter songs, nicely swinging the first
one, ``Blue Moonlight.'' Carter played his lyrical ``Evening Star.''
   The best part of the evening had Jon Hendricks singing ``When
Lights Are Low,'' ``Cow Cow Boogie'' and ``Doozy'' and Jon
Hendricks and Company singing the arrangement Carter wrote for
Basie of his sparkling ``Meetin' Time.''
   The finale had everybody singing ``All That Jazz'' and Carter,
saying he was overwhelmed, blowing out candles on a cake. Icing
melted by the burning candles splashed onto Carter's suit.
Gillespie whipped out his big handkerchief and played mopup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
