<DOCNO> AP890809-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-09 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Social Scientists Who Opposed Li Peng Expelled From Party, Fired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two leading social scientists who tried in May to
persuade Chinese legislators to oust Premier Li Peng were expelled
Wednesday from the Communist Party and fired from their research
posts.
   Yan Jiaqi, who fled to the West, and Bao Zunxin, who is believed
to have been arrested, are the first party members to be expelled
in the crackdown on dissent that has followed the June 3-4 army
attack on student pro-democracy protesters.
   Many other academics have been arrested or lost their jobs. But
even party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, who was ousted from his
party posts, has been allowed for now to retain his party
membership.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Yan and Bao ``were expelled
because both had stubbornly clung to bourgeois liberalism over a
long period of time.'' Bourgeois liberalism is China's official
phrase for Western-style liberalism.
   They also were fired from their research fellowships at the
prestigious Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
   ``They joined in fanning and organizing the recent student
unrest, turmoil and counterrevolutionary rebellion,'' Xinhua said.
It accused Yan, who recently helped organize a Chinese students'
group in the United States, of continuing to plot against China's
leadership from abroad. A warrant has been issued for Yan's arrest.
   Xinhua did not comment on Bao's whereabouts. Both are among 10
authors whose works can no longer be published or sold.
   Since January, they were prominent participants in an emergent
democratic movement among intellectuals that was crushed when the
army crushed the seven-week student protests.
   Both signed petitions for the release of political prisoners,
and after the students began marching, both spoke out in support.
They signed a May 17 declaration that said China was still ruled by
an emperor, a reference to senior leader Deng Xiaoping, and
published an article in a Hong Kong newspaper calling on China's
legislature to oust Li.
   In othere developments Wednesday:
   _ Foreign-language newspapers went back on sale at Beijing
hotels after being banned nearly a month ago.
   _ Chinese newspapers continued to harshly criticize Zhao, the
ousted party chief, and said Western concepts of human rights were
irrelevant in China. However, Li Ruihuan, the party official in
charge of press and cultural control said the party still wanted
``exploration in art and literature.''
   Hotel managers in Beijing said they did not know why the
state-run China National Publications Import and Export Co. resumed
delivering foreign newspapers this week.
   ``They came as silently as they left,'' said Max Wilhelm,
manager of the Great Wall Sheraton. He said company officials told
him ``things have been settled, but we never got a straight
answer'' about what the problem was.
   The publications company halted its deliveries in mid-July and
seized copies of newspapers and magazines already on hotel racks.
Hotels in other tourist cities were not affected.
   Most of Beijing's major hotels said newspaper delivery resumed
on Monday or Tuesday, but they did not receive any magazines or
Hong Kong-based Chinese-language newspapers.
   ``Maybe the magazines will come tomorrow, and maybe next week
we'll get the television,'' Wilhelm said. The government ordered
hotels to cut their reception of foreign television, including the
U.S.-based Cable News Network, last month.
   Hotels are among the few places Chinese have access to foreign
publications that provide alternatives to the official line on the
protests and crackdown.
   China's leading newspaper, meanwhile, heaped more criticism on
Zhao. In a front-page article, the People's Daily accused Zhao of
using the pretext of ``adapting'' the party to new ideas to weaken
its ideological stance.
   The Beijing Daily ran a commentary arguing that China's human
rights policy is irrelevant because China rejects Western
definitions of human rights.
   ``They make human rights out to be independent of society,'' it
said. ``Therefore, it is a sacrifice any time the authority of the
society, race or country demands necessary limits on the authority
of the individual. They cry out that this is an invasion of human
rights.''
   The commentary said that under Marxism, ``no human rights exist
outside of or independent of society.''
</TEXT>
