<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Subway     08-09 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Subway,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Accept Extra Pay Deal, Tell Drivers To Call Off Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders Wednesday accepted a London subway
management pay offer and told workers to abandon a 15th weekly
strike planned for Thursday.
   Andy Dodds, assistant general secretary of the National Union of
Railwaymen, and leaders of the Associated Society of Locomotive
Engineers and Firemen said they were pleased with the pay offer,
although it represented about one-third of what London Underground
drivers had been seeking for operating trains alone under a planned
phase-out of rear guards.
   Under the mediated offer, the Underground's 2,600 drivers will
receive an extra $27.10 weekly, without having to boost
productivity as management initially had demanded. Drivers had
asked for an extra $104 a week.
   Guards will also receive a separate $9.70 a week raise in the
deal.
   Union leaders said they were confident workers would be on their
jobs Thursday.
   Most of the pay raise would be paid beginning Aug. 1, and the
rest on Jan. 1, when drivers will earn $539 a week.
   A board appointed by the government's Advisory Conciliation and
Arbitration Service last week mediated the agreement between
management and unions as the 15th strike loomed.
   The subway strikes have been one of the longest-running
stoppages during a summer of labor unrest, which also hit passport
offices, railways, London's double-decker buses and other
industries.
</TEXT>
