<FIRST>r w AM-UrbanLeague     08-09 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Urban League,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Bush Talk, Black Leaders Now Want to See Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights leaders said Wednesday it was
kind of President Bush to come talk at their conference, but one
added that it's now time to ``dance with me, Prexy.''
   ``We set the clock yesterday when he started talking and we will
run it until we get here next year,'' John D. Jacob, president of
the National Urban League, told reporters at a news conference
winding up a four-day convention here.
   The Rev. Joseph E. Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, struck a similar note in a concluding
address.
   ``We heard Mr. Bush say the right words. Now he must turn on the
music and dance with me, Prexy,'' he told delegates.
   ``Yesterday's meeting with the president would have been a lot
different if he had some dependency on African American voters,''
Jacob said.
   ``The truth of the matter is that George Bush was being kind
when he came here yesterday. We didn't elect him and he knew that.''
   Bush in his speech committed his administration to combatting
discrimination, but some delegates expressed disappointment that he
did not comment on recent Supreme Court decisions that have eroded
affirmative action.
   ``We must call the administration to sacrament,'' said Lowery.
``We must call it to deal realistically with the terrible problems
we face today.''
   Jacob said he believes Republicans are making modest inroads
among black voters, but added, ``If the Republicans are really
serious about attracting African Americans, they need to get some
programs that deal with the problems, concerns and aspirations of
the African American community.''
   He said Bush was the first president to participate in a
national Urban League conference in a non-election year since Jimmy
Carter in 1977.
   ``This president has at least said that he is willing to debate
the issues and work with us,'' the Urban League president said.
   Jacob said he believed the conference made headway in dealing
with the issue of drugs, which was high on its agenda.
   ``I think this conference has made a major contribution through
raising the consciousness level,'' he said, ``but also putting this
organization on record as being at least one national organization
that is African American that has publicly stated that it intends
to wage war on drugs.''
   Jacob said it was up to the government to stop drugs at the
border and provide drug treatment programs, but, ``We can, in our
own neighborhoods, help put the pushers in jail.''
</TEXT>
