<FIRST>r a AM-NicaraguanDetainee     08-09 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaraguan Detainee,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugee Wants to be Deported, But Red Tape Stalls His Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan refugee being held at an immigration
detention facility is fighting to be deported to his homeland.
   Four months after a judge ruled that Samuel Thomas should be
sent back to Nicaragua, he remains at the Krome Avenue detention
center. He's even willing to buy his own ticket back to Managua,
the Nicaraguan capital.
   ``I can't stand it. I'm desperate to see my family,'' said
Thomas, 31. ``I want to go, but they don't want to send me.''
   Of the dozen or so Nicaraguans at Krome, Thomas is the only one
who wants to go back, he said.
   Thomas' case is bogged down in Washington, where it is under
review by the Immigration and Naturalization Service and the
Justice Department.
   Since 1987, it has been standard for Nicaraguans' deportation
orders to be checked by Justice Department officers to give
asylum-seekers an extra level of review before they're forced out
of the country, said Ken Powers, assistant director of deportation
for the Miami district of INS.
   ``I would have to admit it's bureaucracy,'' Powers said of
Thomas' situation. ``We've added additional steps to protect the
rights of Nicaraguans going to back to Nicaragua. This process is
very cumbersome.''
   But added Powers, ``It's ridiculous to have the system prevent a
guy from going back.''
   Thomas arrived March 15 at Miami International Airport with a
valid visa but without documentation as a cruise ship employee. He
initially asked for asylum at the airport but dropped that by the
time he had a hearing April 11.
   The INS ruled him excludable, and Thomas didn't appeal.
   At that point, Powers said, even though it had been noted in
Thomas' file that he wanted to be deported, his records were
shipped to Washington along with those of people fighting
deportation.
</TEXT>
