<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     08-09 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Announces New Military Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government has set up
more regional military courts and extended martial law powers to
junior army commanders, according to an official Burmese report.
   The report, issued Tuesday, came on the first anniversary of the
beginning of a natiowide uprising for democracy, which Gen. Saw
Maung crushed in September after he took power.
   A July 18 order empowered the commanders of the Rangoon region
and northwestern and central areas to establish military courts to
try martial law violators. These were already put into effect in
the capital, Rangoon.
   The new courts, which can impose sentences ranging from three
years in prison to death, have now been set up in the northwestern
and central military administrative districts, the official Radio
Rangoon said Tuesday, quoting new orders dated Aug. 2. A transcript
of the report was available Wednesday in Bangkok.
   The new orders also extended the authority to dispense martial
law to junior commanders in both areas.
   On Aug. 8, 1988, tens of thousands of people took to the streets
of Rangoon to protest a quarter century of harsh socialist rule.
The following day, troops shot and killed hundreds of unarmed
protesters.
   Although Saw Maung has promised to hold multiparty elections
next year, martial law forbids open political dissent.
   However, Western diplomats in Rangoon reported a number of small
protests by students who braved martial law to commemorate last
year's protests.
   One diplomat reached by telephone from Bangkok on Wednesday
quoted a witness who reported seeing a student clubbed on the head
with a rifle butt Tuesday. Troops at the time were reportedly
dispersing about 70 demonstrators and 200 bystanders in the center
of Rangoon.
   Five people were arrested, said the diplomat, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The diplomat said there were also reports from the northern city
of Mandalay that several thousand monks had mounted a protest
Tuesday.
   He said groups of up to 300 monks walked in single file past
heavy concentrations of troops brought into the city to ward off
protests. The action was interpreted as ``a pointed protest showing
the feeling of the monks against the regime,'' the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
