<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:Abyss     08-09 0894</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Abyss,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tossed in a Storm of Sequels, `The Abyss' Surfaces as an Original</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Abyss'' could well be this summer's most
ambitious, most problematic and, finally, most fascinating movie.
   ``The Abyss'' features no major stars, and while the rest of the
film season has unfolded nearly seamlessly, this $43 million
project was a magnet for miscues. It missed its original release
date by a month, and because its rough cut ran 40 minutes long, a
number of important expository and spectacular effects scenes were
cut.
   But 20th Century Fox's ``The Abyss'' finally arrived, opening
Wednesday on 1,550 screens.
   The cast and crew of this technically uncompromising adventure
movie endured 3{ months of principal filming, 40 percent of it
underwater. It stars Ed Harris (``The Right Stuff'') and Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio (``January Man'').
   So elaborate is the film's look and sound that almost everyone
from director James Cameron to sound mixer Lee Orloff labored seven
days a week, every week, throughout the first half of 1989.
   The final print of ``The Abyss'' was completed just hours before
its first media preview, on July 28. ``The ringing sound of
hysteria was always just around the corner,'' said Cameron, the
writer and director of such acclaimed and personal techno-thrillers
as ``The Terminator'' and ``Aliens.''
   ``It seems t
cut is a crucial sequence explaining that the story's underwater
aliens are worried about nuclear war. That's why the sub crashes,
the hurricane suddenly materializes and a now deleted tidal-wave
assault develops.
   ``Jim had a huge story to tell,'' Mastrantonio said. ``And
there's a whole lot that's been cut. But given the time limitations
of any normal film ... I think that he's told it cohesively.''
   Cameron and Hurd say, too, they have succeeded in assembling a
persuasive and cautionary tale about common people facing uncommon
circumstances.
   ``A film should always try to take somebody somewhere, whether
it's emotionally or physically transporting one to another place,''
Cameron said. ``I see this as much of an emotional journey as a
physical one.
   ``The great thing about film is that you can really do anything.
You can show the biggest, most spectacular thing in the world, and
in the next split second you can focus down to the most microcosmic
human moment.
   ``The ocean is for many people a great primal fear,'' the
director said. ``It's a very powerful thing, it can be incredibly
fickle _ weather and currents can turn on you instantly _ but it's
also the source of life and a place of incredible wonder.''
</TEXT>
