<FIRST>r a AM-Quake     08-09 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quakes Reported in California, Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANZA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake centered in a remote
southern section of the San Bernardino National Forest was barely
felt in nearby desert resort communities Wednesday, authorities
said.
   ``I didn't feel a thing and didn't hear about any telephone
calls,'' said a police dispatcher in Palm Springs, about 10 miles
away from the epicenter.
   The 6:42 a.m. temblor measured 3.3 on the Richter scale, and its
epicenter was pinpointed near the forest's southern boundary, said
Robert Finn of the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
No damage was reported.
   Also Wednesday, a minor earthquake shook south-central Utah, but
no damage or injuries were reported, the University of Utah
Seismograph Stations said.
   Spokeswoman Sue Nava said the 9:28 a.m. MDT quake, measuring 3.3
on the Richter scale, was centered seven miles south-southeast of
Beaver.
   On Tuesday, a strong earthquake struck the San Francisco Bay
area, 400 miles north of the quake near Anza. That 1:13 a.m.
temblor had a magnitude of 5.2.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude, or the height of quake-generated shock waves recorded
on a seismograph.
   Some experts say the actual amount of energy released may be 30
times greater.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
