<FIRST>u w PM-China-Dependents     08-09 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dependents,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Authorizes Return of Dependents to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 260 American dependents of U.S.
government personnel in China who were evacuated from that country
two months ago have been authorized to return, the State Department
said today.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the decision was
based on an assessment that the security situation has improved in
China. But she said the State Department is continuing to recommend
that Americans defer non-essential travel to China until further
notice.
   The dependents were ordered home on June 7 in the wake of
``indiscriminate firing'' by Chinese troops on a compound for
diplomats and other foreign residents.
   The shooting incident prompted a strong U.S. protest to Chinese
authorities. Ms. Tutwiler was unable to say whether the issue was
resolved to the satisfaction of U.S. officials.
   The evacuation was ordered three days after protestors who had
occupied Tienanmen Square in Beijing for weeks were routed by
Chinese military forces.
   Other officials said almost all dependents of other foreign
diplomatic missions have since returned to China. In addition,
about 150 of the estimated 350 U.S. businessmen who left China in
June in China have returned, they said.
