<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0637 08-09 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0637,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Press Expresses Willingness to Help on Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to ADD dropped word ``and.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran will help free Western hostages if
Israel releases an abducted Shiite Moslem cleric and if four
Iranians missing in Lebanon, long thought to be dead, are located,
a Tehran newspaper said Wednesday.
   Abrar, the Farsi-language paper, did not mention a condition set
by the English-language Tehran Times on Tuesday: freeing billions
of dollars in Iranian assets the United States froze a decade ago.
   President Bush said Tuesday the assets, which include arms and
military equipment ordered before the fundamentalist Shiite
revolution, could not be linked to the hostage issue. Sixteen
Western captives are held in Lebanon, including eight Americans.
   Kayhan, another Iranian daily, said Wednesday that Iran would
rather ``wash its hands'' of its assets than compromise its
``ideological principles,'' the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
   It quoted Abrar as saying: ``Iran has repeatedly announced its
readiness to exert its influence ... to help solve the hostage
issue in response to any sign of goodwill by the West.''
   The four Iranians are believed to have been killed when they
disappeared in 1982.
   President Hashemi Rafsanjani is seen as a pragmatist who wants
improved relations with the West as a means of getting help to
rebuild from the eight-year war with Iraq. He is opposed by the
radical faction of Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, to which
compromise with the West is anathema.
   In the past, Rafsanjani has linked hostage releases the three
Iranians and a Lebanese driver with an Iranian passport who were
kidnapped by Christian militiamen in north Lebanon in July 1982.
   All four are believed dead. Iran Iran wants the case
investigated and publicized to show it, too, has been a victim of
kidnappers.
   Israel kidnapped Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, 33, from his home in
southern Lebanon on July 28. It has offered to trade him and the
estimated 300-400 Shiite prisoners it holds for three 3 Israeli
soldiers held in Lebanon and the Western hostages.
