<DOCNO> AP890809-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1451EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonists     08-09 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonists,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Britain-Soviet Balloon Flight Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Britain and the Soviet Union work toward a
joint space venture, two veteran pilots plan to link the two
countries the old-fashioned way: by balloon.
   Don Cameron, a record-breaking balloon pilot, said Wednesday he
will team up with Lt. Gen. Gherman Titov for the 1,400-mile trip
from Bristol in southwest England, across the North Sea, Denmark,
southern Sweden and the Baltic Sea to Leningrad.
   Titov, 53, was the backup man for Yuri Gagarin, the first man in
space on April 12, 1961, and Titov became the world's first
multiple-orbit astronaut by circling the Earth 17 times in the
spaceship Vostok 2 on Aug. 6-7, 1961.
   ``We're not trying to give the world a political message for
doing our flight,'' said Cameron, 50. ``It's just an interesting
sporting objective.
   ``I'm one of the world's great cowards, so we have tried to
remove as much of the risk as possible,'' he added. ``But it's
quite a long flight, a lot of it over the sea.''
   Depending on the weather, the flight will begin as early as the
second week of September, and is expected to take four days.
   The two men will travel beneath the 60,000-cubic-foot hot air
balloon in a bright yellow, 100-pound gondola bristling with
satellite navigational equipment and radios to communicate with
Cameron's home base in Bristol, a Soviet base and air traffic
controllers.
   Titov, who at 25 was the youngest person in space, was selected
by the Soviets from among 200 volunteers for the balloon flight.
   A similar process of weeding through volunteers was undertaken
to select Britain's first cosmonaut for an eight-day mission to the
Soviet space station Mir in 1991. Medical tests on 150 finalists
began Monday.
   Cameron has yet to meet his copilot.
   ``Titov has a tremendous amount of experience in many things,
but probably not ballooning,'' he said. ``I'll take over for the
takeoff and landing, which are the tricky bits. Control in the air
is fairly easy.
   ``I've been learning little scraps of Russian. I don't know what
Titov's English is like, but I'm sure we'll get by.''
   Non-stop gas balloon flights between Western Europe and Russia
last took place around the turn of the century when Count Henry de
la Vaulx made several flights from Paris. In 1900, he smashed the
long-distance balloon record by floating 1,193 miles from Paris to
Korosticheff in Russia.
   Cameron claims to be the first balloonist to cross the Sahara
Desert and the Swiss Alps in the early 1970s. He lost out on the
first successful trans-Atlantic helium balloon crossing when his
craft ditched 108 miles off the western French coast. Weeks later,
in July 1978, an American team set the record.
   A balloon designer and manufacturer, Cameron approached Soviet
authorities two years ago and got the OK for his West-East
adventure in July 1988.
   A balloon factory that has since opened in Moscow will begin
turning out Cameron-designed balloons by the end of the year to be
used to carry tourists on sightseeing trips over historical sites
in the Soviet Union, he said.
   Later on Wednesday, a second British-Soviet balloon venture was
announced by Thunder and Colt, a British balloon manufacturer.
   The company said it is building a hot air balloon for a flight
from its headquarters at Oswestry, Shropshire, to Minsk. No date
has been set for the flight, which is still seeking financial
sponsorship, said Chris Kirby, the company's marketing director.
   The Thunder and Colt balloon would be flown by two British
businessmen, Oliver Holmes and Richard Barr, the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
