<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1456EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UnearthedCadavers     08-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unearthed Cadavers,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buried Medical School Bodies Give Glimpse of Lost Profession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As grave robbers go, Grandison Harris was
pretty good.
   Purchased as a slave in 1852 by the Medical College of Georgia,
Harris was a ``resurrection man,'' who dug up new graves in black
cemeteries, cracked open the crude wooden coffins, bagged the
contents and delivered them to the medical college for dissection
by students.
   A century after a law change that made the craft obsolete,
Harris' handiwork is coming to light as workers renovate the
basement of the old medical college building.
   This week, about 40 boxes of bones from 19th century dissections
were taken to Atlanta to be studied at Georgia State University for
insights on the health, nutrition and lifestyles of Georgians in
the 1800s. Campus officials are unsure how many bodies are in the
boxes.
   Student volunteers also collected coins, buttons, bottles,
surgical instruments, test tubes and clothing from the earthen
basement of the 1835 building.
   ``I can think of no other archaeological find in the U.S.
remotely like it,'' said Robert L. Blakely, a Georgia State
University anthropologist. ``There may be other medical colleges
that have things like this in their cellars, but they haven't been
discovered.''
   Records by George M. Newton, dean of faculty at the college in
the mid-1800s, indicate that grave-robbing was a booming business
until 1887, when the laws changed.
   Grave-robbing was often the only way medical schools could get
around laws that equated human dissection with desecration.
   Newton bought 2,000 gallons of whiskey in the 1850s and made
references to transactions such as, ``Joe for subject, $10.''
   The ``subjects'' were preserved in Newton's whiskey until the
time came for them to provide medical students vital lessons on the
basics of human anatomy.
   The bodies were mostly blacks because ``when you have a large
population of a depressed class, you're going to have fewer
problems robbing their graves than the mayor of Augusta,'' said
Russell R. Moores, a hematologist and historian of the medical
college.
   A manuscript on the resurrection man's career by the late Lane
Allen, a professor of anatomy at the college, recounts how Harris
performed his job, digging into graves by moonlight, smashing the
crude wooden coffins with an ax, removing the ``subject'' and
placing it in a sack, which he carried to the college in a
horse-drawn cart.
   Sometimes, on his return, Harris would stop for a drink.
   One tale recounts how a student once removed the corpse while
Harris was in the saloon and climbed in the sack. He moaned in a
ghostly voice when Harris came back to the cart: ``Grandison, I'm
cold! Buy me a drink.''
   Legend says Harris replied: ``Get your own drink.''
   Harris continued to work for the college after the Civil War
provided his freedom, at a salary of $10 to $15 a month. He retired
as a janitor at the college in 1905 on a pension of $10 a month.
   Blakely said the Georgia State researchers believe the bones
``will cover the entire period the medical college was in that
building, from the 1830s to the early 1900s.''
   Blakely said the remains eventually will be returned to the
medical college, where they will be cremated next spring with the
remains of current dissections and buried with them in an annual
memorial service.
</TEXT>
