<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-09 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Guerrillas Violating Moslem Ban on Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday that
Moslem guerrillas were violating Islamic law by killing civilians
with rocket attacks during the current holy month.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani criticized the
guerrillas for calling themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy
warriors, while rocketing the capital during the month of Muharram.
   ``They claim to be the advocates of Islam and they pay no heed
to these holy days, and they fire rockets on civilian targets and
houses and they claim they are trying to kill communists,'' he said.
   Amani said Moslems mourning the death of a grandson of the
prophet Mohammed during this month are not permitted to kill other
Moslems.
   However, Moslems always are under a religious ban against
killing other Moslems.
   Rockets have been crashing into Kabul almost daily since late
June. The Soviet-backed Marxist government blames the guerrillas
for the attacks.
   Most of the rockets have struck civilian areas. At least 281
people have been killed and 745 injured in the rocket attacks and a
car bombing, according to U.N. sources.
   On Wednesday, no rockets were reported to have hit Kabul.
Intermittent thuds from government artillery could be heard,
however, and missiles heading for targets outside the capital could
be seen flashing across the sky.
   Amani said the guerrillas killed 16 civilians in a rocket
barrage late Tuesday.
   One of 10 rockets hit a military weapons and ammunition depot in
northwest Kabul, setting off a chain reaction of explosions that
lasted for 3{ hours.
   U.N. sources said one man who lived about 500 yards away was
killed.
   Amani said 1,200 people were evacuated from the area, but he
said the 16 casualties he reported were caused by rockets that hit
elsewhere.
   In other military action over the previous 24 hours, air force
planes destroyed a 1{-mile guerrilla arms convoy in Logar province
south of Kabul, Amani said. He said trucks that tried to return to
Pakistan, where the most powerful rebel forces are headquartered,
were also destroyed.
   Amani had no further details, and the report could not be
independently confirmed.
</TEXT>
