<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan Bjt   08-09 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kaifu Chosen New Prime Minister, Works at Regaining Public Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governing party leader Toshiki Kaifu became prime
minister Wednesday after an unprecedented battle in parliament, and
he immediately began trying to build public support by naming two
women to the Cabinet.
   Women voters, angry over a new sales tax and a sex scandal
involving Kaifu's predecessor, were seen as a major factor in the
Liberal Democratic Party's poor showing in parliamentary elections
July 23.
   In that vote, the Liberal Democrats lost their majority in the
upper house for the first time in their 34-year history.
   The opposition Socialists delayed Kaifu's election by supporting
Socialist Party leader Takako Doi on Wednesday. The Liberal
Democrats hold a majority in the more powerful lower house, which
chose Kaifu. Under the constitution, the lower house decision
prevailed.
   It was the first time in 41 years the chambers had clashed over
leadership of the government.
   ``Today, the door was only half opened, but I am determined to
continue to work to fully open this door some day,'' said Ms. Doi.
   Socialist Secretary-General Tsuruo Yamaguchi told The Associated
Press that ``politically, the upper house vote has proven that this
administration is only half an administration, and Kaifu is only
half a prime minister.''
   Kaifu told reporters the upper house's move was a ``severe
consequence of our election defeat'' July 23.
   ``There are many difficulties awaiting the Liberal Democratic
Party, and I will try to work hard and express my frank feelings to
the people,'' he said.
   Kaifu became Japan's third prime minister in 10 weeks. Noboru
Takeshita resigned in June to take responsibility for an
influence-peddling scandal involving the Recruit Co. conglomerate.
   His replacement, Sousuke Uno, stepped down after 69 days amid
allegations he kept paid mistresses.
   Kaifu, 58, considered a reform-minded politician, was chosen to
lead the party's rebuilding efforts because of his relative youth
and non-involvement in the Recruit scandal, which tainted most
senior leaders. He was chosen party leader Tuesday.
   Kaifu has acknowledged receiving about $110,000 in political
donations from Recruit but said they were legal.
   The company has been accused of giving political donations and
selling bargain-priced stock to leading politicians in exchange for
political favors.
   Kaifu was elected only to fill the remaining three months of
Takeshita's original term. Whether he can keep the post after
October depends on how well he can establish a power base and
brighten the party's image.
   In addition to lacking his own power base in the party, Kaifu, a
former education minister, has little experience in the crucial
areas of foreign affairs and finance.
   The 20-member Cabinet was carefully crafted to distribute posts
among major party factions controlled by senior Liberal Democrats,
despite Kaifu's comment Tuesday that factions are ``an evil.''
   His new Cabinet includes the first woman non-politician to serve
as a government minister _ Sumiko Takahara, an economics specialist
who became head of the Economic Planning Agency. Another woman,
lawmaker Mayumi Moriyama, will head the Environment Agency.
   Eiji Suzuki, head of the Japan Federation of Employers'
Associations, told Kyodo that two women in the Cabinet would
contribute significantly to the revitalization of the party.
   Homemakers were particularly incensed at the 3 percent sales tax
passed in April.
   Five Cabinet posts went to the largest party faction, controlled
by Takeshita, and four each to the next three largest factions.
   Ryutaro Hashimoto, most recently the Liberal Democrats'
secretary-general, was named finance minister, while Hikaru
Matsunaga, a former prosecutor, was given the important post of
international trade minister.
   Taro Nakayama, a former doctor, was named foreign minister, and
former Transport Minister Tokuo Yamashita was named chief Cabinet
secretary, the main government spokesman.
   Ichiro Ozawa was named the new party secretary-general, and
Shunjiro Karasawa became the new chairman of the party's
decision-making Executive Council. Both have acknowledged receiving
legal donations from Recruit.
   Opposition politicians reveled in the upper house rejection of
Kaifu, calling on the Liberal Democrats to dissolve the lower house
for new elections and scrap the new sales tax.
   Business leaders, who traditionally support the Liberal
Democrats, urged the party to push forward with reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
