<FIRST>r a AM-LetterCarrier     08-09 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Letter Carrier,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter Carrier Has 31 Years of Experience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Ray Adkins has carried the mail
for 31 years, and even his wife's illness couldn't keep him away
from a ceremony Wednesday for the centennial of the the National
Association of Letter Carriers.
   Adkins, 56, and Charleston letter carrier Terri Lynn Page
delivered a 3-by-5-foot postcard to the ceremony outside the
downtown post office.
   Stamps have been affixed at each of the 47 states where the
postcard has been canceled, and it will be sent via Express Mail to
the remaining states, ending up in Wisconsin on Aug. 30, the 100th
anniversary of the founding of the postal workers' union in
Milwaukee.
   Adkins' wife of 40 years, Audrey Faye, entered St. Francis
Hospital on Wednesday for cancer treatment, but he said she
insisted that he attend the ceremony.
   ``She didn't want me to miss it,'' Adkins said. ``I've been with
her since she was 16.''
   Adkins, whose route includes downtown Charleston, says one of
the biggest changes since he began work has been the amount of mail.
   ``There's a lot more mail to be delivered _ I'd say at least
triple,'' he said. ``There's heavier volume _ more magazines, more
bulk business rate, which we have to have to stay alive.
   ``They told me 20 years ago it would be like this. That's why I
never slowed down.''
   The Chesapeake, Ohio, native said he and seven of his eight
brothers served in the armed forces and went to work for the
federal government.
   ``I just love being in uniform,'' he said.
   He doesn't even mind working in bad weather.
   ``I kind of enjoy it,'' he said. ``I get used to it _ even the
rain. I put a cape on and look like Batman. People splash me,
though. I think they want to see me duck under that cape.''
</TEXT>
