<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Uprising     08-09 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Uprising,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill Two During Protests, Third Arab Found Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a man and child
in a Palestinian refugee camp Wednesday during demonstrations
marking 20 months of the Arab rebellion, hospital officials said.
   A third Arab was found dead, and Arab reports said he was killed
by Israeli settlers.
   The deaths raised to 533 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli soldiers or settlers since the uprising began in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in December 1987. Thirty-eight
Israelis have died in the violence.
   Officials at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City said 6-year-old Yousef
Ghazi Salameh and 23-year-old Ziad Mohammed Bannat were shot to
death during daylong clashes in the Gaza Strip's Shati refugee camp.
   Hospital officials said Salameh was shot in the heart and quoted
the boy's family as saying a soldier on a rooftop had fired at him.
Bannat died later of gunshot wounds to the stomach and chest, the
officials said.
   The army spokesman's office confirmed Salameh's death but said
he was 8. The office said Bannat's body was taken from the hospital
for burial before the army could confirm the cause of death and
that it was checking further.
   Arab hospital reports said at least 19 Palestinians were wounded
in Shati. Four other Palestianians were wounded elsewhere in the
territories in clashes with Israeli troops, Arab reports said.
   The army confirmed five wounded and said it was checking other
reports.
   The riots at Shati occurred as Palestinians throughout the
occupied lands mounted a general strike to mark the end of the 20th
month of their uprising against Israeli occupation. The territories
were captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Shops and offices were closed, and public transportation was
shut down.
   A nurse in the West Bank city of Hebron said the body of
17-year-old Nidal Ibrahim Mesk was found on a major city
thoroughfare near the Ansar Mosque. He had been shot twice in the
head, the nurse said.
   Arab reporters said Mesk and several friends had been throwing
stones at passing Israeli vehicles, including a state-run passenger
bus and a car carrying Jewish settlers. Passengers from the bus
opened fire as the youths fled, one of the youths told reporters.
   Also Wednesday, an Israeli infant died from wounds suffered in
an exchange of gunfire between his father and soldiers, officials
at Tel Aviv's Tel Hashomer Hospital said.
   The army said troops accidentally shot 19-month-old Itai
Hamtzani on Tuesday night after his father, a West Bank Jewish
settler, opened fire on an army patrol in a grove of trees.
   Israel radio said 30-year-old Daniel Hamtzani fired because he
thought the soldiers were Palestinians lighting a firebomb.
   The father and a second son, 4-year-old Ordan, were wounded, the
army said.
</TEXT>
