<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     08-09 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Premier Holds Talks With U.N. Team, Rejects U.N. Peace
Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Hun Sen met Wednesday with a
U.N. delegation and rejected a U.N. role in resolving the Cambodian
war until the world body stops backing the guerrilla resistance.
   The pro-Vietnamese leader and more than a dozen Cabinet
ministers and military chiefs held two hours of talks with the
team, sent by an international conference in Paris on Cambodia.
   The team arrived Monday to gather technical information for the
possible formation of an international body to monitor the
Vietnamese troop withdrawal and a proposed truce. Vietnam has
promised to pull all of its troops from Cambodia by the end of
September.
   After the talks, Hun Sen told reporters his government was
helping the team because it did not want to block the peace
process. He said this did not mean his government had accepted a
U.N. role in the process.
   ``We cannot accept the role of the United Nations if the United
Nations continues to accept the role (of the Khmer Rouge) in any
political issue of Cambodia,'' he said.
   ``We shall study the role of the U.N. if the U.N. leaves the
Cambodian seat vacant,'' he said.
   The Khmer Rouge is the largest group in the three-party
guerrilla coalition that holds Cambodia's seat in the United
Nations.
   Hun Sen said he rejected a guerrilla offer that the Phnom Penh
government share the seat with the guerrillas.
   ``I said that I cannot sit on the bloodied seat of Democratic
Kampuchea,'' he said, using the name of the resistance government.
   The Paris talks, which opened July 30, have not produced
substantial progress because Hun Sen rejects guerrilla demands that
the Khmer Rouge be included in a transitional government.
   The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
before Vietnam invaded in late 1978, ousted it from power, and
installed the current Phnom Penh government.
   The 15-member U.N. team, led by Lt. Gen. Martin O. Datset of
Norway, is to visit about eight provinces during its weeklong tour.
   On Wednesday, the team visited northeastern Stung Treng
province. On Tuesday, it inspected what is expected to be a major
route for Vietnam's pullout, Highway No. 1 from Phnom Penh to
Vietnam's southern Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   The team includes experts in aviation, communications,
engineering and other fields. They said the task of monitoring the
pullout and supervising the peace would be complex in such an
undeveloped country.
   Wing Cmdr. Greg Weekes, an aviation expert from Australia, noted
Cambodia has few main highways and that many roads are impassable
during the monsoon season.
   Another expert, who requested anonymity, said the scarcity of
telephones and other communications would make it difficult to
report truce violations.
   He said the monitoring body must be much larger than the several
hundred members suggested by Hun Sen if the predominantly jungle
war is to be kept in check.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
