<FIRST>r a AM-DeathRowInterview     08-09 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Death Row Interview,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condemned Man Calls Execution `Spiffy'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted killer said he was depressed
when he won a reprieve from Florida's electric chair and ``can
hardly wait'' for his execution.
   ``I do not have a death wish,'' James William Hamblen said. ``I
would say I don't care about living as distinguished from I want to
die.''
   ``I can hardly wait to sit in Old Sparky (the electric chair).
I'm curious about it,'' Hamblen, 60, said in an interview Tuesday
with The Florida Times-Union at Florida State Prison.
   Hamblen was condemned for the 1984 shooting death of Laureen
Jean Edwards during a robbery at her lingerie store. He was
sentenced to death after firing his public defender and pleading
guilty. He also admitted an earlier murder in Texas.
   ``I'm not the least bit concerned about electrocution. I think
it's spiffy,'' Hamblen said.
   ``If you've got to go _ why not? It's better than AIDS, better
than cancer of the colon, better than slipping into senility day by
day. I can think of a lot more ways I'd rather not die,'' he said.
   Hamblen said he was ``let down'' when public defenders won an
indefinite stay from the U.S. Supreme Court on July 18 just five
hours before he was to be strapped into the electric chair.
   Hamblen denied he was legally insane or incompetent, as defense
lawyers maintained.
   ``I might be wacko ... but within the legal definition, I'm
completely confident I know what I'm doing,'' Hamblen said.
   The inmate said he could commit suicide in his cell if he wanted
to, but doesn't want to. He said the problem with suicide is that
people think the victim is unable to cope with life.
   ``I just don't care to cope,'' he said.
   Hamblen served seven years in the Marines and saw combat duty in
Korea before he was dishonorably discharged in 1953. He was married
and divorced and spent 20 years in prison on rape and burglary
convictions before his release in 1978.
   Hamblen said he returned to crime in 1984 when he killed a woman
he described as a ``beer-drinking buddy'' in Texas. He was fleeing
the murder charge when he robbed Mrs. Edwards' store.
</TEXT>
