<FIRST>r a AM-VincennesMonument     08-09 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes Monument,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain Pays Tribute to Hostage at Dedication</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINCENNES, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former commander of the Navy vessel
that shot down an Iranian airliner last year paid tribute Wednesday
to Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, who was taken hostage in
Lebanon and is believed dead.
   Capt. Will C. Rogers, during a dedication ceremony for a
monument to the USS Vincennes, called Higgins and his wife, Robin,
``comrades in arms, American heroes and friends who exemplify the
Marine Corps motto, `Always Faithful,' whatever the cost.''
   ``Those costs, which recently (were) demonstrated, can be
brutally harsh,'' Rogers said at the dedication of the USS
Vincennes Memorial Monument near the banks of the Wabash River.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Higgins acknowledged ``a virtual certainty''
that her husband had been killed by his captors.
   Rogers ended his two-year command of the current USS Vincennes
on May 27 without apology for the cruiser's mistaken destruction of
the Iranian airliner on July 3, 1988. All 290 aboard the jet died.
   He currently is commanding officer of Tactical Training
Group-Pacific headquartered in San Diego.
   The dedication was held as part of the USS Vincennes
Association's 16th annual reunion in this southern Indiana city.
The association, which paid for half of the monument, is made up of
men who have served on one of the four ships that have taken their
name from the Revolutionary War battle fought at Vincennes.
   Private donations also were used in building the $36,000
monument on land owned by the National Part Service.
   The first USS Vincennes was a wooden sloop-of-war which was in
commission from 1826 to 1867. The second ship, a heavy cruiser, was
commissioned in 1937 and sunk by Japanese gunfire off Savo Island,
about 10 miles from Guadalcanal Island, on Aug. 9, 1942. The third
USS Vincennes, a light cruiser, was commissioned in 1944, fought in
the Okinawa campaign and survived World War II.
</TEXT>
