<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Cardinal     08-09 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cardinal,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges Americans to Pray for Hostages This Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday urged all American
churches and other places of faith to offer ``a special prayer''
this weekend for the hostages in Lebanon and for world peace.
   ``I just want to suggest that this weekend, each in our own way,
that we say a prayer for the American hostages, for their family
and indeed for world peace,'' said Bush.
   ``I believe in prayer,'' said the president, who delivered the
plea at the outset of a private meeting with Roman Catholic
Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston.
   ``So I would ask the churches and other places of faith to say a
special prayer this weekend,'' said Bush, an Episcopalian and
regular church-goer.
   Law later called it ``a wonderful thing.''
   The cardinal, a personal friend of Bush's, said he offered a
prayer before the private lunch with the president, chief of staff
John Sununu and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   Law said they discussed not only ``the terrible situation of the
hostages,'' but ``the broader issue of Lebanon.''
   ``The hostage situation has to be seen in the context of the
question of Lebanon as a whole,'' said Law, who expressed hope for
a revival of the Arab League efforts to end the factional strife
and provide ``greater integrity of territory for the Lebanese.''
   Law said that in the past, Christians and Moslems ``have been
able to forge out a very unique kind of political experiment ...
(and) live together in a political system that really was a model''
in Lebanon.
   Law noted that large numbers of Christians are fleeing Beirut
because of the shelling there and said, ``if there isn't quickly
some resolution to the Lebanese situation ... then one would
despair of that Christian presence.''
   Reporters asked the cardinal if he was optimistic about Bush's
diplomatic efforts to end the hostage crisis.
   ``I'm in the business of hope, I'm in the business of
conversion, so I'm never ready to assume that the status quo is
it,'' Law replied with a smile.
   Law said Bush had tentatively agreed to visit Boston Sept. 23 to
speak at a gathering of Catholic lawyers and judges.
   He said they also discussed events in Central America and Cuba,
a country Law has visited several times.
   Law said that despite recent arrests of human rights activists
in Cuba, he has seen progress in the communist island in the past
five years toward wider freedom.
   ``It does seem to me that Cuba, given its geographic location,
very naturally ought to be in good relationship with the United
States,'' said the cardinal.
</TEXT>
