<FIRST>u w AM-China-Dependents     08-09 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dependents,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Dependents Authorized To Return To China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 260 dependents of U.S. government
employees in China who were evacuated in June have been authorized
to return because of improved security conditions, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said that the State
Department nonetheless is continuing to recommend to Americans that
they defer non-essential travel to China.
   She that the although the security situation has improved, it is
still more unsettled than before the imposition of martial law in
May.
   The dependents were ordered home three days after Chinese
military forces routed demonstrators who had occupied Tienanmen
Square in Beijing for weeks.
   As part of the disturbances, Chinese troops fired their weapons
in the vicinity of a compound where diplomats and other foreign
residents live. The U.S. Embassy's chief of security said bullets
flew through a window into a room where his two children were
watching television.
   The incident prompted a strong protest by the U.S. Embassy to
Chinese authorities. Ms. Tutwiler was unable to say whether the
issue was resolved to the satisfaction of U.S. officials.
   At the time, officials said the shooting appeared to come from
the indiscriminate firing of troops who were attempting to clear
Chinese civilians from the streets.
   The decision to send the dependents back to China contributed to
the notion that U.S.-Chinese relations are gradually normalizing.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III met late last month with
China's foreign minister during a visit to Paris.
   Other officials, insisting on anonymity, said virtually all
other foreign dependents who were evacuated in June have since
returned to Beijing. They also said that of the 350 American
businessmen who departed China, about 150 have gone back.
   The State Department urged American visitors to China to take a
number of precautions. It said Chinese authorities have seized
religious and political materials they deem objectionable and it
urged that Americans refrain from going out after dark or
photographing areas where disturbances have occurred.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
