<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     08-09 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Blasts Communists But Offers Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fledgling parliamentary opposition
said Wednesday that said the Communists had destroyed Hungarian
society in 42 years of rule, but it offered to cooperate with party
reformers after free elections.
   Members of the opposition Hungarian Democratic Forum ruled out
any coalition with the Communist Party before general elections
planned next year.
   But they said even a new government dominated by the forum and
other opposition groups would likely include some Communist
ministers.
   The forum counts among its members a tiny legislative caucus of
three newly elected lawmakers. The country's one-chamber
legislature has 370 members.
   ``We are trying to change a completely wrecked society to a new
one,'' declared Istvan Csurka, a forum leader, speaking to
reporters at his organization's headquarters in Budapest. However,
he did not present a program of change.
   Two of the front legislators complained of interference by local
Communist officials during campaigning and voting in by-elections
Saturday and on July 22. However, they suggested the irregularities
were the work of overzealous individuals _ not part of a larger
plan.
   While only a small fraction of Hungary's electorate took part in
the by-elections, opposition figures have viewed the results as an
indication of Communist weakness during next year's general
elections.
   Communist leaders, who endorsed a multiparty system in February,
have sought to play down the defeat of their candidates, pointing
to low turnouts and claiming their campaigns were low-key.
   Csurka was asked Wednesday if he or other top forum officials
were ready to become prime minister if the opposition won next
year's elections.
   ``We will find the right man from our ranks for any
responsibility,'' he said.
   But he said ``there will be and there must be'' some Communists
in the next Hungarian government, regardless of the election
outcome.
   Forum spokesman Csaba Kiss put conditions on any post-election
cooperation with the Communists.
   ``There can be no coalition if the key positions _ Interior
Ministry, Foreign Ministry, Finance Ministry _ are seized by the
Communist Party, as in 1947,'' he told reporters. Hungary became a
one-party state that year.
   In Poland, the opposition, led by the labor union Solidarity,
has refused to join the ruling Communists in a coalition after
Solidarity scored a sweeping victory in June elections.
</TEXT>
