<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1932EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial     08-09 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liquor Salesmen Describe Kickbacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second and third liquor salesmen to take the
stand at Leona Helmsley's tax evasion and extortion trial testified
Wednesday that they, too, were forced to pay kickbacks on sales to
Helmsley-owned hotels.
   Herbert Cohen of Capital Liquors and James Pursley of Star
Industries both said they had to pay back 2 percent of their gross
sales to four hotels _ the Park Lane, the Palace, the New York
Helmsley and the St. Moritz. The salesmen testified that their
commissions were generally 5 percent on gross sales.
   They testified the payments were arranged by Mrs. Helmsley's top
aide, Frank Turco, and that the kickbacks were no longer required
after Turco was fired in February 1986.
   The testimony was elicited by prosecutors to support the most
serious charge Mrs. Helmsley faces _ the allegation that she
conspired with Turco to extort payoffs and goods from vendors doing
business with Helmsley-owned companies. Turco is on trial with her.
   Last week, the first liquor salesman to testify, Lee West, said
he was forced to kick back the same percentage of his commission to
keep his accounts at Helmsley hotels in New York. He said he gave
about $10,000 in payoffs in 1984.
   Lee testified that in addition he had to take on the task of
acting as central purchasing agent for liquor for the hotels. Mrs.
Helmsley decided to set up the arrangment after she was told
certain employees within the company were taking kickbacks from
liquor salesmen.
   Pursley said he took over the task after Lee left at the end of
1984.
   He testified that at a meeting in February 1985 with other
liquor salesmen, Turco discussed where payments were going.
   ``He told us all that none of the money was going to him. It
goes to Mrs. Helmsley,'' Pursley said, adding that Turco said he
put the money in a special slush fund for Mrs. Helmsley.
   He quoted Turco as saying that Mrs. Helmsley said that ``since
we were so free with our money, she was going to take it.''
   Pursley said he paid an average of $600 a month for one year
beginning in February 1985. He delivered his cash payments in
envelopes to Turco's office, he said. Cohen testified that he
kicked back about $9,000 over two years. He said that one of the
Helmsleys' real estate companies would send him an invoice for
consulting fees and that he would send a check for that amount.
   Mrs. Helmsley also is charged with tax evasion for allegedly
disguising about $4 million in personal expenses as business
expenses. Turco and another former aide, Joseph Licari, are charged
with assisting in that scheme. All three are on trial on the tax
charge.
   The conspiracy charge carries a maximum prison term of 20 years
upon conviction. Penalties on the tax fraud charges range from
three to five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0154 </DOCNO>
