<DOCNO> AP890809-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-APArts:FilmReview 1stLd-Writethru a0650 08-09 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Film Review, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>At the Movies: `The Abyss'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT Nolan to Bridges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: The Abyss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If E.T. took a little ocean vacation with Jules Verne, and
dropped in for lunch with Lloyd Bridges and Flipper, maybe someone
would make a movie out of it. Maybe it could even be called ``The
Abyss.''
   The $43 million 20th Century Fox summer spectacular is about as
derivative as any movie can get. James Cameron, who wrote and
directed, pulls a litany of movie formulas and gimmicks, including
a few from ``Aliens,'' which he also wrote and directed.
   What redeems ``The Abyss'' from being an ``E.T.'' or ``Aliens''
rip-off are some spectacular special effects and camera work.
   Deepcore, a submersible oil rig, is working not far from where a
submarine, armed with nuclear warheads, has crashed in a
fantastically deep trough. The government commandeers the mother
vessel, orders Deepcore to take on a group of Navy SEALS and work
with the divers to salvage the sub.
   At the same time, a hurricane rages above and an alien nation
broods below. It seems the hurricane was a little something the
aliens whipped up to protest nuclear weapons. The aliens, who move
faster than a speeding bullet and who are definitely more powerful
than any locomotive, also are responsible for the sub crash.
   Still, they are friendly, peace-loving little shards of light,
vaguely reminiscent of the ethereal creatures in Ron Howard's
``Cocoon.''
   Deepcore's crew is a lovable bunch of hardcore riggers led by
Bud Brigman (Ed Harris). His estranged wife, Lindsey (Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio), designed the rig and brings down the SEALS
for the salvage operation.
   The SEALS have a definite attitude problem, and their leader,
Lt. Coffey (Michael Biehn), is certifiable.
   The hurricane causes an above-water crane to crash down on
Deepcore, and drags it the brink of the underwater trough. After
communciation is severed with the mother ship, Coffey goes solo and
decides to arm one of the sub's nuclear warheads, terminate the
aliens and kill Deepcore's crew.
   Before his ultimate demise, Coffey manages to arm one of
Deepcore's mini sea Rovers, called Little Geek, with a nuclear
warhead, aimed straight into the trough at the alien nation.
   The first two-thirds of ``The Abyss'' amount to a fairly good
adventure-thriller, with lots of sparkling, hip dialogue, good
character development and nonstop action. The last third is a joke.
   Brigman decides to don a dive suit and go into the trough to
follow Little Geek. He uses a special, experimental Navy liquid mix
as his breathing aparatus. Why does he go? Because it's a dirty
little job and ``somebody has to do it,'' he says with a straight
face. This and other cliches pop up with astonishing frequency as
``The Abyss'' begins its plunge into movie camp.
   There are odd moments: Lindsey drowning in freezing water and
then being revived by Bud slapping her face and calling her names
after adrenalin and shocks have failed; a syrupy and trite Lindsey
confessing to all sorts of mistreatment to Bud as he almost loses
conciousness at depths no human has ever gone.
   There are pure ripoffs: an alien finger resembling little E.T.'s
spindly appendage reaching out and touching a human _ much the same
way as in ``E.T. The Extraterrestrial,'' and Michaelangelo's
ceiling in the Sistine Chapel.
   But Harris and Mastrantonio are a good blend, and the Deepcore
crew is an interesting lot, thanks in part to Howard Feuer's
casting. Still, it's a formula group: a strong woman who helps
leads the crew from disaster; a black; a burly, football type; a
comic who travels with his pet mouse; a laidback guy named Jammer
who comes through when the going gets real rough.
   Mikael Salomon's photography is superb, and the original music
by Alan Silvestri has just the right taste of suspense and promise.
   But in the end, ``The Abyss'' promises so much and delivers so
little.
   Produced by Gale Anne Hurd, ``The Abyss'' is rated PG-13 for
language and thrills.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
