<FIRST>r a AM-LesbianSoldier     08-09 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lesbian Soldier,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lesbian Soldier Can't Re-Enlist in Army, Appeals Court Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has barred an Army
Reserve sergeant from re-enlisting because she is a lesbian, saying
sexual orientation is important for maintaining discipline and the
integrity of command.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a lower court
decision allowing Miriam Ben-Shalom, of Milwaukee, to rejoin the
Army Reserve. The Army had refused to allow her to re-enlist
because of her professed homosexuality.
   Patrick Berigan, Ms. Ben-Shalom's attorney, said she will
appeal. ``It's our intent to keep up with the appeals and go as far
as we can,'' he said from his home in Milwaukee.
   Tuesday's ruling reversed a January decision by U.S. District
Judge Myron Gordon in Milwaukee. Gordon said Ms. Ben-Shalom's First
Amendment rights to freedom of speech were violated by an Army
regulation barring homosexuals.
   Ruling on the Army's appeal, the three-judge appeals court panel
found that while Ms. Ben-Shalom's declaration of homosexuality is
speech, it is also an acknowledgement of identification in a group.
   ``It is the identity that makes her ineligible for military
service, not the speaking of it aloud,'' Judge Harlington Wood Jr.
wrote in the decision. ``Thus, if the Army's regulation affects
speech, it does so only incidentally, in the course of pursuing
other legitimate goals.''
   The appellate court agreed with the Army's argument that it
needs to distinguish military personnel on the basis of sexual
orientation to maintain discipline and preserve the integrity of
rank and command.
   The court also found that Ms. Ben-Shalom's 5th Amendment right
to equal protection under the law had not been violated.
   Ms. Ben-Shalom was traveling in Michigan and could not be
reached for comment, said a friend, Hope Gentle, contacted at Ms.
Ben-Shalom's home in Milwaukee.
   John Hoyle, the Justice Department attorney who argued the case
before the appellate court for the Army, declined to comment.
   Ms. Ben-Shalom, 40, was discharged from the Army Reserve in 1976
after she said she was a lesbian. After a series of court actions,
she was reinstated in September 1987.
   Ms. Ben-Shalom applied to re-enlist for a six-year Army Reserve
term last August. Gordon ordered the Army to consider her
re-enlistment without regard to her homosexuality.
   The Army refused to let her rejoin, but after Gordon found the
service in contempt of court in January, Ms. Ben-Shalom was allowed
to re-enlist. The action was, however, made conditional on the
outcome of the Army's appeal to the circuit court.
</TEXT>
