<FIRST>r w AM-Children-900Numbers     08-09 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children-900 Numbers,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACT Asks Stronger Federal Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that monitors children's television
asked the government Wednesday to regulate paid telephone message
services pitched to young viewers and said calls to such numbers
can bring parents unexpectedly large telephone bills.
   Calling it a pocketbook issue rather than a free speech one,
Action for Children's Television requested the Federal Trade
Commission to restrict such 900-number services.
   Its petition asks the FTC to require American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. to issue refunds on demand to parents for
unauthorized calls made by their children, make a blocking device
available to parents and itemize telephone bills ``for child
services.''
   The group's targets are the numbers advertised on children's
programs shown on independent stations during weekday afternoon
hours, when many ``latchkey'' children are at home but their
parents are at work.
   The 900 numbers invite children to talk to popular personalities
and cartoon characters, such as the Tooth Fairy, Mighty Mouse or
She-Ra and He-man, and often offer products such as posters, signs
or shirts as enticements to call, according to the ACT petition.
   Although children are told they will ``talk to'' a character,
they hear a recorded message instead, the petition says.
   In fact, AT&amp;T says that any 900 service for which it consents to
do the billing must be a recorded message. It must also say what
the call will cost, tell children to ask for their parents'
permission and allow no ``funny technology,'' such as the service
that told children to hold the phone to the TV while it bleeped out
tones.
   A typical call to such a 900 number might cost $2.45 _ $2 for
the first minute and 45 cents for each additional minute.
   Andrea West, AT&amp;T's product marketing manager for 900 services,
said the company doesn't issue all 900 numbers although ``we have
some sponsors that do provide programming with licensed
characters.''
   Licensed characters are those for whom the rights are owned by a
company.
   West said customers can contest their bills although AT&amp;T has no
blanket policy on granting refunds. She said regional phone company
have the choice of offering itemized billing and in some instances
do offer blocking devices.
   AT&amp;T says it set its guidelines ``in concert with'' the
regulatory guidelines of the Children's Advertising Review Unit of
the Council of Better Business Bureaus.
   The ACT petition calls the AT&amp;T safeguards ineffective. ACT
President Peggy Charren said that although AT&amp;T may not issue all
the numbers, ``the ones they bill are the ones we are talking
about.''
   The Better Business Bureau unit that oversees children's
advertising says it does not ``encourage or endorse this form of
advertising to children'' but is proposing guidelines.
   Robert H. Lorsch, president and founder of Teleline Inc. of
Beveraly Hills, Calif., one of the leading providers of such
services, said research shows that an average call lasts less than
two minutes, that children have asked their parents' permission and
that children who don't understand that the costs mount with the
time they are on the phone probably couldn't make a call in the
first place.
   He said his company has worked closely with ACT and the business
bureau to put out responsible programming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
