<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-09 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas at Campus Protesters, Detain Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas at hundreds
of black protesters marching from a university campus in defiance
of emergency regulations Wednesday. Fifteen journalists were
detained.
   At least 1,500 black students and other activists held a
lunchtime rally at the mixed-race University of the Western Cape as
part of a national campaign of defiance against emergency
restrictions and apartheid laws.
   The protests, which have been marked by almost daily
student-police clashes in the Cape Town area, coincide with the
campaign for Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. The Parliament
excludes representatives of the black majority of 28 million.
   After the rally, police detained 15 reporters, photographers and
cameramen for foreign and local news organizations for about four
hours. They were placed in police vehicles and held outside the
campus while police fired rounds of tear gas at the between 500 and
600 people who marched off the university grounds after the rally.
   The journalists were later taken to a police station and warned
that they were under investigation for allegedly violating the
3-year-old emergency regulations that restrict press coverage of
unrest. Enforcement of the press restrictions has not been
comprehensive.
   ``About 20 policemen were firing tear gas at random as the
marchers with placards came about a quarter of the way across the
road, then moved back,'' said a journalist who watched the events.
``The police were firing tear gas over the cars passing on the
road, then they went onto the campus and fired tear gas all over.''
   It was not known whether any students were arrested or injured
in the clash.
   The Argus, a Cape Town newspaper, said in an editorial Wednesday
that the defiance protests, which began a week ago with black
patients seeking treatment at white hospitals, were gathering
momentum.
   The paper said organizations and individuals restricted under
the 1986 emergency were refusing to ``meekly acquiesce in their own
repression.''
   ``The government's response has been predictable,'' said The
Argus. ``It has furiously denounced the organizations leading the
defiance and ordered a tough police response _ no doubt sensing
that such handling of the situation could boost its flagging
fortunes in the general election campaign.''
   The 924,000-member Congress of South African Trade Unions is a
leader of the defiance campaign, despite a government decree that
bans the organization from engaging in political activity.
   The congress issued a statement Wednesday mocking Law and Order
Minister Adriaan Vlok's comment that he will investigate the labor
federation's breaking of the emergency restrictions.
   ``What he will find is that the vast majority of right-thinking
South Africans have stopped observing the state of emergency long
ago,'' the statement said. ``Not only are these regulations
incomprehensible and unenforceable, but people do not regard
themselves as bound by laws which they had no say in passing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
