<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2008EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Gunman     08-09 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Gunman,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Says `Voices' Told Him to Kill President Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man arrested after a bank robbery said he
committed a string of heists around the country while trailing
George Bush because ``voices'' told him to kill the president,
police said Wednesday.
   John Spencer Daughette, a 34-year-old transient, reportedly told
investigators he robbed the bank because he needed money to carry
out his assassination plan.
   ``He was going to get about $3,000 to buy a motorcycle and go
east and assassinate the president or kill some children,'' said
Oakland police Sgt. Greg Bingham. ``I believe with all my heart
from talking to him, he would have done just that.''
   Bingham said the FBI told Oakland police that Daughette fits the
profile of someone capable of carrying out such an act.
   ``We had no idea what we had on our hands when we picked him
up,'' said Bingham. ``As he started talking, we realized we had a
very scary individual in our presence.''
   During an interview with police and the FBI, Bingham said
Daughette appeared ``very calm, relaxed and with very good recall.''
   While an investigation continued to determine whether the
alleged assassination plan may result in criminal charges,
Daughette remained jailed without bail in San Francisco on one
count of bank robbery.
   Geoff Hansen, the federal public defender appointed to represent
Daughette, declined comment about his client. He said information
about the Daughette case and background will likely be revealed at
a detention hearing scheduled in U.S. District Court on Thursday.
   After he was arrested Friday for allegedly robbing Gateway
Savings in Oakland, Daughette ``readily admitted to the robbery of
this bank and seven others across the United States,'' said Sgt.
Sam Maddux. ``He also admitted he had been stalking or pursuing the
president of the United States in an attempt to kill him.''
   His assassination plan was attributed to voices that ``were
telling him to do certain things, and if he did not do so, he would
be poisoned,'' Maddux said. ``These voices did not tell him why.''
   Bingham said Daughette indicated his presidential death plan
focused on ``the office, not the man ... he wants to assassinate
the president.''
   Maddux said Daughette also ``made some mention he had seen the
TV news reports about the school children shootings in Stockton,
and at that point he heard very loud voices that said if he
couldn't kill the president, he should go after school children.''
   On Jan. 17, Patrick Edward Purdy opened fire with a
semiautomatic AK-47 on a Stockton schoolyard, killing five children
and wounding 29 students and a teacher.
   John Henneman, spokesman for Richard Roudebush Veterans
Administration Medical Center in Indianapolis, said Daughette was
admitted on Jan. 14, 1987, for a 30-day stay and again in April
1987 for 45 days. Daughette was admitted on Feb. 10, but walked
away from the hospital on March 20, he said.
   Henneman said he could not reveal what Daughette was treated
for, but said he is an Army veteran from Flora, Ind.
   Bingham said Daughette told him he had been treated at VA
hospitals for mental problems, and that he had been interviewed by
Secret Service authorities for alleged threats against ex-President
Reagan. State and federal checks failed to show any criminal record
for Daughette, he said.
   Daughette said that ``on one occasion in Michigan, he was
somewhat close (to harming Bush), but because of security
precautions, he was unable to carry out the threat,'' Maddux said.
   James Huse, special agent in charge of the Secret Service office
in Detroit, said Daughette claimed he had been in Hamtramck the
night before Bush's April 17 speech to a crowd of 4,000. Daughette
apparently diagramed the area where Bush spoke, Huse said.
   ``He told agents he had picked out the perfect spot to shoot
from but couldn't reach it on speech day because of metal
detectors,'' Huse said. ``He then ran to several areas trying to
get close enough for a shot but before he could shoot, the
president finished and left the podium.''
</TEXT>
