<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Lucas     08-09 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Affiliated With Lucas Defends Apartments in Racial Discrimination
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit firm with which failed civil rights
chief nominee William Lucas is affiliated is defending an apartment
building against racial discrimination suits, the Justice
Department said Wednesday.
   The most recent lawsuit, filed Wednesday by the department's
civil rights division, charged that River House Cooperative, Inc.,
of Detroit had engaged in a pattern of intentional racial
discrimination against blacks.
   Lucas, whom President Bush had nominated to be assistant
attorney general for civil rights, has not been involved and will
not participate in the law firm's handling of the case, said
Justice Department spokesman David Runkel.
   River House has been represented by Evans and Luptak, a Detroit
firm where Lucas is listed as ``of counsel'' on a financial
disclosure form he filed earlier this year.
   River House has already been the subject of a discrimination
suit brought by private plaintiffs, said Justice Department
spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade.
   The federal suit charges that the cooperative ``has engaged in a
policy and practice of discrimination'' against blacks in violation
of the Fair Housing Amendments Act of 1988 and the fair-housing
provisions of the 1968 Civil Rights Act.
   In a statement, U.S. Attorney Stephen J. Markman said, ``It's
long past time that such discrimination in housing is acceptable in
Michigan.''
   President Bush's nomination of Lucas, 61, a former sheriff and
chief executive of Wayne County, Mich., to head the Justice
Department's civil rights division was defeated last week by the
Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Opponents charged that Lucas lacked professional qualifications
to head the 150-lawyer division of the Justice Department. They
also questioned his commitment to enforcing civil rights laws.
   Supporters said Lucas, who is black, was a victim of racism or
was being penalized for his refusal to criticize recent Supreme
Court decisions that they say weaken affirmative action.
   The White House says Bush is still considering giving Lucas a
so-called recess appointment to the position, which would enable
Lucas to serve without Senate confirmation through 1990. But such a
move could anger Senators and create political difficulties for
Bush.
   Runkel, meanwhile, said the Justice Department had compiled a
list of possible alternative candidates for the civil rights post.
   Lucas will be given a job within the Bush administration,
possibly at the Justice Department, Runkel said.
   He ruled out the possibility that Lucas would be appointed to
head the U.S. Marshals Service, a position Lucas had reportedly
sought before the civil rights nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
