<FIRST>r a AM-Pony     08-09 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pony,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pony Owner Billed By Railroad For Service Disruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMAGANSETT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cupcake, the pony whose errant hoof
disrupted service on the Long Island Rail Road, now has another
tale of whoa.
   LIRR officials are demanding a $2,625 payment for the buses it
was forced to hire to get commuters to their destinations when the
pony's hoof was stuck between train tracks in December, setting off
a two-hour delay.
   Railroad officials said in a letter this week to Cupcake's owner
that if she did not pay the expenses within 30 days they would take
her to court.
   The iron horse can wait until the cows come home, said owner
Anne Eggers of Amagansett. She's not paying.
   ``I think this is a very high and mighty way to handle what
happened,'' said Mrs. Eggers who owns two other ponies. ``This is
outrageous.''
   Cupcake, 19, escaped during the night from the barn in the
Eggers' backyard. ``We had just built a new barn and apparently the
latch was faulty,'' said Mrs. Eggers.
   Cupcake trotted over to the railroad tracks, a few miles away,
where his hoof got stuck. The Eggers were called early in the
morning and told their horse was stalling train traffic.
   ``When we got there Cupcake looked so sad,'' said Mrs. Eggers.
``His head was slumped down and he looked like he had just given up
any chance of ever being free again.''
   A veterinarian injected the horse with a sedative. Rescue
workers then picked him up by his tail, lifting him uninjured from
the railroad ties.
   ``What happened was not our fault, not Cupcake's fault,'' said
Mrs. Eggers. ``There is just no way we are going to pay for this.''
   ``We think Cupcake is getting a bad rap,'' she said.
   LIRR spokesman Michael Charles said he regrets what happened to
Cupcake, but the owner should have kept him on her property.
   ``This is a unique case'' because there is a horse involved,
Charles said. He said the railroad often seeks payment from people
who disrupt service, such as motorists who damage crossing gates by
driving through them.
</TEXT>
