<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Shenker     08-09 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Shenker,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Lawyer Morris Shenker Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morris A. Shenker, an attorney best known for
defending Teamster boss Jimmy Hoffa, has died. He was 82.
   A spokesman said Shenker, who had recently undergone heart
surgery and who wore a pacemaker, died Tuesday night in Santa
Monica, Calif., where he had been visiting his daughter. He had
been hospitalized for a few days with pneumonia.
   Shenker, a Russian immigrant who grew up in north St. Louis,
made a name for himself as a young lawyer by doing free legal work
for the poor and getting involved in Democratic politics.
   Hoffa, his most famous client, had links to organized crime,
disappeared years ago and is presumed dead.
   Because of his Teamsters connection, Shenker, who operated the
Dunes Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas in the 1970s, ran afoul of the
Nevada Gaming Commission.
   Despite state and federal investigations, however, Shenker
escaped indictment until this year.
   In February, a federal grand jury accused him of conspiring to
conceal hundreds of thousands of dollars from the Internal Revenue
Service and bankruptcy creditors. Shenker denied any wrongdoing.
   Shenker filed for bankruptcy in 1984 and had been involved in
court battles over his finances ever since.
   Survivors include a daughter, Patty Shenker Stoll, of Santa
Monica, Calif.; a son, Arthur Shenker, of Las Vegas, and two
granddaughters.
   Services were scheduled Sunday at Temple Israel in St. Louis.
</TEXT>
