<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-Labor     08-09 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Labor,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Woman Tried to Inject Cocaine Before Giving Birth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was discovered trying to inject
herself with cocaine in a delivery room minutes before giving birth
to a premature boy, police said.
   Gayle Turenne, 31, was charged Wednesday in a warrant with one
count of possession of cocaine, said Lt. Jim Singer. St. Paul
police could not say whether she had been arrested by Wednesday
night.
   ``The woman needs help. We hope we can do something about it,''
Singer said, adding that Turenne has been referred to Ramsey County
Community Human Services for evaluation.
   She had been taken by ambulance to United Hospital while in
labor Saturday morning, police spokesman Paul Adelmann said.
   A nurse noticed her inserting a hypodermic syringe into her
wrist and stopped her before the drug was injected, he said. Five
minutes later, she delivered a five-week premature boy.
   Turenne, who has three other children, was discharged from the
hospital Monday.
   Doctors had ordered a search of the woman's suitcase and purse,
which yielded three packets of cocaine, a bag of marijuana and drug
paraphernalia, police said.
   The baby remained hospitalized, hospital spokeswoman Carol
Hobart said, but she declined to comment on the child's condition.
   Under a state law that took effect Aug. 1, doctors are required
to report to county child protection officials evidence of use of
illegal drugs by pregnant women or the presence of drugs in the
systems of newborn babies. The law defines a positive drug test of
a newborn as proof of child neglect.
   Doctors say pregnant women who use cocaine place themselves at a
greater risk of miscarriage and premature birth and their babies
are more susceptible to sudden infant death syndrome and erratic
and violent behavior as toddlers.
</TEXT>
