<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1847EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-09 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Day Of Record Lows, Thunderstorms Develop Across West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures slid to record lows in 23 states Wednesday from the
Plains to the East Coast, and thunderstorms buffeted Florida,
causing some damage.
   More than 70 cities reported record or record-tying lows, mostly
in the 40s and 50s although states along the Gulf of Mexico posted
record lows in the 60s. Apalachicola, Fla., tied its record of 71.
   Low-temperature records were broken or tied in Alabama,
Arkansas, Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Kansas,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, Missouri, Nebraska, New
York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, South Carolina,
Tennessee, Texas, Virginia, West Virginia, and the District of
Columbia.
   Strong thunderstorms erupted across Florida during the
afternoon. Thunderstorm wind damaged a house at Jensen Beach and a
gust to 68 mph was clocked at Daytona Beach, the National Weather
Service said.
   Gusts reached 55 mph in the West Palm Beach area and a
thunderstorm dropped small hail and 1.66 inches of rain in one hour
at Gainesville.
   Strong showers and thunderstorms developed across the
Intermountain region _ between the Sierra Nevada and the Rockies _
where Las Vegas, Nev., suffered damage from high wind up to 99 mph
late Tuesday.
   Flash flood watches were posted for Utah, southern and
east-central Nevada, and western Wyoming.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across parts of
the Northwest and west-central Plains and along the lower Texas
coast.
   Rain was scattered over eastern sections of the Carolinas and
Georgia, where Hinesville got 1.30 inches of rain in the six hours
up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 107 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 39 at Bradford, Pa.,
and Lewisburg, W.Va.
   For Thursday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast over the
southern Atlantic Coast states, with rain likely over much of
Virginia, Delaware and Maryland. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were forecast across the northern and central Rockies
to western sections of the northern and central Plains, and from
southeastern Louisiana to Alabama. Widely scattered thunderstorms
were forecast over New Mexico, and western sections of Texas and
Oklahoma. Scattered showers were forecast over southeastern
Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
   Highs in the 70s and lower 80s were predicted from the Great
Lakes across the upper Ohio Valley and the northern and middle
Atlantic Coastal states to the Carolinas, and along the Pacific
Coast and over Washington state; highs above 100 were predicted
over the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s across much of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
