<FIRST>r a AM-BronxTour     08-09 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bronx Tour,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visitors Bureau Gets Bronx Cheer Over `Burnout Wilderness' Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Convention and Visitors Bureau
apologized Wednesday to the Bronx borough president for posting a
flyer that promised a tour of Fort Apache and ``the Burnout
Wilderness'' in the South Bronx.
   The flyer had been ``brought in for display by this private
sightseeing company and unfortunately was one of those things that
slipped through,'' said Jack MacBean, spokesman for the Visitors
Bureau.
   In a letter to Marshall Murdaugh, president of the Visitors
Bureau, borough President Fernando Ferrer protested against the
flyer ``on behalf of the Bronx Zoo, the Botanical Garden, the
Yankees and the more than 1.2 million residents of the borough of
parks and universities.''
   He also expressed fear that the flyer could deter potential
investors from continuing their rehabilitation efforts in parts of
the Bronx where housing was abandoned or burned down in the late
1970s and early 1980s.
   ``Aren't you aware,'' Ferrer wrote, ``that more than 16,000 new
units of housing are being created here, most of them in the South
Bronx? And that unfortunate characterization of the 41st Police
Precinct as Fort Apache is a wornout cliche that no longer holds
true.''
   Murdaugh apologized for the flyer and said the Visitors Bureau
promotes ``the Bronx in all of our publications in extremely
positive terms.''
   The 41st Precinct's nickname of Fort Apache was popularized in a
movie starring Paul Newman called ``Fort Apache, the Bronx.''
