<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Planes     08-09 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Planes,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Parliament To Probe Procurement of Military Planes, Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Wednesday began action to
investigate purported kickbacks during the Socialist administration
of former Premier Andreas Papandreou in procuring 80 U.S. and
French jet fighter planes.
   It approved formation of a 12-member fact-finding commission to
determine whether enough evidence exists to justify a full
investigation by a parliamentary committee.
   The probe involves 40 F-16s and 40 French-made Mirage 2000s and
300 Magic II missiles. Conservatives proposed the investigation
following allegations that Greek taxpayers paid many millions of
dollars more than they should have.
   When Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement decided to buy
the French and American built aircraft after first coming to power
in 1981, negotiations began between the governments.
   The F-16s were to be bought through U.S. military credits, and a
letter of intent was signed in 1984. Greece receives $500 million
in U.S. military credits a year.
   Negotiations broke down and the socialist government came into
direct contact with General Dynamics. It later signed a contract
for the F-16s following what was billed as a ``political decision''
by Papandreou.
   The Mirage deal was signed earlier after Papandreou announced he
made the decision following direct negotiations with
Dassault-Breguet of France.
   Papandreou said direct agreement with the manufacturer
eliminated middlemen and helped keep the total price lower.
   The government-to-manufacturer negotiations raised questions at
the time since the aircraft's unit price was reportedly much higher
than what the same firms quoted to other countries. The government
said the aircraft contained additional sophisticated electronics
that greatly boosted the unit cost.
   Conservative New Democracy leader Constantine Mitsotakis said
Tuesday in parliamentary debate that his party considered the
purchase the ``biggest scandal'' in the socialists' eight-year
administration and Papandreou's ``biggest political mistake.''
   The 70-year-old Papandreou is recuperating from a kidney ailment
and is also honeymooning with his 35-year-old bride. He was not
present in Parliament to reply to the charges. He has not appeared
during debates on scandals in which his former government was
allegedly involved before losing June 18 general elections.
   Government spokesman Athanasios Kanelopoulos said last week it
was unlikely the parliamentary commission would seek information
from the aircraft manufacturers during the probe.
   In March 1985, a spokesman for Papandreou's government said $2
billion would be spent on the 80 jets. In January 1987, the
purchase price of the 40 F-16s was given by Greece as $940 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
