<DOCNO> AP890809-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ArmsTalks     08-09 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow Urges Accord On Nuclear Testing This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet arms control negotiator on Wednesday
called on the United States to agree to monitoring measures for
underground nuclear weapons testing by the end of the year.
   Igor Palenykh, Moscow's chief envoy to the superpower nuclear
testing talks, said the United States is moving ``too slowly'' on
the issue and urged Washington to respond to a Soviet proposal.
   He called for the talks to be wrapped up this year.
   A six-week round of negotiations that ended Tuesday produced
agreement on some ``important technical aspects'' for possible
inclusion in a testing accord, Palenykh told a news conference.
   The talks are to set verification provisions and secure U.S.
Senate approval for two 1970s unratified superpower nuclear accords.
   But negotiations stalled over the monitoring techniques for
atomic weapons tests, Palenykh said.
   U.S. negotiator C. Paul Robinson has said ``high-level
decisions'' in the two capitals will be needed during the recess to
move them along.
   No date was set for resuming the testing talks. The next phase
of negotiations will focus on a nuclear test ban.
   Palenykh said he hoped Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze and U.S. Scecretary of State James A. Baker III would
discuss the testing accord at their Sept. 19-20 meeting in the
United States.
   The Soviet proposal would allow use of both remote seismic or
on-the-spot monitoring for ``any explosion starting from a certain
threshold.'' He did not specify the threshold Palenykh said.
   ``We favor the idea of combining various methods of
verification. Of course it will be the right of each side to use
the methods in its own combination,'' he said.
   He said Washington wants to use only an on-site method in which
blasts are measured by a cable placed down a hole near the
explosion site. The United States says its method is the most
accurate.
   The Soviets say remote monitoring of the shock waves is precise
enough, simpler and less expensive.
   The talks are to establish verification provisions for the
unratified 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty for nuclear weapons tests
and the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty on non-military
blasts.
   Both limit the power of explosions to 150 kilotons, the
equivalent of 150,000 tons of TNT.
   The Senate rejected the original accords, arguing they could not
be enforced. Most military analysts agree, however, that both sides
have generally abided by the limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0182 </DOCNO>
