<FIRST>r a AM-ActivistMurdered     08-09 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Activist Murdered,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors Point to Drug Dealers in Death of Activist's Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stood guard Wednesday at an apartment
building where an anti-drug crusader was killed, and her husband
spent the day testifying against a man she had accused of selling
cocaine.
   Fearful neighbors said they would remain quiet because of
violent drug dealers.
   ``You open your mouth and try to help out and see what
happens,'' says one man, sitting on a stoop down the street from
where the Hernandez family lives.
   Maria Hernandez, a 34-year-old mother of three, was getting
ready to go to work about 4:30 a.m. Tuesday when at least five
shots were fired through the closed bedroom windows of her
first-floor apartment in the Bushwick section of Brooklyn.
   One of the bullets hit her in the head and she died a few hours
later at Wyckoff Hospital.
   Her husband, Carlos Hernandez, 33, testified Wednesday before a
grand jury against his neighbor, Raymond Gonzalez, who allegedly
stabbed him in the arm and threatened him with an Uzi machine gun
last month after Mrs. Hernandez accused Gonzalez of selling cocaine
in front of their home.
   Neighbors say the couple often chased drug dealers off their
property.
   The shots were fired through heavy drapes, but Chief of Brooklyn
Detectives Francis X. Smith said he believed the shots were not
meant as a warning.
   ``If you shoot into a lit residence when people are inside, I
have to assume it was meant to hurt someone,'' he said.
   Asked Tuesday if he planned to stop his anti-drug efforts,
Hernandez said, ``Never.''
   A patrol car had been driving past the three-story house about
once an hour since Saturday because the family had received death
threats from drug dealers.
   Detectives went door-to-door Wednesday, but a police spokesman,
Sgt. Maurice Howard, said, ``They haven't narrowed it down to any
specific suspects.''
   ``She's trying to protect her neighborhood, her kids,'' said
Marguerite Wise, who lives around the corner and knew the family
because their children were good friends. ``That woman never hurt
anybody.''
   She said she was angered by the drug dealers that plague the
neighborhood, but is afraid to complain to police.
   ``On my block I see what goes on but I shut up,'' she said.
``I'm afraid for my life and my kids.''
   While women with baby carriages and children congregated in
front of the Hernandez's apartment, a block away a half-dozen or
more drug dealers impassively continued their trade, selling heroin
under brand names like ``Terror'' and ``Steel Ball.''
   A police cruiser stopped at the intersection and two officers
bolted out, hands on their holsters, and headed toward a group of
men huddled together.
   The men ran in all directions and the police nabbed only one,
who had a pocketful of cash but no drugs, and so was let go.
   Less than an hour later, the heroin hawkers were back.
   ``It's wheeling, dealing over here,'' the man sitting on his
stoop said. He declined to give his name, saying he was afraid the
dealers would come after him, even though he lives in Queens and
was only visiting relatives.
   ``If I can notice it, what's their problem?'' he asked,
referring to the police.
   The two officers assigned to guard the home said they realize
what's going on around them, just out of sight, but said they don't
have the answers.
   ``Drugs is a way of life around here,'' one said, speaking on
condition that his name not be used. ``This is an every day thing.''
   ``The drug problem's one thing, but the violence has gotten
worse, even toward police officers,'' his partner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
