<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     08-09 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas At Carbide Protest; 500 Arrested, 25 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of demonstrators threw stones at
police Wednesday during a protest demanding that Union Carbide get
out of India. Police responded with tear gas, and 25 people were
injured and 500 arrested.
   The protest took place outside the Union Carbide Research and
Development Center in Bhopal. Union Carbide's Indian subsidiary
operated the Bhopal pesticide plant, where a gas leak in 1984
killed more than 3,400 people.
   The Union Carbide plant in Bhopal has not opened since the gas
leak, but the protesters demanded that the Danbury, Conn.-based
multinational shut down its remaining Indian operations. They
include a Bombay plant that makes batteries.
   Gas victims, opposition politicians and activists had designated
today the start of ``Union Carbide Quit India'' week.
   Exactly 47 years ago, on Aug. 9, 1942, Mohandas K. Gandhi
launched India's campaign for independence from Britain with a
``Quit India Day.''
   Bhopal observed a general strike today called by opposition
parties and activists to press demands for more compensation for
survivors of the gas leak, the world's deadliest industrial
disaster.
   Public transportation operated, but shops and businesses were
closed.
   About 200 police were deployed outside the Union Carbide
research center to keep out protesters. When some demonstrators
threw stones, police responded by firing tear gas shells and
lashing out with their lathis, long bamboo batons tipped with steel.
   Several people in the crowd received bloody noses, and some
appeared to have broken bones.
   Police vans rushed many of the injured to hospitals. At least
five policemen were among the injured.
   Abdul Jabbar Khan, leader of the Bhopal Gas Tragedy Women's
Organization, lost consciousness as police beat him with their
bamboo batons. Khan had said earlier the protesters would try to
take over the research center.
   ``We want Union Carbide to be prohibited from continuing its
business in India and all industries owned by the killer
multinational to be handed over to the workers,'' he said.
   The protesters denounced the $470 million settlement reached in
February between Union Carbide and the government as compensation
for the gas leak. Opponents say it is not enough.
 
</TEXT>
