<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1919EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Irish     08-09 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Killed; Family Claims No Riots in Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was reported killed
by a police plastic bullet during a night of riots in Belfast, but
family and friends claimed Wednesday there was no rioting in that
area.
   The riots marked the anniversary of a British policy, since
abandoned, of detaining terrorism suspects without trial.
   British news reports said Seamus Duffy, 15, died after being
struck by a plastic bullet fired by security forces trying to
control young supporters of the outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
Wednesday plastic bullets had been fired in self-defense, to
protect property and curb rioters.
   Duffy's family and friends denied there was rioting in the
Dawson Street neighborhood where he was hit.
   Police said crowds in Roman Catholic areas of west Belfast threw
stones and gasoline bombs, lit bonfires and burned British flags.
They reported more than 20 arrests.
   ``While it must be emphasized that the circumstances of Seamus
Duffy's death have yet to be established, the RUC nevertheless
regrets this loss of young life,'' said police statement issued
Wednesday.
   ``The RUC emphasizes once again they have no desire whatsoever
to use plastic baton rounds. If there is no rioting, there will be
no plastic baton rounds.''
   Damien Brown, a 15-year-old friend of the victim, said they were
walking along a street and saw no rioting. ``I heard a shot, looked
back and Seamus was on the ground,'' he said.
   Brendan Duffy, the dead boy's father, accused police of
``opening fire for no reason at all.''
   Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Brooke defended use of the
plastic bullets and said, ``There is no grounds for suggesting
their use last night was other than in accordance with the law.''
   Brian Feeney of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, the
largest predominantly Roman Catholic party in the province, said
plastic bullets were inaccurate, lethal weapons.
   ``Plastic bullets are not used as a last resort; in most cases
in these circumstances they are used as the first resort,'' Feeney
said on Ulster Radio.
   Ireland's government expressed ``deep concern'' about the boy's
death. The British news agency Press Association quoted an official
source as saying Ireland would request a report on the matter.
   Government figures show police fired 54,234 plastic rounds from
the time they replaced rubber bullets in 1975 through June 14.
Press Association said 16 people, half of them under age 16, had
been killed by plastic bullets before Duffy died.
   Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, issued a statement
blaming the death on provocation by security forces.
   The street violence marked Britain's introduction Aug. 9, 1971,
of a policy of interning suspects in Northern Ireland without
trial. IRA supporters, the main targets, continue to mark the
anniversary even though the policy was abandoned in 1975 following
worldwide criticism.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to drive Britain from
Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
the Irish Republic, which is overwhelmingly Catholic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
