<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Riot     08-09 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Riot,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Attack Christian Shops, 35 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem fundamentalists threw firebombs at
Christian-owned shops in a provincial town to avenge an affair
between a Moslem woman and a Christian man, police said Wednesday.
   A police officer said on condition of anonymity that ``many
people'' were injured and 35 were arrested after an unspecified
number of Moslem fundamentalists went on a rampage in northern
Mahmoudeya late Monday. He said he expected 65 more would be
detained.
   No weapons other than the firebombs were used, and police did
not clash with the attackers, the officer said.
   The identities of neither the Moslem woman nor the Christian man
were released.
   The daily state-run Al-Akhbar said Wednesday Moslem extremists
set fire to an appliances store in the Nile Delta town 85 miles
north of Cairo.
   The paper said many of the 35 arrested came from neighboring
towns.
   The police officer said the incident occurred after a Moslem
woman reported her affair with a Christian man to police.
   Friends decided to avenge the woman, who was unable to marry the
Christian man. Egyptian law says a Moslem woman can only marry
someone of her own faith, and the man was apparently unwilling to
convert to Islam to marry her.
   Although the woman consented to the relationship, she was afraid
of her family's reation, the officer said. She asked for
protection, he said.
   In rural areas, there have been reports of fathers killing
daughters who have had sexual liaisons before marriage.
   It was the second incident this year of an attack on Christians
who engage in liaisons with Moslem women. The first occured May 1
in southern Assiut when seven Moslem fundamentalists broke into the
home of a Christian student, killing him and wounding another
Christian man and two Moslem women in the house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
