<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     08-09 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Captain Pleads Not Guilty in R.I. Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Greek-flagged tanker
that ran aground and spilled 300,000 gallons of heating oil off
Rhode Island in June pleaded innocent Wednesday to two state felony
counts.
   Iakovos Georgudis, 43, was released on $20,000 personal
recognizance by Superior Court Judge Thomas J. Caldarone, said
Thomas Connell, spokesman for the attorney general's office.
   Georgudis was indicted by a state grand jury last month on
charges of polluting coastal waters and failing to have a harbor
pilot aboard the World Prodigy when approaching Narragansett Bay.
He has admitted he erred by failing to wait for a pilot before his
tanker grounded on Brenton Reef on June 23.
   In a related development, a hearing was set for next week in
U.S. District Court in Providence on federal misdemeanor charges
against Georgudis.
   Attorneys for Georgudis and U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond
declined to comment on whether the hearing before U.S. Judge Ernest
C. Torres next Wednesday would involved a plea bargain Almond
outlined last week.
   ``That's up to the judge as to what comes up,'' said Thomas H.
Walsh, a lawyer for Ballard Shipping Co., which owns the World
Prodigy.
   On Friday, Almond said a plea bargain was being discussed that
would involve one misdemeanor charge each against the captain and
Ballard Shipping, which has not been charged with anything.
   Walsh attended a closed conference Wednesday with the judge.
Neither he, Almond nor Georgudis' attorney, Peter DiBiase, would
say what the session was about. DiBiase also declined Wednesday to
comment on the plea agreement.
   Georgudis is free on $50,000 bail on two federal pollution
charges. As a condition of that bail he was required to surrender
his passport and remain in Rhode Island, Massachusetts or New York.
   Almond would not identify the penalties that the government
planned on recommending in the federal plea. Each of the charges
carries a potential one-year jail term and fines totaling twice the
cleanup costs.
   Georgudis faces a maximum of $20,000 in fines and 13 months in
jail if convicted of the state charges.
</TEXT>
