<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Jani     08-09 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Jani,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producer Robert Jani Dies at Age 55</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALOS VERDES ESTATES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert F. Jani, producer of
such spectaculars as the U.S. Bicentennial celebration in New York
Harbor in 1976 and halftime for football's Super Bowl, has died at
the age of 55.
   He died Sunday at his home here after a three-year struggle with
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, known as Lou Gehrig's disease, said
a spokesman for his firm, Robert F. Jani Productions.
   Jani also staged much of the live entertainment that has become
standard fare at Disneyland and Disney World, where he worked for
11 years.
   He was also a consultant on master plans for Euro Disneyland,
which opens in 1992, and the new Disney-MGM Studio Tour at Walt
Disney World in Florida.
   In 1978, after he left Disney, he produced the revival of Radio
City Music Hall's ``Magnificent Christmas Spectacular.'' He was in
charge of all live stage productions at the New York City theater
from 1979 to '82 and was credited with its revitalization after a
long period of decline.
   Jani also staged the 1983 Super Bowl entertainment in which
spectators amazed themselves and a national television audience by
spontaneously hoisting 103,000 synchronized flash cards, filling
the Rose Bowl with bright rainbows. It was believed to be the
biggest stunt-card spectacular of all time.
   He drafted the master plan but did not stage the opening and
closing ceremonies at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics. That contract
eventually went to David L. Wolper.
   In 1981, Jani produced ``The Glory of Christmas,'' with a cast
of 400 and a small menagerie of animals at the Crystal Cathedral in
Garden Grove.
   Survivors include his wife, mother, daughter and son. A memorial
service was held Monday at the Rolling Hills Covenant Church in
Rolling Hills Estates.
</TEXT>
