<DOCNO> AP890809-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1940EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nagasaki     08-09 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nagasaki,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>24,000 Gather in Remembrance of Atom Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAGASAKI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 24,000 people on Wednesday mourned
the victims of the world's largest atom bomb used against humans
and called for Japan to strengthen its ban on nuclear warheads.
   In Nagasaki's Peace Park, the crowd commemorated the day 44
years ago when the United States dropped an atom bomb on this
western coastal city.
   The world's first atomic attack had been carried out three days
earlier in Hiroshima, killing 140,000 people. The bomb that hit
Nagasaki, dubbed ``Fat Man,'' was more powerful. But because of the
city's many hills, the damage was contained and 70,000 died, more
than half the population.
   The city's call for stepped-up enforcement of a national policy
banning nuclear warheads, including those on U.S. ships at Japanese
ports, may command the attention of the government now that the
governing Liberal Democrats have been weakened by a series of
scandals and unpopular policies.
   Under the 1951 U.S.-Japan Security Treaty, the United States
pledges to notify Japan if it plans to bring nuclear arms into the
country. Japan says the United States has never consulted with it,
and so it believes such weapons have not entered Japan.
   Critics charge the government uses the agreement to avoid the
question of whether U.S. ships dock in the country with nuclear
weapons aboard.
   ``It is a government's duty to its citizens to strive to shed
light upon the truth, not to wait passively for prior
explanations,'' said Mayor Hitoshi Motoshima, an independent.
   Socialist Party Chairwoman Takako Doi said recently that if a
Socialist government were formed after the next election for the
lower house of Parliament, it would advocate checking all U.S.
ships that enter Japanese waters for nuclear weapons.
   In elections last month, the governing Liberal Democrats lost
their majority in the upper house.
   The disclosure in May that a U.S. hydrogen bomb was lost near an
island in southernmost Japan 24 years ago stirred anger among
citizens and opposition politicians. After investigating, the
government last month said the area had normal radiation levels and
was safe.
</TEXT>
