<FIRST>r i AM-Maldives     08-09 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maldives,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Sri Lankans Sentenced for Attempted Coup in Maldives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The High Court in the Maldives Wednesday
sentenced 15 Sri Lankans to prison terms from 17 to 20 years each
for participating in an attempted coup in the Indian Ocean
archipelago, the Maldivian government said.
   On Tuesday, the court sentenced six Sri Lankans to death and
ordered imprisonment of six others, according to statements telexed
to New Delhi by the Maldivian Department of Information and
Broadcasting.
   Fifty-five Sri Lankans have so far been convicted for the Nov. 3
coup attempt, which left at least 17 people killed. Twelve have
been given death sentences and the others were sentenced to prison
from 17 to 38 years each.
   No dates have been set for the executions.
   Sentencing in the two-month trial began Sunday, the statement
said. There is no higher court of appeal and only President Maumoon
Abdul Gayoom can commute the sentences.
   The court has also fined the convicted men $14 million as
compensation for deaths, injuries and damage to Maldivian property,
the statement said.
   At least 68 Sri Lankans and seven Maldivians were arrested after
Indian paratroopers landed in Male, the capital of the Maldives, to
crush the attempted overthrow.
   The Maldivian government says the coup was led by a Sri
Lanka-based Maldivian, Abdullah Luthufi, who was aided by
mercenaries belonging to the People's Liberation Organization of
Tamil Eelam, one of the several separatist groups that had
participated in the war for an independent Tamil nation in Sri
Lanka.
   Luthufi is among the defendants still on trial.
   The Maldives are a string of 2,000 coral islands about 500 miles
south of India and roughly the same distance southwest of Sri
Lanka. Only about 200 of the islands are inhabited.
</TEXT>
