<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Economy     08-09 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Economy,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sarney Approves Economic Measures Designed to Cut Public Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Wednesday it
would sell 14 state-run companies to the private sector among
emergency measures to cut the public deficit and curb 1,000 percent
annual inflation.
   The measures included selling off government shipping operations
and official residences in Brasilia, the capital, according Ronaldo
Costa Couto, President Jose Sarney's chief of staff.
   Costa Couto refused comment on whether thousands of civil
servants would be fired, as Sarney promised in January. He said the
government would maintain strategic state companies, but he would
not elaborate.
   On Thursday, congressional leaders urged economic reforms to aid
Brazil's ailing economy, including boosting imports to increase
industrial competition, and slashing state subsidies and tax breaks
to the private sector.
   In a 30-point document, they also suggested Sarney eliminate
privileges enjoyed by high officials, including non-essential trips
and state-funded publicity campaigns.
   Plagued by a $112 billion foreign debt _ the developing world's
largest _ and negative economic growth, Brazil sorely needs new
money to meet an interest payment of $3 billion due in September to
private foreign banks.
   The government is negotiating an economic agreement with the
International Monetary Fund that would qualify the country for
nearly $4 billion in fresh loans withheld by private banks and
lending organizations.
   Creditors have refused to lend more money to Brazil, which has
been unable to control inflation, monetary expansion or a
ballooning public deficit, which is around 7 percent of the $300
billion gross national product.
   The government four times has announced it would sell off
state-run enterprises and eliminate jobs in the years since Brazil
returned from military to civilian rule in 1985. But Sarney has yet
to fulfill those promises.
</TEXT>
