<HEAD>Airline Imposes 90-Day Suspensions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two USAir mechanics have been suspended
without pay for 90 days following a company investigation into the
emergency landing of an airliner in North Carolina last week, a
company spokesman said Wednesday.
   The action extends a temporary suspension imposed last week
after federal investigators found wheel chocks were unintentionally
left in both wheel wells before the plane took off from Washington
National Airport.
   USAir spokesman David Shipley declined to release the names of
the mechanics or details of the company's investigation.
   USAir Group, headquartered outside Washington, merged its
Piedmont subsidiary into USAir on Saturday, three days after the
Piedmont Boeing 737 with 100 people aboard on a flight from
Washington bound for Columbia, S.C. landed at Greensboro, N.C. with
only the nose and right landing gear in place.
   There were no injuries, and only the left engine was damaged.
   A NTSB spokesman said Friday the initial investigation showed
the two mechanics were responsible for the final check before the
plane was turned over to the flight crew.
   Investigators found a 2{ foot rubber wheel chock, used to keep
planes from rolling on the ground, jammed into the left wheel well,
and they believe one in the right wheel well was shaken out.
   The plane was moved six times the night before the flight, NTSB
has said.
   The investigators said ground crews sometimes stuff the chocks
in the wheel wells when moving planes.
