<FIRST>r a AM-NCSL-Politics     08-09 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NCSL-Politics,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown, Atwater Trade Political Barbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party Chairman Ronald H. Brown
attacked corruption at Housing and Urban Development during
Republican administrations Wednesday and Republican Chairman Lee
Atwater charged statehouse and congressional districts were
``rigged'' for Democrats.
   The two men rallied their party members at separate sessions at
the National Conference of State Legislatures.
   Brown said Republicans had been elected on a mandate to
eliminate waste, fraud and abuse in government but had instead
raised misdeeds to ``a new art form.''
   ``The more we turn over the HUD record, the more slime oozes
into the light,'' Brown told a gathering of about 200 Democratic
lawmakers.
   Atwater, speaking to about 300 Republican legislators in an
adjoining banquet hall, asked them to lead an assault on a
Democrat-favoring system of statehouse and congressional districts
during redistricting in 1991.
   ``Right now, most legislative and congressional districts are
rigged in favor of Democrats,'' Atwater said. ``Republican
candidates received nearly half the congressional vote in 1988, but
only make up 40 percent of the seats in Congress.
   ``We believe that the voters have a fundamental right to choose
their representatives _ freely and fairly _ to the state
legislature and to Congress. They shouldn't have to go through
vote-laundering Democrats in some smoke-filled room to make their
opinions known.''
   Brown said Republicans had used HUD as ``a dumping ground for
unemployed Republican political hacks.'' He cited as HUD abuses the
building of a housing project in Beverly Hills, Calif., a country
club in southern California and a swimming pool on New York's Long
Island.
   ``And just down the road in Stilwell, Oklahoma, they built
sewage treatment facilities to serve a single poultry processing
plant, which has yet to be opened,'' he said.
   He said Republicans under the Reagan administration gave the
Pentagon a blank check and ``looked the other way while contractors
bribed Pentagon employees and gouged the government.''
   Brown accused President George Bush of paying lip service to
important issues such as the environment and the war on drugs.
   Brown also addressed redistricting, saying said there is no
bigger priority for Democrats and that it is vital that Democrats
maintain their majority status.
   ``What I mean is that the pen that draws those lines is in the
hands of good Democrats,'' he said. ``We need to target our
resources to make sure that we hold that pen.
   ``The Republicans have threatened to litigate us to death on
redistricting plans and we expect them to do it.''
   Atwater said politics of the next decade will be shaped by what
happens during redistricting.
   ``The political landscape of the nation over the next 10 years
is going to be determined by whether we have a fair redistricting
in 1991,'' he said.
   ``When Democrats look to the future, this rigged system of
representation is about all they have left,'' Atwater said. ``We're
the party of the future. The Democrats are the party of the
political machine.''
   He said Republicans are within six seats of winning a majority
in 20 state legislative chambers and ``fair redistricting is within
our grasp.''
</TEXT>
