<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 08-09 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrested U.S. Soldiers Exchanged After Three-Hour Blockade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 9th pvs, `Panamanian military...' to
UPDATE with U.S., Panamanians condemning each other for the incident; picks
up 10th pvs, `At the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT AMADOR, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. forces blockaded Fort Amador for
more than three hours Wednesday after two American soldiers were
arrested, then withdrew after the troopers were exchanged for two
arrested Panamanians.
   U.S. Army helicopters circled overhead during the confrontation,
and Panamanian troops could be seen aiming anti-aircraft weapons at
them.
   Fort Amador is a shared area that includes barracks for
Panamanian troops, a building where Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has
an office, offices of the U.S. Southern Command offices, a U.S.
naval station and a golf course used by U.S. personnel.
   Sources said Noriega, commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces
and the country's de facto ruler, was not at the Fort Amador office
Wednesday.
   Col. Ronald Sconyers, spokesman for the Southern Command, said
the incident began when a U.S. military policeman was arrested near
El Chorillo, where the Panamanian Defense Forces general staff has
its headquarters.
   The soldier was taken to nearby Fort Amador, where another U.S.
military policeman was arrested when he tried to obtain his
comrade's release, Sconyers said.
   U.S. troops then arrested two Panamanian military policemen at
the gates to the fort and U.S. troops and armored personnel
carriers blockaded the entrance until the men were released.
   Arresting the Americans may have been retaliation for the brief
detention by U.S. authorities on Tuesday of 29 Panamanians,
including Noriega's brother-in-law and eight other soldiers.
   Panamanian military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed Sconyers' account but gave no reason for the initial
arrest.
   The Southern Command and the Defense Forces later accused each
other of violating agreements relating to movements of their
respective troops in the area.
   ``They are trying to humilitate us in our own house,'' said Maj.
Edgardo Lopez Grimaldo, a spokesman for the Defense Forces. ``We
will not be trapped into provocation, in order not to respond to
Yankee arrogance.''
   At the Pentagon in Washington, Army Maj. Kathy Wood said the
actions did not violate the Panama Canal treaties, under which
``the commander of a military area of coordination has
responsibility for the security of his area.''
   Civilians, including reporters, were allowed across the line
during the blockade at Amador, but not Panamanian soldiers.
   Reporters watched about three hours later as U.S. and Panamanian
officers met and exchanged the soldiers. The five armored personnel
carriers withdrew and the entrance was reopened.
   The blockade delayed a Panamanian anti-terrorist unit that
planned to hold an exercise at the National Bank of Panama, a
15-story building in Panama City, because the unit could not take
trucks and other equipment out of Fort Amador.
   A few dozen soldiers from the two countries lined a street that
divides nearby Quarry Heights, where Southern Command headquarters
is located, from Panama City.
   Southern Command said 29 Panamanians were detained 75 minutes
Tuesday because they entered a joint-use military area without
authorization. Among them were four military officers, including
Maj. Manuel Sieiro, Noriega's brother-in-law.
   Weapons taken from them included four automatic rifles, a
machine gun, two grenades and seven pistols, the Southern Command
said.
   The U.N. Security Council has scheduled debate for Friday on
Panama's complaint that the United States is trying to undermine it.
   Gen. Noriega was indicted in Florida last year on U.S. charges
of drug trafficking and money laundering. He denied the charges and
fought off U.S. efforts to force him to quit, including economic
sanctions against Panama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
