<FIRST>r a AM-Paris-Fire     08-09 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paris-Fire,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Strikes Sled Maker Amid Foreclosure Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH PARIS, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire blamed on faulty wiring broke out
Wednesday at the Paris Manufacturing Co., the nation's oldest
manufacturer of wooden sleds and toboggans, but didn't interfere
with a foreclosure auction.
   First Assistant Fire Chief William Grover initially said fires
which erupted in two separate painting booths in the wood-frame
manufacturing plant appeared suspicious. But by midmorning,
investigators from the state fire marshal's office had traced the
blaze to an electrical problem.
   Grover said a frayed wire short-circuited and ignited one of the
painting booths. Fueled by lacquer, the fire activated the
sprinkler system and the sudden blast of water blew burning lacquer
into the other booth, he said.
   Damage was confined largely to the painting booths.
   Wednesday was the second and final day of an auction closing the
books on one of western Maine's best-known industries.
   The sale was intended to clear the company's $1.8 million debt
to Oxford Bank and Trust Co., guaranteed by the Finance Authority
of Maine and the Small Business Administration.
   Tuesday's sale brought in $54,750 for a 27.3-acre site with saw
mill, storage buildings and equipment, and an additional $27,000
for a nearby 22-acre tract. The remaining property auctioned
Wednesday included the main manufacturing plant.

</TEXT>
