<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Temple     08-09 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Temple,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Jews Pray At Western Wall To Mourn Lost Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Jews prayed Wednesday night at the
sacred Western Wall in Jerusalem's Old City to mourn the
destruction of their temple by the Romans 1919 years ago.
   The nightlong prayer marked the start of Tisha Be-Av, or the
ninth of the Jewish lunar month of Av, the greatest day of mourning
in the Jewish calendar.
   The holiday this year was also marked by heavy security measures
linked to the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories and the annexed east Jerusalem and
fears of a possible terror attack.
   Hundreds of police officers and paramilitary border policemen
guarded the Western Wall square inside the walled Old City.
   Police also erected a special electronic gate at the entrance to
the Western Wall square and said no weapons would be allowed near
the sacred stones.
   Tisha Be-Av commemorates the destruction of the First Temple in
Jerusalem by the Babylonians in 586 B.C. and the destruction of the
Second Temple by the Roman emperor Titus in 70 a.d. The Western
Wall is the last remnant of that temple.
   The body of Jewish religious teachings lists other disasters
said to have accurred on that day, such as the fall of Beitar, the
last stronghold of anti-Roman Jewish rebels, in 135 A.D. and the
creation of a Roman temple in Jerusalem a year later.
   During the ages, Tisha Be-Av had become a symbol of misfortune
and persecution that befell the Jewish people. The expulsion of
Jews from Spain in 1492, during the period of the Inquisition, is
also said to have occurred on that day.
   The mourning for past tragedies is marked by fasting and prayer.
Near the Western Wall, religious Jews chant sections from the
Scroll of Lamentations or the Book of Job, sitting on the ground or
on low stools.
   Tisha Be-Av lasts from nightfall till afternoon on the next day.
During that period, Jews are forbidden to eat, drink, and bathe.
   Although work is technically allowed, it is customary to abstain
from it. Many Israeli businesses closed for 24 hours. Restaurants
and movie houses also closed or faced a fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
