<FIRST>r w AM-Leland-TheWait 2ndLd-Writethru a0701 08-09 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-The Wait, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0701,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland Staff Puts on Brave Front as Wait for News Contines</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Adds graf with departure of Ackerman and Wheat for Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-wishers around the country lit up the
telephones in Rep. Mickey Leland's office Wednesday as his staff
spent a third day waiting for word about the missing congressman.
   Leland, a Houston Democrat and chairman of the House Select
Committee on Hunger, disappeared Monday after his twin-engine plane
took off from Addis Ababa on its way to a refugee camp on
Ethiopia's border with Sudan, about 480 miles away.
   ``We're still waiting, anxiously,'' legislative assistant James
Williams told a caller. ``We're waiting for him to call us up and
ask us for his messages.''
   Inside Leland's personal office at the Rayburn House Office
Building, spokeswoman Alma Newsom sat at his desk conducting a
string of interviews that she said keeps her mind off the grim
possibilities.
   ``Everything is in their favor at this point. The weather is
temperate, it's not too hot or cold, and these planes do carry
adequate provisions. They're not in any immediate danger on the
ground,'' said Ms. Newsom, a friend of Leland's since their college
days.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson stopped by the office and said a prayer
for Leland with his staff, while Leland's brother, Gaston, answered
the phnes, paced the marble hallways and waited.
   ``There may be some concern that I'm not up here crying,'' Ms.
Newsom told reporters. ``Congressman Leland is an exceptionally
positive person. He does not want people who are not positive
around him. ... I just absolutely have not heard anything that
would cause alarm.''
   ``We feel he's just landed, stranded and waiting to get in touch
with us,'' Williams said between phone calls.
   Thirteen othrs were on the plane with Leland, including two of
his staff members. The aircraft was last heard from 15 minutes
after taking off Monday morning.
   As nightfall in Ethiopia ended the second day of an air and
ground search with no word, Ms. Newsom said staff members were not
letting themselves ``be anything but upbeat.''
   Meanwhile, prayers and good wishes continued to pour in.
President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Tuesday
called Leland's wife, Alison, who is six weeks' pregnant with their
second child, and CBS anchorman Dan Rather, a friend of Leland's,
called to say ``he had sent up a prayer.''
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., sent Reps. Gary
Ackerman, D-N.Y., a member of the Select Committee on Hunger
chaired by Leland, and Al Wheat, D-Mo., a member of the
Congressional Black Caucus, to Ethiopia to represent the House in
observing the search for Leland. The two, accompanied by House
Sergeat-at-Arms Jack Russ, left Andrews Air Force Base Tuesday
night.
</TEXT>
