<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-09 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>23 Die In Ethnic Strife, Extremists Raid Air Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 23 people died in ethnic
strife over the past 24 hours and Sinhalese extremists captured
sophisticated weaponry in a raid on an air force base, the
government said Wednesday.
   The government also said it would take control of the port of
Trincomalee in northeastern Sri Lanka. For two years, Indian
peacekeeping troops have had virtual authority over the port, which
is one of the world's largest natural harbors.
   On Wednesday, Sri Lankan industrialist Kanagasabai Gunaratnam
was slain by two men on a motorcycle as he sat in his car in
Colombo, a company spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Police said motives for the slaying of 72-year-old Gunaratnam
were unclear, although they appeared related to the island nation's
ethnic strife.
   Among other victims were six members of a family in Gampha, 15
miles northeast of Colombo. Military officials blamed the deaths on
the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese extremist group.
   It was not immediately clear how the other victims died.
   The front has targeted government officials and supporters,
saying Premadasa has made too many concessions to the Tamil
minority, who have been fighting since 1983 for a separate nation
in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   Government troops searched Wednesday for Sinhalese extremists
who raided an air force camp at Vavuniya, 135 miles northeast of
Colombo. The guerrillas escaped with a rocket-propelled grenade
launcher, three rockets, and a Chinese light machine gun.
   A spokesman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, said he
was unaware of Sri Lanka's announcement.
   The Sinhalese majority controls the government, military and
economy. Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of the island's 16 million
people, say they are discriminated against in jobs, education and
language.
   India intervened in Sri Lanka's internal strife after the two
nations signed a peace agreement in July 1987 to end the Tamil
rebellion. Indian peacekeeping troops arrived in the nation's
northeast to disarm the rebels, but the largest guerrilla faction
reneged on the peace agreeement.
   Sri Lanka now wants the Indian force out. The Defense Ministry
said the port of Trincomalee, which harbors more than 100 ships,
would be placed under control of the Sri Lankan navy.
   At its peak, the Indian peacekeeping force numbered 70,000, but
tapered off to 45,000 by February. India resumed troop withdrawals
on July 29, and the force now numbers about 43,000.
</TEXT>
