<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PacificSummit-Joke     08-09 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pacific Summit-Joke,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official's Joke Fails To Amuse Conference Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to a summit meeting on trade among
Pacific Rim countries said they were offended by a Bush
Administration official's joke about Soviet women and his attack on
Marxism.
   ``It was only a joke, but I don't like the joke,'' said Lu
Zu-wen, commercial consul for the Chinese Consulate in San
Francisco. ``He's a joker. I don't know what his purpose was.''
   Fred M. Zeder II, head of the government's Overseas Private
Investment Corp., began his address Tuesday with a joke in which
China's late Chairman Mao Zedong is asked by a foreign journalist
what ``might have happened if Lee Harvey Oswald had assassinated
Khrushchev rather than President Kennedy.''
   Mimicking a stereotypical Chinese accent, Zeder said Mao
replied: ``Only one thing certain. Aristotle Onassis would not have
married Mrs. Khrushchev.''
   Delegates said few listeners were amused.
   Nor was the Soviet delegate to the week-long summit happy to
hear Zeder turn to his opinion of Marxist philosophy at a gathering
designed to improve trade relations between 23 Pacific Rim nations.
   Zeder accused the Soviets of ``marching into Poland, Hungary and
Yugoslavia,'' of ``bringing Castro's Cuban mercenaries into
Nicaragua, Angola and Ethiopia,'' and of spreading Marxism ``every
place in the world.''
   Zeder's speech received scattered applause, but Soviet delegate
Vyacheslav Zilanov drew louder applause later when he criticized
Zeder's remarks.
   ``I don't agree with some of the opinions put forward by Zeder
in his morning speech,'' Zilanov said. ``I don't feel this Pacific
summit is the right place to discuss Marxist-Leninist theory and
its position right now.''
   In a telephone interview Wednesday from his home in Washington,
D.C., Zeder said he didn't mean to offend anyone. ``I was talking
to the wrong audience. I apologize to any technocrats who might
have been offended by anything.''
   The joke, he said, ``is an old, old joke'' told to him by Bob
Hope. ``It's not racist, not vulgar, not provocative. It's just
funny. I told that same joke to the ambassador from Beijing; he
thought it was very funny,'' said Zeder.
   ``I think they might have been offended by the fact that I tried
to explain that the Marxist-Leninist process didn't work,'' he
said. ``Gorbachev himself has admitted that the system is flawed.
That was my message _ that the system has failed.''
   Zeder, 68, was appointed this year to head OPIC by President
Bush.
   John Anderson, director of the Washington state Department of
Trade and Economic Development and chairman of the summit
organizing committee, said officials had reviewed Zeder's initial
speech and toned it down.
   Anderson did not give details of the earlier draft, but said
``we were looking at something that could have blown the conference
up.''
   The agency provides U.S. investors overseas with political risk
insurance, loan guarantees and other assistance,
</TEXT>
</DOC>
