<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SharkAttack     08-09 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Shark Attack,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Attacked by Shark in Bahamas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman swimmer who suffered severe hand and arm
injuries in a shark attack in the Bahamas underwent surgery at a
Miami hospital Wednesday to have the hand amputated, hospital
officials said.
   Judy St. Clair, 31, was attacked earlier in the day in waters
off Highborn Cay on Great Exuma Island, about 220 miles southeast
of Miami, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Steven Sapp.
   She was airlifted to Nassau and then to Miami for more extensive
medical treatment. She was taken into amputation surgery soon after
she arrived at Miami's Jackson Memorial Hospital, said
administrator Susan Cataldo.
   ``Yes, it's just the hand, I expect it'll be just above the
wrist,'' the administrator said, adding she didn't know which hand
was amputated.
   Ms. St. Clair is a U.S. citizen, but her hometown was not
immediately available, said hospital officials and the Coast Guard.
   Coast Guard officials said the woman was pulled from the water
with extensive bites to her arm and hand.
