<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Strike     08-09 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Strike,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Border Plants Ask Mexican Authorities To Help End Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American-run assembly plants are asking
the government to help end a wildcat strike now in its third week
that has idled 2,000 workers along the U.S.-Mexico border, company
officials said Wednesday.
   ``Everything is on hold. We're waiting to see what the
government will do,'' said James Gaffney, vice president of the
local industry assocation in Reynosa, just south of McAllen, Texas.
   The strike involves a dispute between two labor leaders vying
for control of workers in Reynosa, Gaffney said.
   The strike is the worst to hit the border industries, which
import raw materials and equipment duty-free, use cheap Mexican
labor and then export the goods.
   It has idled 15 such plants since it began 16 days ago. Local
industry has lost an estimated $500,000 daily said Osvaldo
Gutierrez, another business leader.
   ``This is a very critical situation for Reynosa,'' Gutierrez
said. ``Both local and international investors must have guarantees
of labor stability if they're going to risk their capital.''
   The so-called ``maquiladora'' industry is one of the
fastest-growing maanufacturing activities in Mexico. About 1,400
plants are strung along the Mexican side of the border, employing
392,000 workers.
   In 1985 about 800 plants with 218,000 employees were operating.
   Gaffney said the strike was caused by a dispute among Reynosa's
three unions representing the maquiladora industry. All three are
affiliated with the Federation of Mexican Workers, the country's
biggest labor organization.
   Rafael Morales de la Cruz, general secretary of one union and a
leader of another, is trying to control all three labor
organizations and many union members are resisting.
   Morales' union put up strike banners across the gates of 11
plants July 25 and kept workers out. Four other plants closed their
doors in protest.
   Morales is opposed by Abel Hernandez, another union leader.
   Representatives from the association and the Economic
Development Corporation in McAllen are asking authorities in Mexico
City to rule in favor of Hernandez, Gaffney said.
   Gaffney said all 2,000 workers affected by the strike continue
receiving their $1.20 hourly wages.
   Reynosa has 42 assembly plants, which employ 25,000 workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
