<FIRST>r i AM-Pirates-Refugees     08-09 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pirates-Refugees,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Tell of Thai Pirate Attack That Killed 71</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S.MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai pirates took pleading
Vietnamese refugees from the hold of a boat one by one, beat them
with sticks and iron rods and then hacked them to death, survivors
told refugee officials Wednesday.
   The officials said 71 Vietnamese were reported dead.
   The pirates sank the refugees' boat by ramming it twice with
their own boat and then systematically killed survivors swimming in
the sea, they added.
   Jean Marie Fakhouri, chief representative in Malaysia for the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, said 13 who survived
were interviewed Wednesday by U.N. and Malaysian refugee officials
and gave this account:
   Their boat left Vietnam on Thursday, Aug. 3, carrying 58 men, 15
women and 11 children.
   On Saturday night, two fishing boats intercepted them and towed
them for some distance. Fishing crew boarded their boat and robbed
them of their valuables.
   Some Vietnamese were transferred to the fishing boats. The rest
were kept in the hold of the refugee boat.
   The fishermen-pirates then brought up men singly from the hold,
clubbed them and then killed them with axes, the refugee officials
said.
   The men cried and pleaded, but the pirates, whom they
ascertained to be Thais because of their appearance and language,
showed no mercy.
   ``In the panic that followed, others tried to storm out of the
hold, but were contained by the pirates, who tied fishing nets over
the opening. The trapped men then tried to cut their way through
the nets without success,'' Fakhouri reported, quoting the
survivors.
   He said the ramming, sinking and killing of Vietnamese in the
water followed, but 13 survived by swimming to an oil rig, where
workers rescued them.
   The rig, off Kuala Trengganu, 180 miles northeast of Kuala
Lumpur, was operated by Esso, a subsidiary of Exxon of the United
States.
   The latest incident brought to 271 the number of refugees
reported killed by pirates in the South China Sea off Malaysia this
year in four attacks.
</TEXT>
