<FIRST>u a AM-OhioCasino 2ndLd-Writethru a0786 08-09 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ohio Casino, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0786,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gambling Proposal Comes Up Short, Backers Scramble For Signatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with group giving up on petition
drive; picks up 7th graf pvs: `Spitzer's committee ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT E. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a plan to authorize casino
gambling in Ohio conceded defeat Wednesday after failing in a
last-minute push Wednesday to place a proposal on the Nov. 7
ballot, officials said.
   The casino advocates notified the state shortly before 10 p.m.
that they had given up the effort to get enough petition signatures
by a midnight deadline, said Steven Fought, a spokesman for the
Secretary of State's office.
   Auto dealer Alan Spitzer, spokesman for the group and a
potential casino owner, seemed to concede defeat at a news
conference Wednesday afternoon and made plans for a similar effort
for the 1990 ballot.
   The proposal got new life, however, when the Secretary of
State's office agreed to accept the signatures until midnight,
Fought said.
   The group needed 306,661 signatures, or 10 percent of the number
of people who voted in the 1986 governor's election, to put the
proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot.
   Spitzer said the LUV Ohio Committee _ LUV stands for Let Us Vote
_ collected between 250,000 and 275,000 signatures.
   Spitzer's committee began petitions in June after the state
Senate, despite passage by the House, rejected a bill authorizing a
casino in Lorain.
   The ballot proposal would go further. It would permit casinos in
seven so-called casino districts, generally surrounding and
including Ohio's largest cities, subject to approval of voters in
local elections.
   Spitzer, whose family owns car dealerships throughout central
and northern Ohio, says the plan would help create jobs and boost
the economy.
   He has talked of building a $300 million to $400 million resort
complex and casino in an abandoned shipyard in Lorain, saying it
would breathe new life into the northern Ohio steel city's economy.
   At a news conference, Spitzer blamed a late start on the
petition drive and a lack of people needed to circulate petitions.
``Time and people _ we didn't have enough of either,'' he said.
</TEXT>
