<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Markham 1stLd-Writethru a0657 08-09 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Markham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>James Markham, Paris Bureau Chief of New York Times, Dead at 46</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs, quoting newspaper on new position, rifle near
body.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James M. Markham, Paris bureau chief of The New
York Times, died Wednesday in an apparent suicide, the newspaper
said. He was 46.
   Markham headed the newspaper's bureaus in Saigon, Beirut, Madrid
and Bonn before his 1987 assignment to Paris.
   He reported for The Associated Press in New Delhi and West
Africa before joining the Times in 1971.
   Times Executive Editor Max Frankel said police found Markham in
his home in Paris on Wednesday morning and that they believe it was
a suicide. He did not say how Markham died.
   ``We mourn the loss of a wise and perceptive correspondent. Jim
distinguished himself on many continents and almost every day made
the Times a better paper,'' Frankel said.
   Markham was a Phi Beta Kappa graduate of Princeton University
and a Rhodes Scholar at Bailliol College, Oxford.
   Survivors include his wife, Stephanie; his parents; his sister;
a daughter; and a son.
   In its Thursday edition, the Times said Markham died apparently
of a self-inflicted gunshot wound. It said a hunting rifle lay next
to his body, but no note was found.
   The newspaper said Markham was named deputy foreign editor last
month and was due to leave France next month to take up his new
position in New York.
</TEXT>
