<FIRST>a i AM-Philippines-Land Adv18   08-09 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Land, Adv 18,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Philippines Land Reform Program Bogged Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once hailed as the showpiece of
President Corazon Aquino's government, the land reform program is
so bogged down in corruption and red tape and crippled by loopholes
that even the official responsible for it wants to change it.
   Mrs. Aquino signed the Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Law in
June, 1988, to redistribute land to nearly 4 million peasants and
free rural Filipinos from what she called ``their ancient poverty.''
   Land reform was widely hailed as essential to defeat the
20-year-old communist insurgency in the countryside and break the
grip on power enjoyed by powerful landlords.
   Last year, the government distributed 150,000 land titles
covering some 254,000 acres. Most of the titles were awarded to
rice and corn farmers, making the effort merely an extension of the
land reform program decreed by ousted President Ferdinand E. Marcos.
   Marcos' program covered only corn and rice-producing lands but
the Aquino plan encompasses all crop holdings.
   Critics claim the new law is so flawed that it stands little
chance of achieving its goals and of being more successful than the
dozen previous attempts at land reform since the 1930s.
   Under the program, expected to cost $10 billion, the government
will pay landlords for their land. Those who then take possession
must repay the government over 30 years at 6 percent annual
interest.
   Militant farmer groups claim few can afford to repay and have
proposed that peasants pay half a sack of rice per hectare (2.47
acres) a year for three decades.
   Most critics also cite loopholes favoring landlords. Landowners
can retain five hectares (12.3 acres) plus three hectares (7.4
acres) for each direct heir over age 15.
   The Department of Agrarian Reform acknowledges that it is
uncertain how much of the 24 million acres of agricultural land has
effectively been removed from the program by exemptions.
   Under the program, estates of more than 50 hectares (123.5
acres) are to remain untouched until 1992. The program also gives
landowners the option of establishing profit-sharing plans for
workers in lieu of transferring titles.
   Among those who opted for this alternative was Mrs. Aquino's
family, the Cojuangcos, who established a stock plan for workers on
their 12,350-acre sugarcane estate in central Luzon.
   A review committee suspended the implementation of the profit
sharing scheme after critics claimed Mrs. Aquino's family grossly
undervalued their property.
   ``If land reform means to set the peasant free from the
political and economic domination of the landlord which is the
essence of a genuine agricultural reform program then, on the
whole, it failed to break land monopoly,'' said Jaime Tadeo, leader
of the leftist Philippines Peasant Movement. ``What it gave were
just crumbs, a few leftovers.''
   In an attempt to get more large estates for redistribution
before 1992, the government offered landlords the option of selling
their property now.
   But in several cases, the government paid far more for the land
than it was found to be worth, triggering allegations of corruption.
   The most controversial case involved the proposed purchase of
4,666 acres in Camarines Sur province for the peso equivalent of
$2.9 million. The sale was blocked when investigators found the
land was worth only about $143,000.
   ``Those scandals have given more ammunition to those attacking
the program,'' said Rep. Edsel Lagman, chairman of the House of
Representatives' agrarian reform committee. ``Those supporting it
are now wavering and the skeptical are slowly joining those who
have been opposing it.''
   The scandal led to the resignation of Philip Juico as the
agrarian reform secretary and suspension of a voluntary sales
program pending a review of the more than 700 sale offers.
   Juico was replaced by Immigration Chairman Miriam Defensor
Santiago, who recently told a House of Representatives committee
that the current law is ``a hodge-podge full of inconsistencies''
and should be amended.
   She said the provisions for establishing ``just compensation''
for landowners was too complicated and that the reform aspects of
the program had been ``watered-down'' by landlord blocs in Congress.
   Mrs. Santiago also said the government lacks the money to
purchase lands under the current system.
   The government had hoped to finance the program in part through
the sale of assets recovered from Marcos and his associates. But so
far, that effort has generated only $340 million. About $140
million in foreign aid is also available for land reform.
   Problems in the land reform program have given the rebel New
People's Army a propaganda coup. It has announced its own ``land
reform'' program in which it distributes to supporters property
seized from landlords.
   The government estimates indicate the rebels have seized more
than 76,500 acres nationwide, but rebel spokesmen claim to have
handed out 111,000 acres in the central Visayas islands alone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 18</NOTE>
