<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv11   08-09 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 11,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 11, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet A.A. Termed ``Reconstruction of the Soul.'' ^With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As head of the first Soviet office promulgating
the tenets of Alcoholics Anonymous, Helen Kuzmicheva says the
approach makes for ``reconstruction of the soul.''
   ``It offers not just recovery from alcoholism, but a program of
spiritual recovery,'' she says. ``It brings out a completely new
personality.''
   Ms. Kuzmicheva, an attractive blonde Russian of 38 and
coordinator of the newly opened Soviet-American Alcoholism Center
in Moscow, says the A.A. technique is being found as effective
there as in America.
   After all, ``we are human beings, all of us,'' she said in an
interview. ``Due to the changes being made in our country, we also
have been able to acquire the movement.''
   Among participants, she said, believers ``speak of God'' helping
them overcome their addiction. ``Others speak of a higher power.
They all recognize they need a higher power exerted to help them.
   ``As to what kind, they need time to understand it is God.''
   Such religious terminology may seem unusual for a
health-promoting agency in an officially atheist society, but
millions of people there are devout believers.
   However, A.A. itself steers clear of overtly religious
affirmations or criteria, acknowledging only that help of a
``higher power'' is essential in overcoming alcoholism, but leaving
that aspect undefined.
   Individuals may interpret that power as the group and its
mutually supportive associations, or may consider it the
Judeo-Christian God who acts in human affairs, or both. Whichever
involves a spiritual dimension.
   It is purposely kept vague, so as to take in all comers.
   ``God as you understand him,'' Ms. Kuzmicheva puts it, using a
typical AA phrase, meaning that the power is whatever recovering
alcoholics consider it.
   ``They had lost control over themselves and lost the very
quality of being human when they drank,'' she said. ``When they see
life with sober eyes, miracles happen in their lives. They grow
spiritually.
   ``They regain their best spiritual selves.''
   Ms. Kuzmicheva, a professional educator who served as a factory
personnel director before taking the post at the new Moscow center,
recently completed a month-long U.S. tour with three Soviet A.A.
members.
   Accompanying them was the Rev. J.W. Canty, a New York Episcopal
priest who had established the new Soviet center, and who in 1987
had started the Soviet's first A.A. group called Moscow Beginners.
   He says Soviet authorities initially were dubious of the
project, but their attitude has changed to ``cautious respect'' now
that they are ``seeing alcoholics get a second chance at life.''
   On the 16-city tour concluded in late June, the group had
addressed school and church gatherings, met with numerous A.A.
groups, usually in churches, but also with an atheist-agnostic A.A.
group in New York.
   They also toured various health facilities and met with former
Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter and their wives, attending
a Sunday school class taught by Carter in his hometown of Plains,
Ga.
   Ms. Kuzmicheva said the Scripture lesson, as Carter interpreted
it, emphasized that when God gives his promises, they sooner or
later are fulfilled.
   ``This is very promising for our country,'' she said, adding
that recent liberalizing developments there pointed toward a more
fulfilling future.
   However, like America, the Soviet has immense problems with
alcoholism. Soviet leader Gorbachev in 1985 launched a campaign
against it, but popular resistance forced him to ease some of the
restrictions.
   ``Unfortunately the problem is very acute in our country,'' Ms.
Kuzmicheva said, estimating there are 10 to 15 million alcoholics
in a population of 290 million.
   ``We have seen how strong and spiritual the A.A. movement is in
this country and we hope to have the same success in our country,''
she said. ``It will work. It will work all over the world.''
   On the U.S. tour, the Soviet A.A. members often gave their
testimony in U.S. meetings, using only first names as customary in
A.A. Two of them were atheists, one of them a believer.
   They told of families breaking up, being repeatedly
hospitalized, but not being able to quit drinking until admitting
they couldn't without help of a higher power. Saha, 43, an engineer
and a non-believer puts it this way:
   ``With alcoholism, you have to admit despair before you
experience victory.''
   Ms. Kuzmicheva, not an alcoholic herself, says she is a
believer, but not a regular church-goer. ``Many did not believe in
God when they drank, but when they become sober, they begin to
believe. ''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
