<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-`Bordertown     08-09 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-`Bordertown,' Adv 25-27,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 25-27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Bordertown' Filmed in Authentic Replica of Western Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Richard Comar says the set built for
``Bordertown'' is so authentic a cowboy from the Old West could
ride in and feel at home.
   An entire town was built on a ranch east of Vancouver, Canada,
for the half-hour weekly Western series on the Family Channel.
Sixty-five carpenters worked 5{ weeks to build the half-million
dollar town.
   ``Every building is complete inside and out,'' said Comar, who
stars as U.S. Marshal Jack Craddock.
   ``We film everything there, with no studio work at all. In the
winter the streets are muddy. The prop people came in and _ in the
general store, for instance _ they stocked every shelf and drawer.
If you open the lace drawer there's lace in it. The saloon has
antique bottles. The livery stable has period tack, and the saddles
are a hundred years old.''
   The show is set in a town that straddles the U.S.-Canadian
border. Comar plays a gunfighter-turned-marshal, while John Brennan
is Clive Bennett, a Canadian Mountie who goes strictly by the book.
French actress Sophie Barjac also co-stars as the town doctor. It
is a joint Canadian-French production that will also be shown in
Canada, France, Germany and Italy.
   Comar said he compares Craddock to a New York street cop and
Bennett to a London bobby. Craddock is a functioning illiterate who
is a pack rat and is terribly disorganized. Bennett is very
organized and a member of a semi-military organization. They have a
bit of an ``Odd Couple'' relationship.
   ``The authentic town and props help us get the feeling of what
the West was like,'' Comar said on a visit here. He was attired in
his costume: chaps, a handmade gun belt, and a heavy-duty cotton
shirt with a bib front that can be taken off when it gets dirty.
   ``Craddock's looking for a soft place to retire. He's a former
Texas Ranger. He worked on a ranch near Laredo and killed a Mexican
rancher's son while stealing horses in Mexico. In retaliation they
killed his son and daughter. That's when he went to Bordertown to
ease the pain.''
   The Western series has made a small comeback on the networks,
which have two shows this year, CBS' ``Paradise'' and ABC's ``The
Young Riders.'' But the Western is thriving on the Family Channel.
In addition to ``Bordertown,'' the cable network as ``Gunsmoke,''
``Wagon Train,'' ``Bonanza: The Lost Episodes,'' ``The Big Valley''
and ``The Rifleman.''
   On Saturdays and Sundays, the Westerns start at 11:30 a.m. EDT
with ``Roy Rogers.''
   The Family Channel has also ordered a new version of ``Zorro,''
to be made in Spain.
   ``They're considering a two-hour `Bordertown' movie,'' Comar
said. ``It would be the pilot we never made. It would be great to
get a superior story and to be able to flesh it out.
   ``We sometimes have a guest villain on the show, but we try to
concentrate on human relations. The things that are happening in
the town. People get tired of violence, so the jeopardy caused by
the bad guys is secondary. We've also had stories about real
people. In one show Bat Masterson came to town trailing four men.
In another, President Garfield's life is threatened when he comes
to town. He's assassinated elsewhere, however.''
   Comar is a former stage manager and lighting director for rock
groups and ballet companies. He lived in Paris for two years and
worked there off and on for six to eight years.
   During time off from ``Bordertown'' he went to New Zealand to
co-star with Susanna York in an episode of ``The Ray Bradbury
Theater.'' Last summer, he played a television executive in the
Home Box Office miniseries ``Glory, Glory.'' He was an FBI agent in
the CBS miniseries ``Echoes in The Darkness,'' and had roles is the
movies ``Switching Channels,'' ``Short Circuit II'' and ``Big
Town.''
   ``My wife, Leslie, and I moved to Los Angeles a year ago but
we've only spent three months in our house,'' he said. ``I've been
working in Canada or New Zealand. We're expecting our first child
on Labor Day.''
   Comar said when he auditioned for ``Bordertown'' it was for the
role of the mountie.
   ``I'm well-educated, I'm neat, I hate guns,'' he said. ``I'm the
complete opposite of Craddock. My wife hates it that I don't shave
for five months. She doesn't mind the long hair.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug. 25-27</NOTE>
</DOC>
