<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-09 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0827</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge heard the first in an expected
parade of guilty pleas when two brothers became the first traders
arraigned on charges stemming from a federal probe of fraudulent
trading at the world's largest futures exchanges.
   Brian Sledz, 29, and James Sledz, 24, pleaded guilty Tuesday to
one count each of violating the Commodities Exchange Act. The elder
brother also pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud, and the
younger to one count of mail fraud.
   The brothers are among 46 traders indicted Aug. 2 in the FBI
probe of the Merc and the Chicago Board of Trade. Published reports
have said as many as 30 defendants are expected to plead guilty and
cooperate with authorities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick Wang resigned as president of Wang
Laboratories Inc., the company founded by his Chinese immigrant
father, and the stock of the troubled computer maker jumped 20
percent.
   Analysts said Wang's resignation on Tuesday signaled the
company's intention to get serious about its problems, which
include a recently announced $375 million quarterly loss.
   The stock rose to $6.87{ a share from $5.75 a share on the
American Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on three-year Treasury notes fell to
the lowest level in 18 months as the government began a series of
huge debt auctions intended to raise $44.5 billion this week.
   The Treasury sold $10 billion in three-year notes at an average
yield of 7.93 percent Tuesday, down from 9.12 percent at the last
auction on May 9 and the lowest rate since averaging 7.42 percent
on Feb. 2, 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $2.99 billion more in
consumer debt than they retired in June, the government reported,
as the pace of borrowing slowed in part because of declining auto
sales.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday that consumer credit in
June rose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.1 percent, down
from May's revised 7.3 percent rate. The May increase was revised
from $3.6 billion to $4.2 billion.
   Consumer credit increased 8.5 percent over all of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp., a low-profile metal
manufacturer, announced Tuesday it has acquired a 6.6 percent
interest in Midway Airlines Inc. and may attempt to take control of
the mid-sized airline.
   But Midway ``has no interest in being acquired'' and has not had
discussions with Ampco-Pittsburgh, David R. Hinson, the airline's
chairman and chief executive, said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots are supporting a
continuation of their 5-month-old strike, union officials said.
   Air Line Pilots Association members meeting in Newark, N.J.,
voted 203-15 Tuesday in favor of sustaining the strike, union
officials said. Late Monday, Eastern pilots in Atlanta voted
493-121 not to return to work.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year in corporate limbo ended for Norden
Systems Inc. with the announcement that the subsidiary of United
Technologies Corp. is no longer for sale.
   The Norwalk-based manufacturer of radar systems and other
electronic military equipment was put up for sale in April 1988,
but UTC said Tuesday it decided to keep it after receiving offers
it said were inadequate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoylake Investments Ltd. released details of its
cashless offer for BAT Industries PLC, but BAT again advised
shareholders not to accept the offer valued at about $21.6 billion.
   Hoylake said it values its stock-and-debt offer for BAT at the
equivalent of $14.14 a share, but the stock closed at the
equivalent of $13.65 a share Tuesday on London's Stock Exchange, up
5 cents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a development that could help
Spanish-language television compete for advertising revenue,
Nielsen Media Research said it has been selected to develop a
national Hispanic television rating service.
   The rating service will attempt to define the audience for
Spanish-language programming among people who identify themselves
as Hispanic, information one executive called critical to the
growth of the medium.
   Nielsen, the leader in English-language TV ratings for nearly 40
years, said Tuesday it had signed a multimillion-dollar contract to
develop the Hispanic ratings service with the two largest
Spanish-language television operators, Univision Holdings Inc. and
Telemundo Group Inc.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed again Tuesday to another post-crash high as
the Dow Jones industrial average finished just under the 2,700 mark
in active trading.
   The widely watched Dow average of 30 industrials rose 4.18
points to 2,699.17, just 23.25 points short of the record high
closing of 2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Bond prices finished mixed.
   The dollar fell against most major currencies.
   Cotton futures prices surged; grain futures fell; crude oil and
precious metals futures rose; and livestock futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
