<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Who'sBlue     08-09 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Who's Blue,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Drops Complaint Against Computer Distributor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHPORT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM has decided to drop its objection to
a Long Island computer distributor's use of the name Big Blue
Products Inc., but the owner of the smaller firm says the whole
experience has left him cold.
   Jeff Alnwick, owner of Big Blue Products Inc., says
International Business Machines Corp. had no right to question his
use of the name and caused his company to lose thousands of dollars
in lawyer's fees and missed sales.
   ``Their sneezing cost me $20,000,'' he said.
   IBM spokeswoman Cynthia Stevens said IBM has decided to let
Alnwick's company use ``Big Blue'' as long as there is no confusion
and Alnwick's company does not trade on IBM's reputation.
   Alnwick, owner of a 5-year-old computer products distribution
company, received a letter in May from IBM telling him to stop
using the ``Big Blue'' name.
   Alnwick hired attorneys and discovered IBM's trademark
application for ``Big Blue'' had been denied just before the letter
was sent.
   Concerning the denial of the trademark application, Stevens
said, ``It's standard procedure ... It is not unusual. It is part
of the process with the Patent and Trademark Office.''
   She said has resubmitted the application with several requested
amendments. Both companies have ``Big Blue'' trademark applications
pending. In the meantime, IBM says it already has a trademark under
common law, even though it is not registered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SoftwareMergers     08-09 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Software Mergers,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acquisition Activity Shrinks in Software and Service Industries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mergers and acquisitions in the field of
computer software and services slowed sharply in the first half of
1989, an investment banking firm said.
   The number of deals fell 12 percent and the value of the deals
dropped 65 percent, reflecting the scarcity of mega-deals,
according to Broadview Associates of Fort Lee, N.J.
   ``The industry is catching its breath after the exceptional
levels of activity in early 1988,'' Charles Federman, a partner in
the firm, said in a news release Tuesday.
   Broadview prepares the figures for Adapso, the Arlington,
Va.-based computer software and services industry association.
   The biggest deal of the half-year was the $320 million purchase
of Cullinet Software Inc. by Computer Associates International
Inc., the world's biggest software company.
   The figures did not include the buying spree of International
Business Machines Corp. because IBM did not buy entire companies.
So far this year it has made 10 minority investments, Broadview
said.
   The number of deals fell to 168 from 190 a year earlier, while
the value of deals plunged to $1.9 billion from $5.4 billion. The
value of deals was $2.1 billion in first-half 1987 and $1.9 billion
in first-half 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
