<FIRST>u f BC-McCaw-LIN     08-09 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-McCaw-LIN,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Extends Bid For LIN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. on
Tuesday announced a three-week extension of its $110-per-share cash
offer for all shares of LIN Broadcasting Corp.
   McCaw's action came more than a week after a LIN-imposed
deadline for a negotiated buyout pact passed without agreement.
   LIN, a New York-based cellular telephone, television,
broadcasting and publishing concern, said on July 31, its deadline,
that its board would pursue other options.
   McCaw's outstanding hostile tender offer of $110 per share for
LIN stock it doesn't already own had been scheduled to expire at
midnight EDT Friday. It will now expire at midnight EDT Sept. 1,
McCaw said.
   About 1.07 million LIN shares have been tendered, McCaw said
Tuesday.
   LIN has said the $110 offer is inadequate. There was no
immediate comment from LIN about the McCaw extension.
   The two companies said in mid-July they were talking about a
possible buyout at $127.50 a share. But Kirkland-based McCaw said
July 21 it had suspended those talks pending further review.
   After that, LIN set a July 31 deadline for reaching a definite
agreement under which McCaw would acquire LIN stock for $127.50 a
share, an offer that would value LIN's 53.9 million shares at
nearly $6.9 billion.
   But that deadline passed without agreement.
   McCaw is the nation's largest cellular phone operator.
</TEXT>
