<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WangResigns Bjt   08-09 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wang Resigns, Bjt,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frederick Wang, Son of Wang Labs Founder, Resigns As President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos NY80, LOW1 of Aug. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry analysts and Wall Street welcomed the
decision by Frederick Wang to resign as president of the troubled
computer company founded by his father.
   Share prices in Wang Laboratories Inc. jumped 20 percent after
the announcement Tuesday.
   Analysts said Wang's resignation signaled the Lowell-based
company's intention to get serious about its problems, which
include a recently announced $375 million quarterly loss.
   ``Like a general who lost a battle, he accepted responsibility
and it will have a beneficial effect on Wall Street,'' said Michael
Geran, a computer analyst at Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   The stock rose to $6.87{ a share from $5.75 on the American
Stock Exchange.
   Still, some analysts said the company will have trouble finding
a strong, independent manager to lead it out of its troubles as
long as An Wang, the company's 69-year-old founder and chairman,
continues to exert control.
   ``A good aggressive executive doesn't want to be No. 2,'' said
John Jones, of Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco.
   The 11-member board of directors assembled for a special meeting
Monday night at Wang headquarters and the younger Wang resigned as
president and chief operating officer.
   The board named as acting president Harry H.S. Chou, currently a
vice chairman and director of the international computer maker. A
search committee for a new president was formed.
   Frederick Wang, 38, is a computer mathematician who worked in
the family business for 17 years. He was elevated to the presidency
in 1986.
   ``There is a general perception that (Fred Wang) was in over his
head. But he was dealing with basic change in the minicomputer
business,'' Geran said.
   ``I believe this action is in the best interest of Wang
Laboratories at this time,'' Fred Wang said in a statement.
``Employees and customers will be best served by a speedy
resolution to the company's current situation.''
   An Wang, in a statement, called his son's resignation ``in
keeping with his constant devotion to doing what he felt was in the
best interest of the company.''
   In November 1986, the elder Wang stepped down as president and
was replaced by his son but retained the job of chief executive
officer. The day his son resigned, An Wang had returned to work
part-time after recovering from surgery for cancer of the esophagus.
   The younger Wang will remain on the board and undertake special
projects.
   Prospects for the company ``depend on the health of the
doctor,'' Jones said, referring to the elder Wang, who holds a
doctorate from Harvard in computer science and often is called by
that title. ``If the doctor's healthy, they'll bring in a president
and they'll try to resurrect themselves.''
   The Wangs hold a controlling interest in the company and have
resisted any suggestion they sell it, preferring instead to try to
get the business back on its feet.
   Jones, the Montgomery Securities analyst, said stockholders
would benefit most if the company were sold or, at the very least,
if An Wang stepped out of the way.
   Last week, the company announced a $375 million quarterly loss
and said it it suspended dividend payments. Its financial
predicament put it in violation of a bank-lending agreement, the
company noted.
   Most of the quarterly loss resulted from a $237 million pre-tax
charge to cover the cost of a restructuring that involved closing
factories, cutting jobs in its worldwide work force of 28,000
people, and lowering the book value of outdated assets.
   Wang stock has lost more than 80 percent of its value since
early 1984, when it traded at more than $35 a share.
   Founded in 1951, the company made its reputation in the 1970s in
office word processors. But sales began to slip with the increasing
popularity of personal computers. Its minicomputer business fell
behind as well, eclipsed by workstations.
   Paul Henning, a Wang spokesman, said Tuesday of the resignation,
``We wanted to give a consistent message that we are doing
everything and anything possible, even taking steps that are
painful,'' he said.
   ``We have a lot of work to do,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
