<DOCNO> AP890809-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerCredit     08-09 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Credit,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports Consumer Debt Rose at Slower Pace in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $2.99 billion more in
consumer debt than they retired in June, the government reported,
as the pace of borrowing slowed in part because of declining auto
sales.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday that consumer credit in
June rose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.1 percent, down
from May's revised 7.3 percent rate. The May increase was revised
from $3.6 billion to $4.2 billion.
   Consumer credit increased 4.3 percent in April after rising 6.6
percent in March and 9.5 percent in February.
   Consumer credit increased 8.5 percent over all of 1988.
   Consumer spending is watched closely as a barometer of the
economy's health since it represents two-thirds of overall economic
activity.
   Economic growth has been slowing recently, prompting concern
that Federal Reserve efforts to contain inflation could move the
economy into a recession instead of the ``soft-landing'' it seeks.
   Economist Sandra Shaber of The Futures Group, a consulting firm
here, said the fact that consumer spending does not appear to be
collapsing helps take the heat of the economy and reduce
inflationary pressures.
   The Commerce Department reported earlier that retail sales had
fallen 0.4 percent in June, dragged down in part by poor sales of
autos. But excluding the automotive category, overall retail sales
actually rose 0.1 percent, it said.
   The Fed reported Tuesday that auto loans fell $267 million in
June, a 1.1 percent decline on a seasonally adjusted annual basis.
They had risen 4.5 percent in May and 3.3 percent in April.
   But Ms. Shaber said car sales increased in July, ``so I think
that the business of liquidating car loans is a very temporary kind
of phenomena that's not going to continue and you might see a
little bit of increase in car loans in July.''
   Leading the overall consumer credit increase in June was the
category of debt that includes credit cards. It rose $ 3.1 billion,
a 20 percent annual rate of growth, after increasing 13 percent in
May and 11 percent in April.
   Ms. Shaber said this reflects a shift toward retail credit, ``to
soft goods like apparel and small items.''
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate increased
$404 million, a 2.5 percent annual rate of advance, but down from
7.2 percent in May and 2.8 percent in April.
   Borrowing for mobile homes fell for the fifth consecutive month,
declining by $257 million or 12.9 percent on an annual basis. That
followed drops of 2.l percent in May and 8.7 percent in April.
   The various changes left total consumer debt in June at a
seasonally adjusted $701.19 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HispanicTVRatings Bjt   08-09 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hispanic TV Ratings, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nielsen Plans to Develop National Hispanic TV Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of the nation's two largest
Spanish-language television operations say they will be better
equipped to compete for advertising dollars once a new national
Hispanic television rating service is in operation.
   Nielsen Media Research's service will attempt to define the
audience for Spanish-language programming among people who identify
themselves as Hispanic, information one executive called critical
to the growth of the medium.
   Nielsen, the leader in English-language TV ratings for nearly 40
years, said Tuesday it had signed a multimillion-dollar contract to
develop the Hispanic ratings service with the two largest
Spanish-language television operators, Univision Holdings Inc. and
Telemundo Group Inc.
   For several months, Univision and Telemundo have been reviewing
proposals from a half-dozen research firms for an Hispanic audience
measurement system.
   Executives of the two companies said the Nielsen Hispanic
ratings will help them attract spending by advertisers and agencies
who in the past have been skeptical about the estimated size of the
Spanish-language TV audience.
   Univision, a subsidiary of Hallmark Cards Inc., is the nation's
largest Spanish-language communications concern, operating a TV
network reaching 85 percent of the estimated 6 million Hispanic
households.
   Telemundo Group operates the nation's second-largest
Spanish-language network, reaching about 70 percent of all Hispanic
households.
   Plans for the Hispanic ratings service, disclosed at a news
conference here, call for a pilot test beginning this fall in the
Los Angeles area, which has a large Hispanic population. Nielsen
plans to begin recruiting 200 families for the sample group there
starting next month.
   Nielsen, a division of Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp., plans to expand
the service nationally to 800 Hispanic households in late 1990 or
early 1991. Nielsen's national sample for all programming is about
4,000 families of all kinds.
   Carlos E. Garcia, research director for the firm Research
Resources in Agoura Hills, Calif., said the Hispanic population has
been growing much more rapidly than the general population and is
expected next year to reach 22 million, or about 10 percent of the
total U.S. population.
   There is some evidence that advertisers are beginning to
recognize the economic clout that this group represents, which
Garcia said the government estimates at $160 billion this year.
   Hispanic Business magazine estimated that 50 leading advertisers
spent $500.1 million on advertising to the Hispanic market last
year, up 12 percent from $490.7 million a year earlier.
   In the past week, companies such as Coca-Cola Co. and Burger
King Corp. have announced plans to increase their efforts at
reaching Hispanics with Spanish-language advertising.
   But Henry R. Silverman, chief executive of Telemundo Group, said
advertisers are spending less than 1 percent of their estimated $30
billion annual television ad budgets on Spanish-language stations.
   He said one reason was skepticism about the size of the audience
for Spanish-language programs.
   Telemundo and Univision subscribe to a ratings service that uses
weekly interviews to estimate their audience size, he said.
   Silverman said he expects the Nielsen ratings to confirm that 60
percent to 70 percent of Hispanic households are watching
Spanish-language television, and that once advertisers recognize it
their spending on the medium will rise.
   Nielsen plans to use so-called people meters for the
Spanish-language program ratings. The electronic devices allow
people to push buttons that immediately record who in the family is
watching particular shows.
   Nielsen has been using people meters for its national
English-language ratings service for two years.
   J. William Grimes, president and chief executive of Univision
Holdings, said Spanish-language television networks face the same
problems in dealing with advertisers as cable networks faced in the
early 1980s before Nielsen started measuring their audiences.
   He said programming improvements and Nielsen audience ratings
enabled cable networks to boost ad revenues to about $1.3 billion
this year from $50 million at the start of the 1980s.
   Grimes said the quality of Spanish-language programming is ``a
long way beyond'' where cable TV was at the start of the decade and
said the new Nielsen ratings could prove ``critical to the growth
of Spanish-language TV.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MidwayBid Bjt   08-09 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midway Bid, Bjt,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ampco-Pittsburgh Announces 6.6 Percent Stake in Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the wake of Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp.'s
announcement that it has acquired a 6.6 percent interest in Midway
Airlines Inc., the carrier's management is waiting to see whether
the suitor will seek control.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh said in a document submitted to the Securities
and Exchange Commission that it had acquired 662,000 shares of
Midway common stock through a Delaware subsidiary, Ampco-Pittsburgh
Securities III Corp. The filing was made public Tuesday.
   ``Ampco-Pittsburgh has not contacted the company in connection
with this investment,'' said David R. Hinson, chairman and chief
executive officer of Chicago-based Midway.
   The manufacturing concern said it bought the Midway shares ``for
investment and to acquire a significant equity interest'' in the
airline.
   Midway's stock reacted favorably to the disclosure. In composite
New York Stock Exchange trading, it climbed $1.50 a share to close
at $20.50.
   The SEC disclosure document said Pittsburgh-based Ampco ``may
also consider seeking to acquire control'' of Midway ``in the
future, although they have no plans or proposals to do so at
present.''
   According to the filing, Ampco-Pittsburgh Securities III bought
the Midway shares at prices ranging from $14.75 to $18 between July
25 and last Thursday for a total of $10.3 million.
   Hinson said Thursday that Midway had not been approached by
anyone seeking to take over the airline, despite heavy trading in
the company's stock.
   Midway ``has no interest in being acquired,'' he said,
attributing the stock activity to new interest in airlines as
takeover targets.
   Midway was founded 10 years ago at the start of airline
deregulation, when it served three Midwest cities from Chicago _
Cleveland, Detroit and Kansas City, said spokeswoman Sandra Allen.
   The airline now serves 51 U.S. cities, from Los Angeles to
Boston, and from Chicago to Miami, she said.
   Midway recently announced it had ordered 74 new jets from
McDonnell-Douglas worth about $2 billion.
   The airline, the nation's 16th-largest carrier, operates from
Midway Airport on Chicago's Southwest Side and has 4,300 employees,
Ms. Allen said.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh and its subsidiaries _ which include Buffalo
Forge Co. and Union Electric Steel Corp. _ make and sell engineered
products. Ampco is the sole shareholder in the subsidiary holding
the airline stock.
   The company is a mystery to some airline analysts.
   ``They aren't a big player,'' said Bob Joedicke, an analyst for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``I've never heard of
them.''
   Joedicke described Midway as a ``niche'' carrier, handling just
0.8 percent of the nation's air traffic.
   ``Their niche is that they dominate Midway Airport in Chicago,
which is much closer to downtown than O'Hare,'' he said.
   ``It has the advantage that a lot of businessmen appreciate
coming into Midway from New York,'' Joedicke said. He said the
carrier has ``developed quite a successful hub in Chicago for
east-west traffic.''
   Last week, Midway announced it had reached a $210 million deal
with Miami-based Eastern Airlines to purchase routes, gates and
aircraft from the strike-plagued carrier.
   The agreement must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court
judge as part of Eastern's strike-recovery plan to restructure into
a smaller airline.
</TEXT>
