<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0821EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-France-CieIndustrielle-Suez     08-09 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Cie Industrielle-Suez,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suez Launches Largest Takeover Bid Ever In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compagnie Financiere de Suez says it is launching
France's biggest ever takeover bid, in a hostile offer for
Compagnie Industrielle, with which it shares control of Groupe
Victoire, a major French insurance group.
   The takeover proposal by Suez, a Paris-based holding company
which traces its history to the financing of the Suez Canal more
than a century ago, was said to be worth about $2.5 billion.
   Suez shares fell sharply in early trading today, reflecting
concern that the company is in for a long, tough battle that will
be costly even if it wins.
   The price dropped from 369 francs ($57.66) per share at
Tuesday's close to 347 francs ($54.22) just after today's opening,
but then rebounded to 355 francs ($55.47) at midday.
   Suez said Tuesday that if the bid is successful it will then
make a tender offer for Victoire's parent company, Compagnie
Financiere du Groupe Victoire.
   The Paris Stock Exchange said in a statement that Suez is
offering to pay 13,000 francs ($2,030) per share for the 81.53
percent of Compagnie Industrielle stock it does not already own.
   That would value the target company's total stock at 19.5
billion francs (about $3 billion) and the Suez offer would total
15.9 billion francs (about $2.5 billion).
   The previous record French takeover was a bid last year by
Schneider SA of about $930 million for control of Telemecanique
Electrique SA.
   But the success of the Suez bid is far from assured, with
Jean-Marc Vernes, president of Compagnie Industrielle, expected to
put up a tough resistance.
   ``Suez wants a majority, and I'm categorically opposed,'' Vernes
was quoted as saying in Wednesday's edition of the daily Le Figaro.
``I made proposals for an arrangement. But if we have to go to
battle, we will.''
   Last year, Suez won a bruising takeover battle with Italian
financier Carlo de Benedetti for control of the huge Belgian
holding company Societe Generale de Belgique.
   Groupe Victoire became much more attractive after making a
friendly acquisition last month of West Germany's second-largest
insurer, Colonia Versicherung AG. Suez said its bid would not
affect the Colonia takeover.
   Compagnie Industrielle's shares were last quoted on the Paris
Bourse at 9,750 francs ($1,525), before being suspended last Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
