<DOCNO> AP890809-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0852EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     08-09 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Traders Arraigned Plead Guilty to Fraud Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three commodities traders accused of cheating
their customers became the first to plead guilty in the federal
fraud investigation of the world's largest futures exchanges.
   Brothers Brian Sledz, 29, and James Sledz, 24, Tuesday pleaded
guilty to one count each of violating the Commodities Exchange Act.
The elder brother also pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud,
and the younger to one count of mail fraud.
   In addition, Thomas Braniff, 33, pleaded guilty to two counts of
violating the exchange act and two counts of mail fraud.
   The three men, yen traders at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
are among 46 traders indicted Aug. 2 in the FBI probe of the Merc
and the Chicago Board of Trade. Published reports have said as many
as 30 defendants are expected to plead guilty and cooperate with
authorities.
   After Tuesday's court hearings, defense lawyer Thomas Durkin
said the Sledz brothers aided federal investigators by agreeing to
wear recording devices to tape conversations of fellow traders.
   The Sledz brothers entered their pleas before U.S. District
Judge George M. Marovich. Additional defendants are scheduled for
arraignment Wednesday.
   James Sledz faces a maximum penalty of six years in prison and a
$350,000 fine, said the brothers' attorney, Barry Spevack. Brian
Sledz could be sentenced to 10 years in prison and be fined
$650,000.
   They have agreed to make restitution to customers, with the
amounts to be determined later, he said.
   The charges in last week's indictments range from pre-arranged
trading to racketeering conspiracy and tax fraud. Most allege
schemes in which traders pocketed part of the profit from trades
made for customers while passing their own losses on to customers.
   James Sledz's plea agreement said he executed pre-arranged
trades to make money for himself and his brother, and mailed
confirmation of the trades to customers in violation of exchange
rules, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Pollack said.
   Brian Sledz said he executed pre-arranged trades on behalf of
the Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. and Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
brokerage houses to make a profit for himself and his brother. He
confirmed the trades through wire communication, Spevack said.
   Both acknowledged engaging in ``numerous pre-arranged trades,''
the attorney said.
   Braniff said in his plea agreement that he conspired with trader
Michael Sidel in July 1987 to defraud one of his customers by
pre-arranging two trades for yen futures contracts. Sidel was
indicted last week on charges of mail and wire fraud and violating
the exchange act.
   Braniff also admitted to conspiring with an unidentified trader
on two transactions in September 1987.
   Braniff faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a
$500,000 fine.
   The Sledz brothers sold their trading seats at the Merc in
January when the first media reports of the undercover probe
appeared.
   The three were barred from the floor of the exchange in an
agreement last week with the Commodity Futures Trading Commission,
which oversees the exchanges, and still face disciplinary action,
said Merc spokesman Andrew Yemma.
   The brothers were released on $4,500 bond each pending
sentencing, which is to be scheduled when the remaining cases
against yen traders are resolved.
   A total of 21 traders were indicted for alleged illegal
activities in the yen pit. The remaining 25 defendants traded in
the Swiss franc pits at the Merc and the soybean and U.S. Treasury
bond pits at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   While Brian Sledz's plea agreement did not name other traders,
Spevack said, James Sledz named three indicted traders with whom he
engaged in pre-arranged trades _ Joseph O'Malley, Sam Cali and
Michael Smith.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
