<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0913EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChryslerDesign     08-09 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler Design,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Plans Simpler Designs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simpler car is in Chrysler Corp.'s
future as consumers find themselves overwhelmed by an array of
options and gadgets, the company's design chief says.
   Tom Gale, vice president for design at the nation's No. 3
automaker, said Tuesday that car buyers are overloaded with choices
to make when buying a car or truck.
   ``When you look at the marketplace of the future, where we have
the greatest opportunity is this whole field of back to basics,''
he said.
   However, he cautioned that cars can't look incomplete, like
basic cars of the past that had obvious places for clocks or
air-conditioning units.
   ``In a much larger sense, that's what we're struggling with on
how we handle the next generation of platforms,'' he said.
   Chrysler will be introducing a new basic design in late 1992 for
the 1993 model year. In Gale's world of designing for the future,
the cars that are built on those platforms are in the works today.
   ``When you get to a world where there are so many things, where
there is so much technology and there's so many models, different
models in different variations of those models, after a while, it's
a blur,'' Gale said.
   ``I think what the marketplace is telling us and what consumers
are telling us is `Hey, we're waiting for the guy who comes along
and just says, `Here's my Chrysler, here's my Dodge.'''
   During last winter's car-show circuit, Chrysler exhibited its
Dodge Viper concept car, a two-seater stripped of a lot of the
electronics that have made other cars more complex machines.
   Company Chairman Lee Iacocca has said a decision will be made on
whether to produce the Viper by early next year, and executives
have said Chrysler should build it.
   However, there is concern over whether it is economically wise
to build the car amid predictions of a continuing slowdown in car
and truck sales and a general softening of the U.S. economy.
   Two weeks ago, Chrysler's top 700 managers met in Detroit and
heard Iacocca outline a program aimed at taking $1 billion out of
the company's costs. Included will be a reduction in the
white-collar work force by about 2,300 people, or just more than 8
percent.
   Company executives said no plants would be closed and product
development plans would remain in place during the cost-cutting.
   Gale said his department wasn't exempt from the cost reductions.
</TEXT>
