<FIRST>r f PM-Dart-Chapter11     08-09 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dart-Chapter 11,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discount Drug Chain Files for Protection From Creditors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Drug Stores Inc., faced with high
debt payments and costs of extensive store renovations, has filed
for protection from creditors under the federal Bankruptcy Code.
   Company chairman Sheldon Fantle said the board of directors
concluded the company could not continue to make payments on its
debt _ much of which was incurred by prior owners who bought the
chain from founder Herbert Haft in 1984 for $160 million.
   ``Our board determined that it was far better to take this step
now, while our company has substantial resources to implement a
plan of reorganization.''
   ``This makes a lot of sense,'' said Kenneth M. Gassman Jr., an
analyst with Wheat, First Securities Inc., of Richmond.
``Emotionally it was hard for them to make that decision, but over
the long term (the company) will emerge much stronger because it
allows them to renegotiate its long-term debt.''
   Fantle led a group of investors that took over management of the
company in November 1987. At that time, Dart owed more than $164
million to bondholders and to its bank lenders. It has paid more
than $26 million in principal and interest payments on that debt.
   Dart operates 69 retail drug stores in Washington, D.C.,
Maryland and Virginia, and five Total-Plus discount stores in the
Richmond area. Dart has more than 2,000 employees and had sales of
about $170 million in the fiscal year ended in 1989.
   Its loss in the third quarter ended April 29 narrowed to $7.3
million from $9.6 million last year. Revenue in the first nine
months fell 26 percent, to $128.8 million from $174.9 million a
year ago.
   Haft founded Dart Drug Stores in 1954. He sold the company to a
management group in 1984 before going on to make a series of
unsuccessful corporate takeover attempts under the mantle of his
Dart Group Corp., which is unrelated to the drugstore chain.
   Fantle attempted to revamp the company by remodeling stores,
placing new emphasis on customer service, a financial restructuring
and an unusual plan to donate 5 percent of the company's gross
receipts to charity.
   The company filed a petition in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Rockville, Md., placing Dart and its subsidiaries under the
protection of the Bankruptcy Court while the company prepares a
plan of reorganization.
   Under the provisions of Chapter 11, the current management will
continue operating Dart Drug Stores under the supervision of the
Bankruptcy Court. While the day-to-day operations will be up to
management, major actions such as borrowing money would be subject
to approval of the court.
   In several motions Tuesday to the bankruptcy court, Dart sought
to arrange up to $30 million in new financing from the Mellon Bank,
of Pittsburgh, Pa. Those funds would allow the business to pay its
existing secured creditors and provide a revolving line of credit
for working capital.
   The company also said employees will be paid this Friday.
   Dart also wants to obtain approval to continue making payments
to charities under its Good Neighbor Fund program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoeingCracks     08-09 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Cracks,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Finds Crack in Fourth 727-100</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines has found a small crack in
a fourth Boeing 727-100 jetliner since the Federal Aviation
Administration ordered an industry-wide inspection in July.
   The FAA reported Tuesday that to date, cracks have been found in
the metallic skins of four United 727s and one American Airlines
727. The cracks ranged in size from 20 inches to less than half an
inch.
   Chicago-based United, the nation's second-largest airline,
previously reported finding cracks in three planes.
   The FAA is considering whether to order continuing inspections
of the 31 oldest 727s registered in the United States, said agency
spokesman David Duff. The inspections might also be broadened to
include somewhat newer 727-100s as well, he said.
   The cracks, first discovered on United jets, occur on the seam
that joins the upper and lower parts of the fuselage. Boeing Co.
modified the way the seam was joined after building the first 46
727s, increasing the thickness of the splice by inserting a spacer
piece of metal between the overlapping fuselage sections.
   ``We had never seen cracking along the lower rivet row (at the
splice),'' Duff said. ``This was something new.''
   Though the cracks' safety implication is not fully understood,
the FAA issued an emergency directive ordering airlines to inspect
the aging 727s for the fuselage cracks, and not to fly the planes
until they were inspected and any cracks repaired.
   The United and American planes have been repaired and are back
in service.
   Each of the planes had accumulated 46,000 to 49,000 flights.
Boeing had billed the planes as having a design life cycle of 20
years and 60,000 flights, said Tom Cole, a Boeing spokesman.
   Boeing still believes the planes can fly indefinitely with
proper maintenance, Cole said.
</TEXT>
