<HEAD>Corn Prices Lower, Soybeans and Wheat Marginally Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures were lower, but soybeans and wheat
prices moved marginally higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The dip in corn prices was attributed to the unusually high
estimate of crop production released Tuesday by influential private
forecaster Conrad Leslie.
   Although Leslie's forecast for soybeans was bearish as well,
most traders apparently thought a late wave of selling at Tuesday's
close was overdone and few sellers materialized after the opening
bell today.
   Price swings may be at a minimum over the next two days in all
the grain pits as traders adjust their positions in anticipation of
Thursday's U.S. Department of Agriculture report on actual crop
production.
   At the open, wheat was unchanged to 1\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.92} cents a bushel; corn
was \ cent to 1\ cents lower, with September at $2.24 a bushel;
oats were 1{ cents to 3 cents higher, with September at $1.39 a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 8 cents higher, with August at
$6.00{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly lower at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .27 cent lower to .07 cent higher, with August
at 74.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .08
