<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed firmer Wednesday in European
trading after retreating from the day's peaks.
   Gold prices were mixed in moderate trading.
   Dealers said the dollar rally which began after the release of
U.S. unemployment figures last Friday might have run out of steam.
   The dollar traded as high a 1.9050 West German marks, and closed
slightly lower at 1.9000. That compared to 1.8900 marks on Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 138.85 yen.
Later, in London, it rose to 139.13 yen.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.6170 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $1.6250 late
Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates late Wednesday in Europe compared with late
Tuesday's rates included: 1.6350 Swiss francs, up from 1.6270;
6.4050 French francs, up from 6.3995; 2.1440 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.1398; 1,364.40 Italian lire, up from 1,362.50; and 1.1710
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1720.
