<DOCNO> AP890809-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-France-CieIndustrielle     08-09 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Cie Industrielle,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Target Of Largest French Takeover Bid Promises Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compagnie Industrielle will resist the largest
takeover bid ever attempted in France, a $2.5 billion offer from a
former ally, its president said Wednesday.
   Jean-Marc Vernes, head of the holding company under attack from
Compagnie Financiere de Suez, a Paris-based bank holding company,
declined to discuss what allies he might be lining up for the fight.
   Suez won a long and difficult takeover battle last year with
Italian financier Carlo de Benedetti for control of the huge
Belgian holding company Societe Generale de Belgique.
   The prize in the takeover battle is Groupe Victoire, France's
second-biggest insurance group. Suez, which traces its corporate
history to the financing of the Suez Canal more than a century ago,
currently shares control of Groupe Victoire with Compagnie
Industrielle.
   The Paris Stock Exchange said in a statement that Suez proposes
to offer the equivalent of $2,030 per share for the 81.5 percent of
Compagnie Industrielle stock it does not already own. That would
value the target company's equity at $3 billion and the Suez offer
would total about $2.5 billion.
   Vernes was quoted by the French news agency Agence France-Presse
as saying he would make no statement until the hostile takeover bid
by Suez has been approved by stock market regulatory authorities.
   The regulatory decision is expected on Aug. 18, and if the bid
is approved, stockholders then would have a month to decide whether
to sell at that price.
   Trading in Compagnie Industrielle stock has been frozen since
Friday. It was last quoted on the Paris Bourse at the equivalent of
$1,525 per share.
   The price of Suez shares fell to $55.55 a share from $57.66 on
Wednesday in active trading.
   Groupe Victoire was originally part of the Suez holdings, but
when it appeared likely that the Socialists would win the 1981
elections, Suez's president at the time, Jack Frances, quietly
transferred control to the holding company Compagnie Industrielle,
which he controlled along with allies including the Dassault family.
   When the new Socialist government indeed nationalized Suez along
with other banks and industrial firms, it was surprised to find the
Groupe Victoire insurance company no longer a Suez subsidiary,
although Suez did retain a minority interest _ partly direct and
partly through Compagnie Industrielle.
   The conservative government elected in 1986 sold Suez to private
investors, but its new owners have had uneasy relations with
Vernes, who succeeded Frances as head of Compagnie Industrielle.
   Suez said if its takeover bid is successful, it will then make a
tender offer for the Victoire insurance company's parent, Compagnie
Financiere du Groupe Victoire.
   Suez already owns 30 percent of Groupe Victoire, but apparently
is unhappy as simply a silent investor. Suez also owns 18.47
percent of the shares of Compagnie Industrielle, which has 40
percent of the capital and 48 percent of the voting rights of
Compagnie Financiere du Groupe Victoire.
   Groupe Victoire became much more attractive after making a
friendly acquisition last month of West Germany's second-largest
insurer, Colonia Versicherung AG. Suez said its bid would not
affect the Colonia takeover.
   Suez said in a statement that its bid for Victoire was part of
its preparation for the dropping of barriers within the European
Economic Community after 1992.
   Reports in several French newspapers Wednesday said Vernes would
likely line up support from the Ferruzzi group of Italy to help
fight off the Suez takeover bid. Vernes is also president of
Beghin-Say, a French paper-making unit of Ferruzzi.
   Vernes declined to comment on the reports that Ferruzzi would be
involved.
   Under French stock market regulations, any competing bid for
Compagnie Industrielle, either by Vernes allies or others, would
have to be at least 5 percent higher than the Suez tender offer.
   The main asset of Compagnie Industrielle is its controlling
stake in Groupe Victoire. It also has some real estate and minority
industrial holdings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
