<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Guerrero Adv13 1stLd-Writethru 08-09 0934</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Guerrero, Adv 13, 1st Ld-Writethru,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Youth Takes Charge At Madrid Stock Exchange, Leads `El Big Bang'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix garble</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans know Pedro Guerrero as a $2
million-a-year slugger who can wallop a baseball, but in Spain's
financial world the name refers to someone known for a different
kind of big bang.
   That Pedro Guerrero is a lawyer, securities professional and son
of a Spanish banker. Last month he was elected chairman of the
Madrid Stock Exchange at age 36, making him the youngest person to
head a major securities market.
   More importantly, Guerrero has been presiding over a profound
reform in Spain's securities industry that's shattered the
160-year-old shackles of government control, a revolution known as
``El Big Bang.''
   It officially began July 29, when the state monopoly on
securities trading ended. Stock exchanges became private
businesses. Government-appointed stockbrokers were replaced by
private brokerages. After a transition period, once-fixed
commissions will be freely negotiatable.
   Like the ``Big Bang'' deregulation of the British markets a few
years ago, the Spanish securities overhaul is aimed at making stock
trading more competitive, efficient and attractive to foreigners
seeking opportunities in one of Europe's fastest-growing economies.
   ``The changeover has gone very well, although we've still got a
long road to run,'' Guerrero said in an interview. ``Many people,
especially in the business press, did not believe we would be ready
by the July 29 deadline, but we were.''
   He's not related to the Dominican-born Pedro Guerrero who bats
cleanup for the St. Louis Cardinals in the United States. But their
aggressiveness is strikingly similar.
   Guerrero's management of the El Big Bang changeover at Madrid's
stock exchange, where 70 percent of Spanish stocks are traded, has
overshadowed his conspicuous youth in a profession historically
dominated by rigid thinking and slow-moving brokers accustomed to
the life of government bureaucrats.
   ``He talks about selling products and services,'' said Jose
Manuel Nunez-Lagos, 67, a 38-year career stockbroker and president
of the Hispano brokerage. ``This is precisely the difference
between the old exchange and the new one.''
   Guerrero smokes heavily and wears modest clothes that belie his
wealth. He made a fortune channeling investment funds from foreign
markets into Spain through the Asesores Bursatiles brokerage, which
he helped found. In 1988, Asesores accounted for more than 5
percent of total volume on the Madrid exchange, 80 percent of that
from foreign investors.
   His youth stands in marked contrast to other world stock
exchange leaders. New York Stock Exchange Chairman John Phelan is
58, for example. American Stock Exchange Chairman Arthur Levitt is
58. Toronto Stock Exchange chairman Charles Caty is 48. Tokyo Stock
Exchange chairman Minoru Nagaoka is 65.
   Guerrero attributed his election by the revamped stock
exchange's 51 members partly to what he called an across-the-board
generational change in Spanish society.
   He mentioned Luis Carlos Croissier, 38, named president of the
National Securities Commission, the government agency that will
police the markets under the reform. Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez
is only 47, Guerrero noted.
   ``In other places where there has been a long, stable history
and much tradition, my election might not have been possible,''
Guerrero said. ``But I'm a firm believer in putting younger people
in important posts.''
   Guerrero said his priorities include revising the cumbersome
time-consuming system for finalizing stock trades and developing
the nation's first stock-options market. Options, widely traded by
speculators in the United States, are rights to buy or sell stocks
within a set time for a set price.
   He also intends to expand computerized trading, introduced in
April using a model of the Toronto Stock Exchange's Computer
Automated Trading System. The Spanish CATS network links the Madrid
exchange to smaller exchanges in Barcelona, Bilbao and Valencia.
   Guerrero said 22 percent of all trading is now done via CATS and
the figure should double by the end of the year, as the historical
open-outcry system of traders shouting bids gradually is phased out.
   His fast rise in Spain's securities industry reflects Guerrero's
own intense drive and ambition. He placed first seven years ago in
the tough state exams for his stockbroker's diploma. But he was
never completely satisfied just peddling stocks and looked for
other opportunities.
   In 1984, he and two friends visited financial institutions in
London to discuss their preparations for Britain's market
deregulation. That's where he got the idea for what became an
immensely successful business in Spain.
   ``They all wanted to hear about Spanish investment
possibilities,'' Guerrero said. ``They said if there was a firm in
Spain that could provide top-quality research and services, it
would get all the clients it could handle and more.''
   Guerrero and friends returned to Madrid and formed Asesores
Bursatiles. In 1985, the firm channeled about $350 million in
foreign investments into the Spanish markets. Last year they
handled $3.8 billion, mainly in foreign money, and have since
diversified the firm into other corporate financial services.
   Asked if he was concerned that Spain's market deregulation would
incite rampant greed and fraud, Guerrero said he believed the
government could still police the securities industry.
   ``I'm completely confident that the new National Securities
Commission is going to strongly discourage this and be very tough
on rule-breakers,'' he said.
   As an example, he mentioned the commission's recent probe of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s Spanish subsidiary. Even before any
formal action was taken, Drexel shut down the operation July 17
after determining it had improperly sold securities in a Spanish
oil company.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Aug. 13</NOTE>
