<FIRST>u f AM-Commodities-FeedGrains     08-09 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities-Feed Grains,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Chairman Defends Decision on Soybeans; Pledges `Clean House'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Commodities Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade will do whatever it
takes to restore confidence after 46 traders were indicted as a
result of a sweeping federal probe of trading fraud, the exchange
chairman pledged Wednesday.
   ``We do not tolerate a single customer being abused on our
exchange,'' board Chairman Karsten Mahlmann told the annual meeting
of the U.S. Feed Grains Council, which ended its three-day session
Wednesday.
   ``We want your confidence. We will do anything and everything to
keep it.''
   Mahlmann told council members the board has increased its audit
and investigation staff by 30 percent, and on Thursday will
consider a proposal to increase the penalty for each rule violation
to $250,000 from $75,000.
   ``That's how bad they want a clean house,'' he said of the
tougher policies, which followed last week's indictment of dozens
of traders at the Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Mahlmann also defended the Board of Trade decision to order the
sale of some July soybean contracts as ``a last resort'' to keep
the market operating smoothly.
   But farmer Jack Kintzle of Coggon, Iowa, said there still are
too many unanswered questions about the soybean sale, which
primarily affected an Italian processor, Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA.
   ``I think the the Ferruzzi deal is bothering the farmers in
gravel-road America even more than the indictments,'' Kintzle said.
   ``If they had left the market run, we'd have had $8 or $9 beans.
Farmers might not have sold but at least they would have had the
opportunity.''
   The Board of Trade move was widely interpreted as an effort to
break up an attempt to corner the market. Ferruzzi denied that was
its aim, saying it needed the beans for its crushing operation and
customers.
   The action forced Ferruzzi to give up nearly all of its July
contracts for the delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission already had taken steps
to cancel an exemption that allowed Ferruzzi to hold contracts for
more than the 3 million-bushel limit. The federal agency has said
there were contracts for delivery of about 40 million bushels of
soybeans and only about 12 million bushels available.
   Mahlmann said the Board of Trade preferred to apply its
liquidation order ``across the marketplace,'' to everyone with more
than 3 million bushels, whether they were buyers or sellers.
   The order required people to liquidate 20 percent of their
contracts each day, and to have contracts for no more than 1
million bushels of beans on July 20, he said.
   The CFTC plan would have forced Ferruzzi to liquidate contracts
for 20 million bushels in one day, Mahlmann said.
   ``That would have had long-lasting, devastating consequences on
the soybean complex,'' he said. ``I wouldn't have wanted to
speculate on where prices would have gone.''
   But farmer Steve Wentworth of Oreana, president of the National
Corn Growers Association, was uneasy about the move.
   ``I have some concerns that it affected the credibility of the
Board of Trade, and some farmers still have problems with that,''
he said.
   The U.S. Feed Grains Council, a private organization of farm and
agribusiness groups, was formed in 1960 to promote export markets
for U.S. corn, barley and sorghum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CitrusLand     08-09 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Citrus Land,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Price of Citrus Land Heating Up in Recovery from Freezes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of Florida citrus land is
rising, reflecting a general improvement in the agricultural
economy and a comeback from winter freezes, according to a new
survey.
   The value of mature South Florida orange groves was up 8.2
percent to $11,873 an acre, and Central Florida orange acreage rose
5.4 percent to $11,800 an acre in the survey period from November
1988 to May 1989.
   The survey, released this week by the University of Florida's
Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences, demonstrated the
confidence and optimism in the heart of the Florida citrus belt,
hard-hit by severe freezes in December 1983 and January 1985 that
killed nearly 200,000 acres of trees.
   ``We've seen prices bottom out and they're on the way back up,''
said John Jackson, citrus specialist with the Lake County
Agricultural Extension Service.
   Relatively mild weather has prevailed during the past four
winters and citrus planting has been active. About 125,000 acres
were planted statewide in 1986 and 1987, industry figures show.
   The value of an acre of mature grapefruit groves in central
Florida was placed at $10,265 an acre, a 5.5 percent jump from
November 1988. In South Florida, grapefruit groves were valued at
$10,420 an acre, a 2.7 percent increase.
   Part of the value of the farmland reflects its potential for
commercial development, said the authors of the report, University
of Florida agriculture professors John Gordon and John Reynolds and
visiting professor J.H. Atkinson.
   They said caution must be used in making year-to-year
comparisons from prior surveys.
</TEXT>
