<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-09 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Prices Lower, Soybeans and Wheat Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures were lower but soybeans and wheat
prices mostly higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Corn was under pressure at the opening bell because of the
unusually high crop production estimate released after the close of
business Tuesday by influential private forecaster Conrad Leslie.
   Although Leslie's forecast for soybeans was bearish as well,
most traders apparently felt that was discounted during the late
wave of selling at Tuesday's close.
   Wheat got its support from a small but steady stream of export
business, including rumors of a possible buy _ perhaps as much as
600,000 tons _ by Taiwan. Also supporting prices in the pit was the
hot, dry weather in growing areas of the United States, Europe and
the Soviet Union.
   Trading remained in a narrow range and is expected to do so
again Thursday as traders square their positions in anticipation of
the U.S. Department of Agriculture report on actual crop production.
   On the close, wheat was { cent to 3\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.94} a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 2 cents lower, with September at $2.22} a bushel; oats
were 1\ cents lower to { cent higher, with September at $1.36{ a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents lower to 5 cents higher, with August
at $5.90{ a bushel.

</TEXT>
