<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-EconomicGrowth     08-09 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Economic Growth,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Posts 1.1 Percent Growth in 1st Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC economy grew by 1.2 percent
during the first quarter of 1989, Eurostat, the statistics agency
of the 12-nation European Economic Copmmunity reported Wednesday.
   It said this was the highest quarterly rate since the third
quarter of 1987.
   By comparison, Eurostat said, the economies of the United States
and Japan _ the EEC's main trading partners _ rose by 1.1 and 2.2
percent respectively during the first quarter.
   Eurostat said the first three months of 1989 saw a 4.4 percent
jump in investments, the highest in four years and well above the 1
percent growth rate of the last quarter of 1988.
   EEC exports grew by 3.7 percent, up from 1.6 percent during the
previous quarter. Imports rose by 1.3 percent, down from 3.2
percent during the last three months of 1988.
   Eurostat said first-quarter growth in private consumption slowed
to 0.5 percent from 0.6 percent during 1988's fourth quarter.
   At 2.9 percent, West Germany posted the strongest economic
growth during the first quarter. It was followed by France (1.1
percent) and Italy, (0.7 percent), Eurostat said.
   The British economy was the weakest with a drop in output of 0.4
percent, Eurostat said.
</TEXT>
