<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1654EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     08-09 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woolworth's Quarterly Profit Rose 12 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woolworth Corp. Wednesday reported an 11.6
percent gain in second-quarter income, boosted by an 18 percent
rise in sales at its specialty stores.
   The newly formed holding company of the big retailer F.W.
Woolworth Co. said sales at its general merchandise stores grew a
smaller 1.2 percent in the quarter ended July 29.
   Woolworth's worldwide after-tax earnings rose to $48 million, or
74 cents a share, from $43 million, or 68 cents a share, in 1988's
second quarter.
   Revenue grew about 7 percent in the second quarter to $1.98
billion from $1.85 billion.
   Besides the Woolworth chain of general merchandise stores, F.W.
Woolworth owns strings of specialty retailers in the United States
and abroad. Its holdings include Foot Locker and Lady Foot Locker
athletic shoe shops as well as clothing and drug stores.
   For the first half of Woolworth's financial year, earnings came
to $84 million, or $1.30 a share, up about 7.7 percent from $78
million, or $1.22 a share, in 1988's first six months. Revenue
totaled $3.86 blilion, an 8 percent gain from $3.57 billion.
   The new corporate structure of Woolworth became effective Aug.
7. Woolworth has its headquarters in New York.
</TEXT>
