<FIRST>u f BC-CocaCola-Pernod 1stLd-Writethru   08-09 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coca Cola-Pernod, 1st Ld-Writethru,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Buys French Bottling Subsidiary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 2nd graf with different price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. said Wednesday it has completed the
acquisition of a bottling and distribution subsidiary of France's
Pernod-Ricard group, putting an end to a dispute that has soured
relations between the two beverage companies for almost two years.
   Coca-Cola said it has agreed to pay the equivalent of about $140
million for Societe Parisienne de Boissons Gazeuses (SPBG) and its
subsidiaries, which have bottled and distributed soft drinks in
France under license from Coca-Cola for the past 40 years.
   Pernod-Ricard put the price higher, at about $155 million. A
spokesman said the difference reflected a payment covering items
such as current contracts and goodwill.
   Coca-Cola's decision to take over its bottling and distribution
activities in France is part of a broader strategy of boosting
consumption of its products worldwide.
   The conflict between Pernod-Ricard and Coca-Cola arose when the
Atlanta-based company said it wanted to take over the French
operations, claiming that Pernod-Ricard was not trying hard enough
to market Coca-Cola products in France.
   Pernod-Ricard accused Coca Cola of breach of contract and took
the matter to court.
   SPBG's sales of Coca-Cola products last year totalled roughly
$220 million, or 42 percent of Pernod-Ricard's soft-drinks business
last year.
   Cyriac de Salaberry, a spokesman for Coca-Cola in Paris, said
the bulk of the purchase price reflects real-estate assets, mainly
bottling plants and storage depots.
   Apart from Coca-Cola, SPBG bottles and distributes Coca-Cola
soft drinks under the brand names Sprite, Fanta and Finley. By
acquiring SPBG, Coca-Cola now has control of more than 90 percent
of its products sold in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
