<DOCNO> AP890809-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NCNBTexas     08-09 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NCNB Texas,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Corp. Completes Buyout Of Texas Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. on Wednesday bought out the federal
government's 51 percent interest in NCNB Texas National Bank,
completing the $1.32 billion purchase of the institution created in
the nation's costliest bank failure.
   The buyout, announced 10 days ago, comes four years ahead of a
timetable established last year when NCNB was selected to manage
the 40 failed banks of First RepublicBank Corp.
   In that deal, Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB also got a five-year
option to buy all of Texas' largest bank holding company, which has
$27.9 billion in assets. NCNB changed the company's name to NCNB
Texas at that time.
   With the acquisition, NCNB becomes the nation's ninth-largest
commercial bank, with about $60 billion in assets and $43.2 billion
in deposits.
   NCNB paid $210 million for a 20 percent share of NCNB Texas on
Nov. 22, then accelerated its plans, paying $310 million for an
additional 29 percent on April 28 and $800 million for the
remaining shares Wednesday.
   The price gives a $270 million profit to the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., which provided $840 million of the initial
recapitalization of First RepublicBank. The FDIC also is financing
part of Wednesday's purchase through a $320 million in a one-year,
interest-bearing note.
   In all, the government has estimated the First RepublicBank
rescue will cost $3 billion.
   Improved profits at the Texas institution led to NCNB's decision
to move up its purchase, the bank said last month. NCNB Texas
earned $63.1 million in the second quarter, with $28.8 million
going to NCNB Corp.
   Analysts said the buyout also removes some potential roadblocks
to NCNB Texas acquiring other banks or thrifts as the state's
troubled financial industry is cleaned up.
   Since entering the Texas market, NCNB Corp. has sold $410
million worth of additional stock and seen its stock price climb to
over $54 a share, more than double its share price on July 29,
1988, when the FDIC announced the deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
