<SECOND>AM-GM-Janesville,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Production of Medium-Duty Trucks at Janesville GM Plant Delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production of General Motors Corp.'s new
generation of medium-duty trucks in Janesville has been delayed for
two weeks, the company announced Wednesday.
   The first vehicle had been scheduled to roll off the assembly
line next Monday, but production has been postponed until Aug. 28.
   Janesville's plant is scheduled to be the only GM plant making
medium-duty trucks. A plant in Pontiac, Mich., had made the trucks,
but GM announced the trucks would be made in Janesville after
autoworkers here agreed to a number of steps to increase the
plant's efficiency and lower its costs to make cars and trucks.
   Medium-duty trucks are larger than pickups but smaller than
over-the-road semitrailers.
