<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Anchor-Vitro     08-09 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anchor-Vitro,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tampa Company Target of Takeover by Mexican Corporation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of one of Mexico's largest
publicly held companies Wednesday announced a $280 million cash
offer for Anchor Glass Container Corp., mired in its second year of
losses after a rapid rise to become America's No. 2 glass maker.
   The subsidiary of Vitro SA has offered $20 a share for the
Tampa-based company. The Vitro subsidiary, THR Corp., and its
affiliates already own 1.43 million shares of Tampa-based Anchor,
or about 10.3 percent of shares outstanding.
   Stock in Anchor Glass shot up more than 60 percent Wednesday,
gaining $7.50 a share to close at $19.75 in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Ernesto Martens, chief executive officer of the Mexican glass
maker, said the takeover could erase financial difficulties at
Anchor.
   ``We believe that our financial, technological and management
resources can reverse what has been a significant decline in
Anchor's operating results and financial position,'' Martens said
in a letter to Vincent J. Naimoli, chairman and chief executive
officer of Anchor. ``We are prepared to make the substantial
capital expenditures required for Anchor's business to reverse this
decline.''
   Anchor has blamed its losses on restructuring costs and a
downturn in the glass container industry. In 1988, Anchor company
posted a loss of $8.5 million and closed two plants. So far this
year it has lost $14.4 million.
   This January, Anchor announced a 5 percent price increase on its
products due to higher raw material costs.
   Vitro's cash-tender offer expires at midnight Sept. 7.
   ``Right now the official word from the company is no comment,''
said Anchor spokeswoman Diane Villanova.
   Anchor manufactures glass containers for the brewing, food, soft
drink, distilled spirits and wine industries. In 1987, it acquired
competitor Diamond-Bathhurst Inc. for nearly $191.3 million.
   Corning Glass Works in Corning, N.Y., is the nation's largest
glass manufacturer, but does not specialize in bottles or
containers.
   Vitro, headquartered in Monterrey, manufactures glass and
plastic containers, flat glass, major appliances, tableware and
glass-making machinery. In 1988, the company earned over $150
million on revenues of almost $1.1 billion.
   It has about 8,000 shareholders and is one of Mexico's largest
employers, with more than 37,000 employees.
   Richard Palm, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in New York,
said the $20-per-share offer appears reasonable considering the
uncertainty in the glass container industry.
   ``Shipments of glass containers have been down seven of the last
eight years and they are only up this year modestly,'' said Palm.
   The Mexican company is also seeking to acquire Latchford Glass
Co., based in Huntington Park, Calif. The tender offer for Anchor
is not conditioned on the acquisition of Latchford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
