<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f AM-GasolinePrices Adv13   08-09 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gasoline Prices, Adv 13,0994</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Aug. 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Whatever Happened to the Summer '89 Gas Shortage?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brimming storage tanks of gasoline that should
be almost empty are teaching oil companies an old economics lesson
this summer: When prices rise, consumers buy less.
   The cost of gasoline, which soared 20 cents or more this spring
in the aftermath of the Exxon Valdez oil spill and widespread
predictions of shortages, has been stabilizing and even dropping in
some places because of a surprising oversupply at the height of the
driving season.
   ``Major oil companies expected people were more indifferent to
prices than they actually turned out to be,'' says William Veno,
director of oil market analysis for Data Resources Inc., an
economic research concern. ``They wouldn't have wanted to raise
prices so much as to undermine demand and they've tended to do
that.''
   Not only are motorists making fewer trips to the filling
station, they're also buying cheaper grades of gasoline, industry
statistics suggest. The result is that instead of shortages there
are surpluses, especially of high-priced high-octane premium.
   That doesn't mean demand couldn't pick up _ there's still a good
month's worth of summer vacation season left. More gasoline
consumption could alter the supply-demand equation and prices could
start rising.
   But as of late last month, the average retail price for all
types of gasoline had dropped to $1.13 a gallon from a peak $1.18 a
gallon on May 19, according to statistics from the Lundberg Survey
Inc., a research group that tracks gasoline prices nationwide.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics in Washington, which monitors the
inflation rate, estimates the average price per gallon for all
grades of motor fuel soared from 94.4 cents in January to $1.15 in
June, a 22 percent gain.
   High octane, which averaged about $1.09 in January, rose 19
cents to $1.28 a gallon in June. Unleaded regular, the most widely
consumed grade, rose from about 92 cents a gallon to $1.11.
   ``When prices of gasoline went up people bought less but more
important they started buying cheaper grades,'' says Dennis Eklof,
an energy specialist with the consulting group Cambridge Energy
Research Associates. ``When the customer switches and downgrades it
increases the overall supply in total.''
   Petroleum Intelligence Weekly, an industry trade publication,
reported recently that premium unleaded sales have fallen at least
10 percent because of motorists switching to regular unleaded.
   Wholesale prices are down even more sharply than retail, in some
cases below levels last seen two years ago. That could translate
into even lower retail prices in coming months.
   The New York price of wholesale regular unleaded, for example,
fell from 78 cents a gallon in late April to about 51 cents a
gallon earlier this month.
   Overestimates of summer driving and concern about supply
disruptions caused by the Exxon oil spill led refiners to make too
much gasoline, analysts say. ``What happened is that people altered
their plans,'' says Brent Crosby, executive director of the Service
Station Dealers of Arizona. ``So the big usage didn't materialize
and now we have a glut of refined product on the market. If the
price falls that much it has to be a tremendous oversupply.''
   Predictions of shortages arose from a number of other causes.
Tougher federal antipollution regulations, for example, require
refineries to use more crude in making gasoline. Refinery
accidents, maintenance delays, and lower production from Britain's
North Sea fields also played a role.
   But the biggest shot to the market psyche was the Exxon oil
spill.
   The March 24 disaster in Alaska jolted the market because the
cleanup temporarily disrupted the flow of crude to West Coast
refiners, raising the possibility of shortages. Refiners responded
by reducing sales to customers.
   Almost overnight, prices rocketed, with wholesale premium
gasoline up 30 cents in some parts of the country. In Los Angeles,
for example, regular unleaded surged to $1.07 on April 5 from 74
cents the day of the spill. The price shock quickly rippled through
the country.
   In the end, shipments from Alaska were disrupted for days
instead of weeks. About 13 million barrels of southbound crude was
delayed, in addition to the 250,000 barrels lost from the leaking
Exxon tanker.
   Moreover, refinery repairs and accidents had not caused other
delays anticipated earlier. Refinery capacity turned out to be
greater than expected and refiners were better prepared to handle
the new antipollution requirements.
   After the spill, crude oil prices stabilized in the
$19-$20-a-barrel range until last month, when they slid to about
$18 in response to the softening gasoline market and a surge in
summer production by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
   Refiners are just starting to slow production while the surplus
dwindles. But that means crude oil stockpiles are growing.
   ``It's a double-edged sword. If refiners don't cut back there's
too much product. If they do then there is too much crude,'' says
James R. Fiedler, energy analyst at E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc.
   Whether late-summer vacationers will reduce the oversupply of
gasoline remains unclear. The American Automobile Association,
which tracks summer driving, had predicted a 4 percent increase
this year over last but now says that growth is unlikely.
   ``It is fair to say that gasoline prices have had an impact on
gasoline consumption and driving habits as well,'' says Jerry
Cheske, spokesman for AAA. ``Whether people cancelled vacations I
don't think so. They're just more conservative in their driving
habits.''
   Some analysts believe consumers have sent a clear message to oil
companies.
   ``The lesson oil companies are learning is that you can't go and
raise prices by 20 percent and not expect something to happen,''
Veno says. ``It's a big lesson.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Aug. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
