<FIRST>u f AM-GtechBuyout 1stLd-Writethru   08-09 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gtech Buyout, 1st Ld-Writethru,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gtech Agrees to Sale for $290 Million to Management and Investor
Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with closing stock price, detail
uses of $290 million; picks up 5th graf, The company ...; SUBS 12th graf,
In early ..., to make both dates early May.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lottery giant Gtech Corp. announced
Wednesday it has agreed to a $290 million buyout by about a dozen
members of management and a unit of the investment firm Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   The price tag includes roughly $160 million for Gtech's stock
and $130 million for payment of fees, refinancing of Gtech's debts
and a contribution to working capital.
   The top managers, including Guy B. Snowden, the chairman and
chief executive, and Victor Markowicz, Gtech's vice chairman, will
retain their positions in the company, Snowden said.
   The purchase price was $16.62{ per share in cash. Gtech stock
rose 75 cents a share to $16 in over-the-counter trading on
Wednesday. The price had been inflated before the announcement by
speculation of a possible acquisition.
   The company has nearly 10 million shares outstanding.
   Gtech, a leading supplier worldwide of on-line computerized
lottery networks, currently serves 35 customers in the United
States and elsewhere, including Ireland, New Zealand, Mexico,
Spain, Venezuela, Iceland, Australia, Sweden, Singapore and Canada.
   If the recently approved sports betting in Oregon spreads to
other states, Gtech would be ``a major beneficiary from this
spread,'' since the sports betting would use the same machines as
the existing lotteries, said William Ritger, an analyst with
Dillon, Read &amp; Co. Inc.
   ``Gtech is going to continue on in the lottery business as is,''
Snowden said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``We are a leader
in the business and we aim to stay a leader.''
   The merger was approved by the Gtech board on Tuesday but
requires approval from Gtech shareholders at a meeting later this
year. Snowden said the meeting would be held in the fall but he
would not say precisely when.
   The company noted that the agreement depends on completion of
financing and on certain government approval and assurances from
some lottery authorities to continue Gtech's contracts.
   Rumors of a possible Gtech takeover surfaced last October,
prompting Snowden to issue a statement saying the company had an
``open-door policy'' and would consider offers.
   In early May, Gtech acknowledged that certain parties had
expressed an interest in acquiring the company. Also in May, the
company announced the establishment of a special committee to
evaluate possible business combinations. The committee consisted of
directors and financial advisors from Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. Inc., and
Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc.
   Snowden declined Wednesday to talk about the outside interest,
other than saying ``we were talking to a lot of people about a lot
of things.''
   Snowden said last year he felt an unfriendly takeover was
unlikely, since any disruption of the company's top management team
would wreck most of its contracts, in both logistical and legal
terms.
</TEXT>
