<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT to Wednesday sted Tuesday. Precedes LONDON
BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned narrowly mixed Wednesday
against key foreign currencies in sluggish trading.
   Gold prices were also mixed. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery rose to $366.90 a troy
ounce from $366.20 late Tuesday. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid for gold at $366 an ounce, up $1.70.
   Currency dealers said concerns of slow economic growth brought a
soft tone to the market.
   The Federal Reserve released its regular bank survey of economic
conditions, known as its ``beige book,'' on Wednesday, and that
showed the economy was still growing but at a slower pace.
   Dealers said the report indicated the central bank had room to
cut interest rates further, which could depress the value of the
U.S. currency.
   Earl I. Johnson, a dealer at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago,
said, ``There's really no motivation now to buy dollars until we
know clearly how soft the economy is.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 138.85 yen. It traded
at 139.13 yen in London, and at 138.945 yen in New York, up from
138.865.
   The dollar rose against the British pound in London. The pound
fell to $1.6170 from $1.6250 late Tuesday. Sterling fetched $1.6625
in New York, up from $1.6255.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.8935 West German marks, unchanged;
1.6315 Swiss francs, up from 1.6288; 1.17095 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.17195; 6.4000 French francs, down from 6.4040; and 1,361.50
Italian lire, up from 1,361.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Tuesday: 1.9000 West
German marks, up from 1.8900; 1.6350 Swiss francs, up from 1.6270;
6.4050 French francs, up from 6.3995; 2.1440 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.1398; 1.1710 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1720; and
1,364.40 Italian lire, up from 1,362.50.
   Gold traded at a bid price of $365.75 an ounce in London, up
from $365.45 late Tuesday. In Zurich gold closed at a bid price of
$365 an ounce, down from $365.85.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.40 to close at a bid $365.88
an ounce.
   Silver prices headed lower. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery fell to $5.155 a troy ounce from $5.156.
Silver was bid at $5.15 an ounce in London, down 1 cent.
</TEXT>
