<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-09 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Prices Lower, Soybeans, Wheat Climb Before USDA Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures were lower, but soybeans and wheat prices finished
higher Wednesday as traders hewed to narrow ranges in advance of a
much-anticipated U.S. Department of Agriculture survey of crop
production for the year.
   On other markets, sugar futures surged on rumors that India was
in the market for as many as 300,000 tons; heating oil led a modest
run-up in the petroleum futures complex; and frozen pork belly
prices continued sliding in the face of historically high
inventories.
   Corn came under pressure with the opening bell at the Chicago
Board of Trade because of the unusually high crop production
estimate _ 7.72 billion bushels _ released after the close of
trading Tuesday by influential private forecaster Conrad Leslie.
   Although Leslie's forecast for soybeans was high as well _ 1.95
billion bushels _ most traders apparently felt that was discounted
during the late wave of selling Tuesday that dragged November
soybeans to yet another contract low.
   Traders tested the contract low at $5.62 again early Wednesday.
After support held above that mark, many traders squared up their
positions and headed to the sidelines to await Thursday's
government report.
   ``The confusion between Leslie's numbers and what the traders
were looking for pulled the market the past two days,'' said Jerry
Gidel, research director for LIT America Inc., Chicago. ``I think
people were happy just to even up and wait and see what the
official numbers look like.''
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 5 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.95 a bushel; corn was { cent to 2 cents
lower, with September at $2.23 a bushel; oats were 1\ cents lower
to unchanged, with September at $1.36 a bushel; soybeans were 1{
cents to 9 cents higher, with August at $5.94 a bushel.
   Rumors of a big purchase by India, which some traders speculated
may already have taken place, pushed sugar futures prices above 14
cents a pound at mid-session.
   ``That number has psychological value and it got some people
excited enough to jump on the bandwagon,'' said Arthur Stevenson of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., New York. ``Sugar supplies have
been tight for a while and a report of somebody coming in and
taking that much out of the market was bound to spur a rally.''
   Late profit-taking helped trim the gains, however, and sugar
finished .05 cent to .26 cent higher on the New York Coffee, Sugar
and Cocoa Exchange, with October at 14.07 cents.
   An American Petroleum Institute report released after Tuesday's
trading showed a substantial drawdown in heating oil supplies last
month and that lifted the entire complex.
   Crude oil was 9 cents to 14 cents higher at the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with September at $18.21 a barrel; heating oil
was .66 cent to .96 cent higher, with September at 49.43 cents a
gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .14 cent to .40 cent higher, with
September at 50.58 cents a gallon.
   Livestock futures were mostly lower, while pork futures were
sharply lower at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .35 cent lower to .27 cent higher, with August
at 74.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .33
cent higher, with August at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .33
cent to 1.23 cents lower, with August at 46.77 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to 1.13 cents higher, with August
at 24.92 cents a pound.
   Precious metals were mixed.
   Gold prices climbed 10 cents to 70 cents on the Comex, with
August at $366.90 a troy ounce; silver slipped 1 cent to 3 cents,
with August at 515.5 cents. Platinum, traded on the New York Merc,
was $1 to $1.80 lower, with September at $484.70 a troy ounce.
