<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1807EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Paramount     08-09 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paramount,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Stock Advances in Active Trading on Takeover Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Paramount Communications Inc. stock
rose in active trading Wednesday on speculation that the company
that launched an unsuccessful $12.2 billion bid for Time Inc. was
itself a takeover target.
   Paramount rose $2.50 to $62.12{ a share and was the second most
actively traded issue on the New York Stock Exchange as more than
4.1 million of its shares changed hands. Paramount stock rose
$2.62{ a share on Tuesday.
   Paramount, the one-time conglomerate that has been selling
assets outside its entertainment and publishing businesses under
Chairman Martin Davis, said it ``does not comment on market
activity, rumors or speculation.''
   Jeffrey Logdson, who follows Paramount for the investment firm
Crowell Weedon &amp; Co. in Los Angeles, said the activity in
Paramount's stock reflected the ``swirl of rumors'' about possible
suitors for the company.
   Among those mentioned have been Chris-Craft Industries Inc. _ a
media concern that is a major shareholder in Warner Communications
Inc. _ and an investor group led by Charles Dolan, head of
Cablevision Systems Corp., a Long Island, N.Y.-based cable
television company.
   Columnist Dan Dorfman said in Wednesday's edition of USA Today
that a group of investors led by Dolan had acquired a stake in
Paramount and may seek control.
   Dolan was said to be out of the country and unavailable for
comment. Cablevision spokesman David Carey said, ``It is our policy
neither to confirm nor deny any speculation about a possible
acquisition.''
   Two calls placed to Chris-Craft were not returned.
   Paramount recently tried but failed with an eleventh-hour
hostile bid for Time, which had earlier agreed to a merger with
Warner.
   Paramount offered $10.7 billion for Time and later raised its
offer to $12.2 billion, but Time deflected the bid by insisting it
was not for sale and amending its stock-swap merger with Warner
into a $14 billion Warner buyout.
   Paramount failed to win a fight in the Delaware state courts to
block the Time-Warner merger and dropped its bid July 24.
   Late last month, Paramount said it had agreed to sell its
consumer and commercial finance unit, The Associates Corp., for
$3.35 billion to Ford Motor Co.
   But some analysts said the sale of the unit that accounted for
46 percent of Paramount's operating income in 1988, coupled with an
expected infusion of cash, could make Paramount more attractive to
bidders.
</TEXT>
