<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-09 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose Wednesday on news that
refineries pumped less gasoline last week.
   West Texas Intermediate for September delivery rose 9 cents on
the New York Mercantile Exchange and finished at $18.21 a barrel.
WTI sets the standard in the U.S. industry for light, sweet crude
oil.
   Contracts for later delivery of WTI posted slightly higher gains.
   Domestic heating oil traded on the exchange showed the biggest
gains. The contract for September rose 0.87 cent to 49.43 cents a
gallon while October rose 0.92 cent to 50.16 cents.
   September unleaded gasoline finished 0.14 cent higher at 50.58
cents a gallon while other contracts also advanced.
   Statistics from the American Petroleum Institute showed that
crude oil runs at refineries fell by 500,000 barrels last week,
while distillate, or heating oil, runs declined by 100,000 barrels.
   The figures suggest that refineries, which have operated at the
highest levels in a decade, slowed their output of gasoline and
heating oil.
   Energy analysts said that those statistics helped offset what
could have been a negative impact from the same API report, which
showed that supplies of crude oil, gasoline and heating oil in
storage all rose during the same week ended Aug. 4.
   Gasoline prices have softened in recent weeks as supply exceeded
demand and inventories increased.
   Crude prices also have weakened recently due to the surge in
summer output by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
and sluggish demand.
   Analysts said the new API data might lead investors to believe
that market fundamentals are improving.
   ``It's too early to say if this is the beginning of a sustained
rally,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker for E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc. ``It could be that traders will be
looking ahead to heating oil season.''
</TEXT>
