<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BallyRefinancing     08-09 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bally Refinancing,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casino Commission Approves $350 Million Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bally Manufacturing Corp. can
begin a $350 million debt refinancing to be paid for largely
through its Park Place Casino in Atlantic City, state regulators
ruled Wednesday.
   The Casino Control Commission rejected arguments from state
gaming officials that the refinancing would put Park Place, one of
Atlantic City's leading gaming halls, on shaky financial footing.
   ``I find that this is a responsible proposal which will not
jeopardize Park Place's financial stability or its ability to
maintain a first-class facility,'' commission chairman Walter N.
Read said.
   Bally Manufacturing, the casino's Chicago-based parent company,
wants to make Park Place more independent. The refinancing plan
includes offering $350 million in mortgage notes to fund a $150
million dividend payment to Bally and retire existing corporate
debt.
   The casino would incur the $350 million debt. About $120 million
would be used by the parent firm to retire debt unrelated to
Atlantic City ventures.
   Read admitted the proposal would increase Park Place's debt
without an equal benefit to the casino.
   But he said he is ``satisfied that the proposed transaction is
responsible and is not a plan to siphon funds from a healthy
facility and leave it in a weakened state. Nor does it mark the
beginning of a withdrawal by (Bally) from the New Jersey gaming
market.''
   Read said Bally has invested more than $600 million in Park
Place while receiving just $43 million in dividends and plans to
spend $213 million more on capital improvements.
   Dissenting commissioner W. David Waters and state Division of
Gaming Enforcement officials argued that the casino will have
problems paying off the debt despite promises by Bally officials.
   Waters said the plan ``merely reshuffles financing to Bally
Manufacturing.''
   ``It in no way benefits the Park Place,'' he said. ``The
facility is basically self-financing. Its future ability to be
self-financing is inhibited.''
   Bally attorney Clive Cummis said the restructuring plan would
begin soon, but he was not more specific.
</TEXT>
