<DOCNO> AP890809-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1836EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Brazil-Debt     08-09 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Debt,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Denies Moratorium On Interest Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega said
Wednesday the nation's foreign creditors have agreed to a delay in
debt payments and he denied Brazil will enter a moratorium.
   Da Nobrega told the congressional Finance Commission that the
government wanted to avoid a confrontation with creditors and
wished to ``negotiate lateness'' until the country's foreign
reserves reached a ``respectable level.''
   In July, the government restricted the outflow of dollars by
channeling all foreign exchange operations through the Central
Bank, equivalent to the U.S. Federal Reserve.
   Since then, Brazil's cash reserves have risen nearly $1 billion
to $6.5 billion, surpassing the minimum level considered safe by
the government, which is $6 billion, equivalent to four months of
imports.
   But the government continues to hold back about $1 billion in
debt payments since June 30, including $400 million to Western
government leaders due July 3 and some $600 million in interest
payments and dividend remittances by foreign multinationals, da
Nobrega said.
   That falls short of a moratorium, which would be a total halt to
payments on foreign debt.
   Da Nobrega said the government needed the reserves to avoid
shocks from abroad and insure a smooth transition of government
during the coming months.
   On Nov. 15, Brazilians will elect President Jose Sarney's
successor in the nation's first people's vote in 29 years. The
winner will take office on Mar. 15, 1990.
   Brazil, tottering under a $112 billion foreign debt, the Third
World's largest, is also seeking fresh money to meet an interest
payment of $3 billion due in September to private foreign banks.
   The government is negotiating an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund that would allow Brazil to receive $4
billion in fresh loans withheld by private banks and lending
organizations.
   Creditors have balked at lending more money to Brazil, which has
not controlled an annual inflation rate of 1,000 percent, monetary
expansion and a soaring public defecit.
   Brazil's public deficit, running at around 7 percent of GNP this
year, is one of the principal generators of inflation.
</TEXT>
