<HEAD>Retirees Sue GM Over Health-Care Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of retired General Motors Corp. salaried
employees has sued the automaker, claiming GM broke health-care
promises and owes them money they shouldn't have had to pay.
   The group of 114 retired employees said in the suit filed in a
Los Angeles federal court Tuesday that GM cut their health-care
coverage after promising them the items would be covered.
   The suit, filed as a class action on behalf of more than 80,000
retired GM salaried workers, most of whom live in Michigan,
Florida, California and Ohio, seeks reinstatement of the cut
benefits and reimbursement of out-of-pocket expenses they have
spent.
   GM spokeswoman Patricia Malloy said company officials had no
comment on the suit since they haven't had time to study it.
   Malloy said all salaried GM workers should have known their
health care benefits could change. She said changes were made to
encourage active and retired employees to switch to more economical
health care plans, such as health maintenance organizations.
   Last year, the company eliminated or reduced some coverage for
the retirees, including chiropractic and psychiatric care, and
imposed copayments and deductibles on basic health coverage.
   ``GM said we would have these benefits for our lifetimes,'' said
Leonard Moeller of Fenton, Mich., an accountant who retired in
1982. ``I felt we had a moral our
