newspaper Granma as saying the three were of ``known
counterrevolutionary affiliation'' and ``carried out a campaign of
slander'' in statements to U.S. television and ``the anti-Cuban
radio sponsored by Washington,'' a reference to the U.S.
government's Radio Marti.
   Neither news agency said how or when the three talked to U.S.
news media.
   The three allegedly told foreign news media that Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa had been drugged by authorities before he appeared in
court, Prensa Latina said.
