<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe 1stLd-Writethru f0178 08-09 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0178,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twelve Traders Plead Innocent in Commodities Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 12 traders pleading innocent,
details; Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Published reports ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve traders in the Japanese yen pit at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges
stemming from the federal probe of trading practices at the world's
largest futures markets.
   The 12 were among 46 traders named a week ago in the first
indictments resulting from the undercover investigation. Charges
ranged from pre-arranged trading to racketeering conspiracy and tax
fraud, most alleging schemes in which traders pocketed profits from
trades made for customers while passing their own losses on to
customers.
   U.S. District Judge George M. Marovich set Aug. 16 as the next
hearing date for the 12 traders. The judge said he would set a
trial date at that time.
   Five of the traders _ John M. Baker, 50, Sam A. Cali, 38, Thomas
A. Crouch, 43, Ray Pace, 33, and Michael D. Smith, 34 _ pleaded
innocent to charges of violating the Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations Act, as well as to multiple counts of mail
and wire fraud.
   The remaining seven traders pleaded innocent to charges of mail
and wire fraud.
   Published reports have said that as many as 30 defendants are
expected to plead guilty and cooperate with authorities.
   Three of the 21 traders indicted at the yen pit at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange pleaded guilty Tuesday. The remaining 25
defendants traded in the Swiss franc pits at the Merc, and in the
soybean and U.S. Treasury bond pits at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The indictments were handed up Aug. 2. In the FBI probe, agents
posed as traders on the floors of the two exchanges and
tape-recorded illegal transactions.
   More indictments are expected this fall as a result of the
continuing investigation.
   The first traders to be arraigned in the case pleaded guilty
Tuesday to fraud and Commodities Exchange Act violations.
   As part of their plea agreements, Thomas Braniff, Brian Sledz
and his brother, James Sledz, admitted to making pre-arranged
trades among themselves and other indicted traders.
   They have agreed to make restitution to customers, and face
prison terms and stiff fines from the government and the Merc. All
have been banned from the exchange.
</TEXT>
