<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-McCaw 1stLd-Writethru f0280 08-09 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-McCaw, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0280,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts Wider Loss in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `LIN said ...,' to CORRECT expiration of offer,
which has been extended.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the
nation's largest cellular telephone company, said Wednesday its
second-quarter loss widened to $87.5 million from $61.7 million a
year ago.
   But Chairman and Chief Executive Craig McCaw said the losses
``are consistent with company expectations since many of our
cellular markets remain in their start-up phase.''
   Costs for acquisitions, construction, interest, marketing and
depreciation are expected to remain high as the company builds its
cellular operations, McCaw said. However, he said operating margins
are improving as the number of cellular subscribers grows.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 64.3 percent to $120.1 million from
$73.1 million a year earlier.
   McCaw has made a hostile tender offer for LIN Broadcasting
Corp., a New York-based cellular telephone, television broadcasting
and publishing company. McCaw has offered $110 a share for the 90.2
percent of LIN's stock it doesn't already own, or about $5.4
billion.
   LIN says the offer, which McCaw has extended until Sept. 1, is
inadequate.
   For the first six months of 1989, McCaw lost $185.2 million on
revenue of $222.2 million in contrast to losses of $123.1 million
on revenue of $141.1 million for the same period of 1988.
   McCaw provides cellular telephone service in a number of major
markets, including Miami, Pittsburgh, Minneapolis, Kansas City,
Mo., Denver, Portland, Ore., and Seattle. It said the number of
cellular subscribers in its markets and in markets where it has the
right to buy a controlling interest increased by 30 percent to
336,000 as of June 30, from 258,000 at the end of 1988.
</TEXT>
