<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TradeDeficit 1stLd-Writethru f0265 08-09 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Deficit, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0265,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Economists Say Budget Cuts Will Aid Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The congressional ...,' to RESTORE dropped letter
``b'' in the word ``billion.'' ^Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slashing the federal budget deficit would
dramatically improve the nation's $129 billion annual trade
imbalance, congressional fiscal experts said Wednesday.
   The non-partisan Congressional Budget Office said that by
meeting the deficit targets mandated by the Gramm-Rudman law _
which requires a balanced federal budget by 1993 _ the country's
trade shortfall could be cut by $40 billion to $65 billion.
   Many economists agree that reducing federal red ink would help
the trade imbalance. But by producing its 77-page report, which
relies on simulations to make its arguments, CBO provided more
ammunition to members of Congress pressing for a fiscal 1991 budget
deal with the White House that would entail major deficit cuts.
   The congressional agency estimated that eventually, every $1
billion cut in the federal deficit would improve the nation's trade
picture by $300 million to $500 million.
   The CBO also said that expanding the money supply would have
little effect on the U.S. trade deficit, since exchange rates are
flexible.
   ``Among the options policymakers have for reducing the U.S.
current account deficit, reducing the federal budget deficit ... is
the most promising,'' the CBO said.
   The current account deficit is the broadest measure of the trade
deficit, registering not only products but services as well. The
U.S. current account deficit reached $132 billion last year and is
expected to be about $129 billion this year. At the beginning of
this decade, the United States had a slight surplus in trade.
   To pay for the extra goods and services entering this country,
the United States must borrow money from abroad.
   ``In the long run, this borrowing will transfer wealth abroad
and this will reduce living standards of Americans in the future,''
CBO Director Robert D. Reischauer said at a news conference.
   Economists disagree over how threatening the trade imbalance is.
Some say it bodes ill because it could trigger protectionist
legislation and recession, while others argue it means little.
   But they mostly agree that cutting the federal deficit would
ease the trade shortfall by lowering the need to borrow from
abroad, reducing interest rates, allowing the dollar to decline and
thus making American products more attractive to foreign buyers.
   The budget deficit for fiscal 1989 _ which ends Sept. 30 _ is
expected to be about $148 billion. The Gramm-Rudman law's deficit
ceiling for next year is $100 billion, and Congress will resume its
efforts to reach that target when it returns from its summer recess
in September.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said the
CBO conclusions ``emphasize the urgency of agreeing upon a bold
deficit reduction package for fiscal year 1991 as soon as
possible.''
</TEXT>
