<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2338EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-HarrisRestructuring     08-09 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Harris Restructuring,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harris Corp. Announces Plans to Sell Data, Computer Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harris Corp. is seeking buyers for its
data communications and personal computer divisions after an $85.2
million restructuring intended to streamline operations, the
defense and aerospace contractor said Wednesday.
   The company, which began to scale down in the mid 1980s, is now
organized into four major sectors: electronics, semiconductors,
communications and Lanier Worldwide Inc., the new name of its
Harris-3M international division.
   ``The businesses we are selling are outside the mainstream of
our future interests, and their sale will release assets and other
resources for ... our core businesses,'' said John Hartley,
chairman and chief executive officer, in a press release.
   The release did not name a price for the two divisions or
whether any companies have expressed interest in them.
   The restructuring cost dropped net income for the year ended
June 30 nearly 80 percent, while sales and per-share profit rose.
   For the 12 months ended June 30, the Melbourne-based company
reported net income of $21.3 million, or 55 cents a share, on sales
of $2.2 billion, compared with net income of $100.5 million, or
$2.50 a share, on sales of $1.8 billion for the previous fiscal
year.
   In the fourth quarter, the restructuring costs led to a net loss
of $52 million on sales of $768.3 million, compared with net income
of $1.8 million, or 5 cents a share, on sales of $471.8 million in
the year-ago period.
   In June, Harris pleaded no contest to filing inflated statements
on behalf of a Filipino businessman convicted of defrauding the
Defense Department. Harris agreed to pay $200,000 in fines and
$300,000 to settle civil claims against it arising from a Justice
Department investigation of fraud involving weapons sales to the
Philippines.
</TEXT>
