<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Phillips-Pickens     08-09 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Phillips-Pickens,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Vacates Favorable Pickens Ruling In Phillips Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday set aside
a decision clearing corporate raider T. Boone Pickens' investment
group of violating securities and racketeering laws in a takeover
bid for Phillips Petroleum Co. five years ago.
   A three-judge panel of the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
vacated a lower court's summary judgment in favor of Pickens' Mesa
Partnership and sent the case back to U.S. District Court in
Delaware.
   The lawsuits brought by Phillips shareholders accused Mesa of
deception in its $9.1 billion attempt to take over the
Bartelsville, Okla., oil giant.
   William Wade, an attorney for Mesa, said from Wilmington, Del.,
that he had not seen the decision and would not comment.
   The court ruled a jury could reasonably conclude that Mesa,
which made $89 million on the takeover attempt, had always intended
to sell its Phillips stock back to the company for a better deal
than the other stockholders received. Such a tactic is known as
``greenmail.''
   During the takeover attempt, Pickens repeatedly said Mesa would
not consider selling back its shares unless the same deal was
offered to all stockholders.
   The partnership changed its stance when Phillips adopted a
``poison pill'' strategy to fight the takeover.
   The appeals court said the district court incorrectly cited a
lack of evidence.
   Although much of the evidence was circumstantial, Circuit Judge
Anthony J. Scirica wrote, no other type normally is available in
bad-faith cases.
   ``A jury could reasonably conclude that the partnership either
was reckless in making the equal-basis statements given the
forseeability of what actually occurred or that the partnership
intended from the outset of its tender offer to sell back to
Phillips on an unequal basis,'' Scirica wrote.
   The appeals panel upheld the summary judgment involving all
Delaware state charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
